column2: Description
Fluorouracil (5-FU) is a chemotherapy medication used to treat a variety of cancers. It works by inhibiting the synthesis of DNA.

5-HTP is a naturally occurring amino acid and chemical precursor to the neurotransmitter serotonin. 5-HTP is used as a dietary supplement to promote serotonin production and balance serotonin levels in the brain.
The definition of absorption is the process of taking in or soaking up something, such as light or sound.
The acai berry is a small, dark purple fruit that grows on acai palm trees in the rainforests of Central and South America. The acai berry has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties.

ACE inhibitors are a class of drugs used to treat high blood pressure, heart failure, and other cardiovascular conditions. They work by blocking the action of ACE, a substance in the body that promotes the constriction of blood vessels.

Acebutolol is a beta blocker that is used to treat high blood pressure and other heart conditions. It works by blocking the action of certain chemicals in the body that can cause the heart to beat too fast or irregularly.
Acetaminophen is a pain reliever and a fever reducer.
Acetazolamide is a medication used to treat glaucoma, epilepsy, and altitude sickness. It is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor, which means it works by preventing the body from producing carbonic acid.
Acetyl CoA is a molecule that is produced when glucose is broken down in the body. It is used in the production of energy in the body.
Acetylcholine is a neurotransmitter that is involved in the transmission of nerve impulses.
Acidophilus is a type of bacteria that is found in the digestive system. It is important for keeping the digestive system healthy and preventing the growth of harmful bacteria.
Acne is a skin condition that causes pimples or blackheads.
Acorn squash is a type of winter squash that is shaped like an acorn. It has a dark green or orange skin and a sweet, nutty flavor.
Activated charcoal is a type of carbon that has been treated with oxygen to open up millions of tiny pores between the carbon atoms.
Actos is a medication used to treat type 2 diabetes. It works by helping the body to better use insulin.
Acupressure is a form of alternative medicine that uses physical pressure on specific points on the body to relieve pain.
Acupuncture is a form of alternative medicine in which thin needles are inserted into the body. It is a key component of traditional Chinese medicine.
Acute diarrhea is a sudden, severe case of diarrhea that lasts for a short time.
Adderall is a central nervous system stimulant medication used to treat attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and narcolepsy.
This Addiction health condition is characterized by a strong and persistent urge to use a substance, despite its harmful effects.
Adenocard is a brand name for the medication adenosine. It is a prescription medication used to treat certain types of irregular heart rhythms.

Adenosine is a nucleoside that is composed of a nitrogenous base (adenine) and a sugar (ribose). It is found in RNA and is involved in many cellular processes, including energy transfer and signal transduction.
The adrenal gland is a small, triangular-shaped gland that is located on top of each kidney. The adrenal gland produces hormones that are essential for life, such as adrenaline and cortisol.
Adrenaline is a hormone that is released in response to stress. It increases heart rate and blood pressure, and it also increases the availability of glucose and oxygen to the muscles.
A person who is fully grown or developed

Generally speaking, however, adult men are typically considered to be those who have reached the age of majority (18 years old in most jurisdictions) and are therefore considered to be legally responsible for their actions. In some cases, the term may also be used to refer to males who are physically mature enough to be considered adults, even if they are not yet legally considered as such.
The definition of adulthood is the state or quality of being an adult.
The definition of advice is a suggestion or recommendation for a course of action.
Advil is a brand name for the drug ibuprofen. It is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) used to relieve pain, fever, and inflammation.

Aerobic exercise is any type of physical activity that uses large muscle groups and causes your body to use more oxygen than it would while resting. The goal of aerobic exercise is to increase your cardiovascular fitness.
Age acceleration is the process of becoming older faster than usual. This can be due to a variety of factors, including stress, illness, and poor lifestyle choices.
Agenerase is an enzyme that is used to treat HIV infection. It is a protease inhibitor that works by blocking the activity of protease, an enzyme that is needed for the HIV virus to multiply.
The definition of aging is the process of becoming older.

Aging skin is a health condition characterized by the thinning and weakening of the skin. The skin becomes less elastic and more susceptible to damage. The production of collagen and elastin, two proteins that help keep the skin firm and elastic, decreases with age. The skin also becomes drier and less able to protect itself from the sun.
The definition of agitation is a state of excitement or nervousness.
The definition of aggression is the use of force or violence to harm someone or something.

Some people might say that AI is a branch of computer science dealing with the creation of intelligent agents, while others might say that AI is a set of techniques used to create or simulate intelligent behavior.

AIDS is a debilitating and often deadly disease caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). HIV attacks the body's immune system, making the person infected susceptible to other infections and illnesses, which can lead to AIDS.
The definition of air pollution is the presence of harmful chemicals or particulates in the air that can cause harm to humans, animals, and plants.

Alpha-linolenic acid (ALA) is an omega-3 fatty acid found in plants. It is considered an essential fatty acid because the body cannot make it on its own. ALA is converted into eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), which are found in fish oil. EPA and DHA are responsible for the health benefits associated with omega-3 fatty acids.
The National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA) defines alcohol as a central nervous system depressant that is consumed by drinking beer, wine, or distilled spirits.
Alcohol dependence is a chronic, relapsing brain disease characterized by compulsive alcohol seeking and use, despite harmful consequences.
Alendronate is a medication used to treat osteoporosis and Paget's disease of the bone. It works by preventing the breakdown of bone and increasing bone density.
The definition of alertness is the state of being watchful and attentive.

Alfalfa is a perennial flowering plant in the pea family Fabaceae. It is cultivated as an important forage crop in many countries around the world. The name alfalfa is used in North America, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Spain. The plant is also known as lucerne in the United Kingdom, France, Germany, Portugal, Italy, Scandinavia, East Asia, South Asia and in other parts of the world.  Alfalfa is a highly nutritious forage crop that is used as feed for livestock. The leaves and stems are rich in protein, vitamins and minerals. Alfalfa is also a good source of fiber. The plant is very drought tolerant and can be grown in a wide range of climates.  Alfalfa is a perennial plant that can grow to a height of 3 feet (1 meter). The leaves are green and the flowers are purple. The plant blooms in the summer and fall. Alfalfa is native to the Mediterranean region but it is now grown in many parts of the world.
Aliskiren is a direct renin inhibitor. It works by blocking the action of renin, a substance in the body that is involved in the regulation of blood pressure.
Alkylating agents are a class of chemotherapy drugs that work by binding to DNA and preventing it from being able to replicate.
Allegra is a brand name for the medication fexofenadine, which is used to treat allergies.

An allergic reaction is a response of the body to a foreign substance, called an allergen, that is perceived as a threat. The body's response is to release chemicals, such as histamine, that cause the symptoms of an allergy.

Allergic rhinitis is a condition in which the person has an allergy to something in their environment, such as pollen, dust, or animal dander. This can cause symptoms such as sneezing, a runny nose, and itchy, watery eyes.
Alli is a weight loss supplement that is designed to help people lose weight by preventing the absorption of fat from the food they eat.

Allulose is a type of sugar that is found in some fruits and vegetables. It is about 70% as sweet as table sugar, but it does not have the same effect on blood sugar levels. Allulose is absorbed more slowly than other types of sugar, so it does not cause a spike in blood sugar levels.

The almond is a species of tree native to the Middle East, the Indian subcontinent and North Africa. Almonds are also the name of the edible and widely cultivated seed of this tree. Within the genus Prunus, it is classified with the peach in the subgenus Amygdalus, distinguished from the other subgenera by corrugations on the shell (endocarp) surrounding the seed.

The Aloe plant is a succulent plant that is native to Africa. It has long, fleshy leaves that are green in color and have serrated edges. The leaves of the Aloe plant are used to make a variety of products, including Aloe vera gel, which is used for its medicinal properties.
Alopecia areata is a condition that causes hair loss. The hair may fall out in patches or all over the scalp.
The Alpha-4-beta-2 receptor is a subtype of nicotinic acetylcholine receptor that is widely distributed in the brain.

Alpha-GPC is a cholinergic compound that is used for its cognitive-promoting effects, and is also a precursor to the neurotransmitter acetylcholine. It is commonly used as a nootropic supplement to improve memory and cognitive function.
Alpha-lipoic acid is a fatty acid that is found in every cell in the body. It is needed for the proper function of enzymes that are involved in energy production.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord. Motor neurons reach from the brain to the spinal cord and from the spinal cord to the muscles throughout the body. The progressive degeneration of the motor neurons in ALS eventually leads to their death. When the motor neurons die, the ability of the brain to initiate and control muscle movement is lost. With voluntary muscle action progressively affected, patients in the later stages of the disease may become totally paralyzed.

Some people define alternate-day fasting as consuming no calories or very few calories (usually less than 500 calories) on one day, followed by eating normally the next day. Others define it as fasting for 24 hours followed by eating normally for 24 hours.

Altitude sickness is a condition that can occur when you travel to high altitudes, usually 8,000 feet (2,438 meters) or more above sea level. It most often occurs when people travel quickly from lower altitudes to higher altitudes, such as when they travel from sea level to high mountains.
Altoprev is a brand name for the prescription medication lodoz, which is used to treat high blood pressure and heart failure.

A chemical element with the symbol Al and atomic number 13. It is a silvery-white, soft, nonmagnetic, ductile metal in the boron group. By mass, aluminium makes up about 8% of the Earth's crust; it is the third most abundant element after oxygen and silicon and the most abundant metal in the crust, though it is less common in the mantle below. The chief ore of aluminium is bauxite.
Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, degenerative disease of the brain that is characterized by loss of memory and deterioration of other cognitive functions.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a health condition that affects a person's vision. It is the leading cause of blindness in people over the age of 50. AMD occurs when the macula, the part of the eye that allows us to see fine details, deteriorates. This can lead to a loss of central vision.

This American ginseng plant (Panax quinquefolius) is a perennial herb that grows in the eastern United States and Canada. It has dark green, deeply lobed leaves and small, greenish-white flowers. The plant produces a small, red fruit that contains seeds. Ginseng roots are used in traditional Chinese medicine and are also sold as a dietary supplement.

American trypanosomiasis, also known as Chagas disease, is a parasitic infection caused by the protozoan Trypanosoma cruzi. The infection is typically spread by contact with the feces of infected triatomine bugs, and can also be spread through blood transfusions, organ transplants, and from mother to child during pregnancy. Symptoms of Chagas disease can be mild, and may not appear for years after infection. However, the disease can also be severe, and can lead to heart failure, gastrointestinal problems, and death.
Amiloride is a potassium-sparing diuretic that is used to treat high blood pressure and congestive heart failure. It works by preventing the body from absorbing too much salt and potassium.
Amino acids are the building blocks of proteins.
Amiodarone is a medication used to treat irregular heartbeats. It is in a class of drugs called antiarrhythmics.
Amlodipine is a medication used to treat high blood pressure and chest pain. It is in a class of drugs called calcium channel blockers.

Amphetamine is a central nervous system stimulant that is used to treat attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and narcolepsy. It is also used as an athletic performance enhancer and cognitive enhancer, and recreationally as an aphrodisiac and euphoriant.
AMPK is an enzyme that is activated by adenosine monophosphate (AMP). AMPK plays a role in regulating energy balance in cells by promoting glucose uptake and fatty acid oxidation.
Amprenavir is a protease inhibitor used to treat HIV infection.

The amygdala is a small, almond-shaped structure located deep within the brain's medial temporal lobe. It is considered to be part of the limbic system, which is a group of brain structures that are involved in emotion and memory.

Anaerobic training is a type of exercise that is performed at a high intensity for a short period of time. This type of training requires the body to use energy from stored sources, such as glycogen, rather than from oxygen.
Anafranil is a tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) that is used to treat depression and anxiety disorders. It is thought to work by increasing the levels of serotonin and norepinephrine in the brain.
Anaphylaxis is a severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction.
The study of the structure and relationships of the body's organs and tissues
Ancestors are the people in your family who lived before you.

Androgen receptors are a type of protein found in the cells of the body that bind to androgens (hormones that stimulate or control the development and maintenance of male characteristics) and mediate their effects.
Androgens are hormones that promote the development and maintenance of male characteristics.
Andrographis paniculata is an annual herb that grows to a height of 2-3 feet. The leaves are lanceolate, and the flowers are white or pale blue. The fruits are small, black, and spherical.
Anemia is a health condition in which there is a decrease in the number of red blood cells or hemoglobin in the blood. This can cause fatigue, pale skin, and shortness of breath.
Anemia of chronic disease is a health condition in which the body does not produce enough red blood cells. This can lead to fatigue, shortness of breath, and other symptoms.

Angina is a type of chest pain that occurs when the blood flow to the heart muscle is reduced. This can happen due to blockages in the coronary arteries, which supply blood to the heart. Angina can be a symptom of coronary heart disease, which is the leading cause of death in the United States.
Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors are a class of drugs used to treat hypertension, heart failure, and myocardial infarction.
Anorexia nervosa is an eating disorder that is characterized by an intense fear of gaining weight, self-starvation, and excessive weight loss.
column22: Obsessive focus on weight and body shape

column2: Ansaid is a brand name for the prescription drug flurbiprofen, which is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID).

Antabuse is a medication that is used to treat alcoholism. It works by causing unpleasant side effects when alcohol is consumed, such as nausea and vomiting. This helps to discourage people from drinking.
Antacids are a class of drugs used to treat conditions caused by excess stomach acid, such as heartburn, ulcers, and gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).

Anthocyanins are a type of flavonoid, which are plant pigments that have been shown to have health benefits. They are found in a variety of fruits and vegetables, and give them their red, purple, or blue color. Anthocyanins have been shown to have antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anticancer properties.
An anthracycline is a type of chemotherapy medication that is used to treat cancer.
The definition of anti-aging is the process of slowing down or reversing the effects of aging.
The definition of anti-cancer is a substance that helps to prevent or treat cancer.
The definition of antibacterial is a substance that kills bacteria or inhibits their growth.
Antibiotics are drugs that are used to treat infections caused by bacteria.
Anticholinergic drugs are drugs that block the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
Anticoagulants are drugs that prevent the formation of blood clots.
A medication used to treat depression.
Antifeedants are substances that deter animals from eating plants.
Antifungals are drugs that are used to treat fungal infections.
The definition of antihyperglycemic is a medication that is used to treat high blood sugar levels.
An antioxidant is a molecule that inhibits the oxidation of other molecules.
Antitumor antibiotics are drugs that are used to treat cancer.

Apha-GPC is a nootropic supplement that has been shown to improve cognitive function and memory. It is thought to work by increasing levels of acetylcholine, a neurotransmitter that is important for learning and memory.
Apigenin is a plant compound that is found in a variety of fruits and vegetables. It has a variety of health benefits, including reducing inflammation and protecting against cancer.

The APOE-4 gene is a gene that codes for a protein called apolipoprotein E. This protein is involved in the metabolism of cholesterol and other lipids. People who have two copies of the APOE-4 gene (one from each parent) are at increased risk for developing Alzheimer's disease.
An app is a software application designed to run on a mobile device, such as a smartphone or tablet.
The definition of appetite is a natural desire to satisfy a bodily need, especially for food.
A fruit that is round, red, and has a green stem.
Apple juice is a type of fruit juice made by extracting the juice from apples.

Angiotensin II receptor blockers (ARBs) are a class of medications used to treat high blood pressure. ARBs work by blocking the action of angiotensin II, a hormone that causes blood vessels to narrow. This helps to relax the blood vessels and lower blood pressure.

The Arnica plant is a perennial herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It has yellow or orange flowers and grows to a height of about two feet. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers have five petals. Arnica is used in herbal medicine to treat bruises, swelling, and pain.
Aromatase is an enzyme that is responsible for the conversion of androgens into estrogens.
Aromatase inhibitors are drugs that block the action of the enzyme aromatase. Aromatase is responsible for converting androgens into estrogens.

This Ashwagandha plant is an evergreen shrub that can grow up to 1.5 meters tall. It has long, thin leaves and small white flowers. The roots of the plant are thick and fleshy, and they are used in traditional medicine. Ashwagandha is native to India and Sri Lanka, and it has been used in Ayurvedic medicine for centuries.
Asian ginseng is a plant that is native to China and Korea. It is used in traditional Chinese medicine to treat a variety of conditions.

Asparagus is a vegetable that is part of the lily family. It is a perennial plant that grows in many parts of the world and has been cultivated for centuries. The asparagus plant has long, thin, green stems and small, green flowers. The edible part of the plant is the young shoot, which is harvested in the spring.
Asthma is a chronic lung condition that causes wheezing, coughing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath. Asthma can be triggered by environmental factors such as pollen, dust, smoke, or cold air.
Atazanavir is a prescription medication used to treat HIV infection. It belongs to a class of drugs called protease inhibitors.
The definition of attention is the ability to focus on a particular stimulus.
Auditory learning is a type of learning that occurs when someone hears and remembers information.
Autoimmunity is a health condition in which the body's immune system attacks and destroys healthy body tissue.
Autonomic arousal is the activation of the autonomic nervous system in response to a stimulus. This can be either a positive or negative response, depending on the nature of the stimulus.
Autophagy is the process by which cells break down and recycle their own components.
The avocado is a tree that is native to Mexico and Central America. The fruit of the avocado tree is green and pear-shaped. Avocados are a good source of vitamins C, E, and K.

Ayurvedic medicine is a system of medicine with historical roots in the Indian subcontinent. Globalized and modernized practices derived from Ayurveda traditions are a type of complementary or alternative medicine.
B. lactis is a species of lactic acid bacteria that is commonly used in the production of cheese and yogurt. It is also a common probiotic, meaning it is beneficial for gut health.

Bacillus coagulans is a species of Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacteria. It is a member of the genus Bacillus, which also includes the well-known pathogen Bacillus anthracis. B. coagulans is a mesophilic bacterium, meaning it grows best at moderate temperatures. It is found in soil, water, and air. This bacterium is known for its ability to produce lactic acid, which gives it a sour taste. It is also used as a probiotic, meaning it is beneficial for human health.
A bagel is a type of bread that is round with a hole in the middle. It is boiled before it is baked, which gives it a chewy texture. Bagels are often eaten with cream cheese or lox (smoked salmon).
The definition of balance is the distribution of weight or matter evenly between the two sides of something.
A banana is a sweet, yellow fruit that is often eaten as a snack.
This barley plant has long, slender leaves that are a deep green in color. The plant produces small, pale green flowers that grow in clusters. The flowers are followed by small, dark brown seeds.

A beta blocker is a type of medication that is used to treat a variety of conditions, including high blood pressure, heart failure, and migraines. Beta blockers work by blocking the effects of the hormone epinephrine, which can help to improve blood flow and reduce the heart rate.
A beta-adrenergic agonist is a drug that stimulates the beta-adrenergic receptors. These drugs are used to treat a variety of conditions, including asthma, COPD, and heart failure.
Beta-alanine is an amino acid that is used by the body to synthesize carnosine, a molecule that helps to regulate acidity levels in muscles and improve exercise performance.
A pigment found in plants that is a precursor to vitamin A.

Beta-endorphins are endogenous opioid peptides that are produced by the pituitary gland and the hypothalamus in the brain. They are released in response to stress and pain, and they act on the opioid receptors in the brain to produce analgesia and a sense of well-being.
The betel nut is the seed of the Areca catechu tree. It is often chewed with betel leaves as a stimulant.
BHB is a ketone body that is produced by the liver during periods of fasting or carbohydrate restriction. It is used by the body for energy production, and is a substrate for ketogenesis.

Bifidobacterium animalis subsp. lactis is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the phylum Firmicutes. It is a commensal organism that is often found in the gastrointestinal tract of mammals, including humans. B. animalis subsp. lactis is a producer of lactic acid, and it has been shown to have probiotic properties.

Bilberry is a small, round, dark blue fruit that is related to the blueberry. Bilberries are native to Europe and Asia and have been used for centuries in traditional medicine. Bilberries contain high levels of antioxidants and are thought to be beneficial for a variety of health conditions, including diabetes, eye health, and cancer.
Biltricide is a medication used to treat parasitic infections.

Binaural beats are auditory illusions perceived when two different pure-tone sine waves, both with frequencies lower than 1500 Hz, with less than a 40 Hz difference between them, are presented to a listener dichotically (one through each ear).
A binding protein is a type of protein that is involved in binding other molecules.

Binge eating is an eating disorder in which a person consumes large amounts of food in a short period of time, often to the point of feeling uncomfortably full. Binge eating disorder is different from overeating or bulimia, which are also characterized by excessive eating.

Binge eating disorder is a health condition characterized by episodes of overeating or bingeing. This may be followed by feelings of guilt, shame, or embarrassment. Binge eating disorder is a serious health condition that can lead to obesity and other health problems.
The bioavailability of a drug is a measure of the extent to which the drug is absorbed and available for use by the body.
The study of the chemical processes in living organisms
Biodiversity is the variety of life on Earth.

Biofeedback is a technique that uses sensors to measure a person's physiological activity, such as heart rate, skin conductance, or muscle tension, and then provides feedback to the person about their physiological activity. The goal of biofeedback is to help the person learn to control their physiological activity.
Bioidentical hormones are hormones that are identical in structure and function to the hormones produced by the human body.
The biological age of a person is the age of the person's body.
Biology is the study of living things.
A biomarker is a measurable indicator of the severity or presence of a disease.
Biosynthesis is the production of organic compounds by living organisms.

Biotin is a water-soluble vitamin that is part of the vitamin B complex. It is also known as vitamin H or coenzyme R. Biotin plays an important role in the metabolism of carbohydrates, fats, and proteins. It is also involved in the synthesis of DNA and RNA.

Biotin deficiency is a health condition that can occur when there is not enough biotin in the body. Biotin is a water-soluble vitamin that is found in many foods, such as eggs, milk, meat, and nuts. It is also available as a supplement. Biotin deficiency can cause hair loss, skin rashes, and brittle nails.

Bipolar disorder is a mental illness that causes people to experience extreme changes in mood. People with bipolar disorder may swing from feeling very happy and energized to feeling very sad and hopeless, and then back again. These mood swings can last for days, weeks, or even months.
The definition of birth is the act or process of bringing forth a child from the womb.

Birth control pills are a type of contraception that is taken orally by women. The pills contain hormones that prevent ovulation and thicken the mucus in the cervix, making it difficult for sperm to reach the egg.
A birth defect is a physical or mental abnormality that is present at birth.

Ajwain, also known as carom seeds or bishop's weed, are the small, oval, ridged seeds of a plant in the parsley family. The seeds have a strong, pungent flavor and aroma that is reminiscent of thyme, anise, and fennel. Ajwain is used as a spice in Indian and Middle Eastern cuisine. It is often used to flavor breads, curries, and vegetables.

Bisphenol A (BPA) is a synthetic compound that is used in the production of certain plastics and resins. BPA is known to leach into food and beverages from containers made with these materials, and has been linked to a variety of health concerns.
Bisphosphonates are a class of drugs that are used to treat osteoporosis and other bone diseases. They work by preventing the breakdown of bone and increasing bone density.
Bitter melon is a tropical fruit that is often used in Asian cuisine. The fruit has a bitter taste and is used in dishes such as stir-fries and curries.
Bitter orange is a citrus fruit that is high in acidity. It is used as a flavoring agent in many foods and beverages.

Black beans are a type of legume that is often used in Latin American cuisine. They are small, round, and black in color. Black beans are high in fiber and protein, and they have a mild, nutty flavor.

This Black cohosh plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to 3 feet tall. The leaves are large and lobed, and the flowers are small and white. The plant prefers shady, moist conditions and is native to North America.

The black haw is a small to medium sized deciduous shrub that is native to North America. It typically grows to between 6 and 12 feet tall, with a spread of 4 to 8 feet. The leaves are ovate to elliptical in shape and are dark green in color. The flowers are small and white, and appear in clusters in the spring. The fruit is a small, dark blue berry that ripens in the summer.
This black pepper plant is a climbing vine that produces small, dark berries. The berries are dried and used as a spice. Black pepper is native to India and is widely used in Indian cuisine.

The black psyllium plant is a small, annual herb that is native to the Mediterranean region. It has black seeds that are used to make a laxative powder. The powder is made by grinding the seeds into a fine powder and then mixing it with water.
Black salves are typically herbal or plant-based ointments or salves that are used topically for a variety of purposes, including to draw out toxins, infections, or splinters from the skin.
The black seed is the seed of the Nigella sativa plant, which is native to southwest Asia. The seeds are used in traditional medicine as a remedy for a variety of ailments.
Black tea is a type of tea that is more oxidized than other types of tea, such as green tea, white tea, or oolong tea.
The black-eyed pea, also called the black-eyed bean, is a legume native to West Africa. It is a subspecies of the cowpea and is sometimes simply called a cowpea.
Bladder cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the bladder. The bladder is a hollow organ in the lower abdomen that stores urine.

Bladder control problems are a common health condition that can affect people of all ages. The most common symptom of bladder control problems is leakage of urine. Other symptoms can include urinary frequency, urgency, and incontinence.
This is a condition where there is bleeding from the blood vessels in the skin. It can be caused by a number of things, including injury, medications, or certain health conditions.
This is a bleeding disorder that is caused by a deficiency of a certain protein in the blood. This protein is responsible for clotting the blood.

Cirsium vulgare, commonly known as blessed thistle, holy thistle or spotted thistle, is a biennial plant in the Asteraceae family. The plant is native to Europe, but has been introduced to other parts of the world, including North America. The plant grows to a height of 1-2 m (3-6 ft) and has dark green, deeply lobed leaves. The flowers are yellow with purple spots, and are borne in heads. The plant flowers from July to September.  The leaves and flowers of blessed thistle are used in herbal medicine. The plant is said to have a number of medicinal properties, including the ability to stimulate appetite, aid digestion and relieve gas. Blessed thistle is also used as a tonic and diuretic.
The definition of blind is someone who cannot see.
Blindness is the inability to see.
Blonanserin is a medication that is used to treat schizophrenia. It is an atypical antipsychotic that works by blocking dopamine and serotonin receptors in the brain.

This Blond psyllium plant (Plantago ovata) is an annual herb that is native to Iran and Pakistan. It grows to a height of 20-30 cm and has small, white flowers. The plant has a taproot and produces a seed that is enclosed in a hard, brown shell. The plant is cultivated for its seeds, which are used in traditional medicine and as a dietary supplement.
The definition of blood is a fluid that circulates in the arteries and veins of vertebrates, carrying oxygen and nutrients to the tissues and carbon dioxide and other wastes away from them.
A blood clot is a solid or semisolid mass formed from blood components.
The movement of blood through the body.
The blood glucose level is the amount of glucose in the blood.
A blood infection is a serious infection that occurs when bacteria or other organisms enter the bloodstream. Blood infections can lead to sepsis, a potentially life-threatening condition.
The force of the blood against the walls of the arteries.
The blood sugar, or glucose, is the sugar that is found in the blood. It is the main source of energy for the body's cells.
A blood test is a laboratory analysis performed on a blood sample that is usually extracted from a vein in the arm using a needle, or obtained from a finger prick.
The blood vessels are the tubes that carry blood around the body.
The blood-brain barrier is a semipermeable barrier that protects the brain from harmful substances in the blood.
Bloodwork is a medical term for a blood test.
The blue crab is a species of crab found in the western Atlantic Ocean, the Chesapeake Bay, and the Gulf of Mexico.
Blue light is a type of light with a blue color.
Blue-green algae are a type of bacteria that can live in both fresh and salt water. They are often found in ponds and lakes.

This blueberry plant is a deciduous shrub that typically grows to 6-10’ tall with a rounded to vase-shaped habit. It is native to eastern North America where it typically occurs in woodlands, swamps, bogs and along streams. It features simple, ovate to elliptic, dark green leaves (to 3” long) that turn yellow to red in fall. Tiny, urn-shaped, white flowers in clusters (corymbs) bloom in late spring, with each flower giving way to a small, round, blue-black berry. Fruits are edible, but somewhat tart.
The body is the physical structure of an organism. It is composed of cells, tissues, and organs that work together to perform the functions of the organism.
Body temperature is the temperature of the human body.
Bodybuilding is the use of progressive resistance exercise to control and develop one's musculature. An individual who engages in this activity is referred to as a bodybuilder.
Boiled milk is milk that has been heated to a temperature of at least 180 degrees Fahrenheit, causing the milk to turn a light brown color.

The stress system is the body's response to any demand placed upon it. The stress system is designed to help the body cope with physical, emotional, or psychological challenges. When the body is placed under stress, the stress system is activated. The stress system includes the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis and the sympathetic nervous system (SNS). The HPA axis is responsible for the body's response to stress. The SNS is responsible for the body's fight-or-flight response.
The stress threshold is the point at which the body can no longer cope with the demands being placed on it and begins to break down.
A stressful situation is any situation in which a person feels overwhelmed or unable to cope. Stressful situations can be caused by a variety of factors, including work, relationships, and finances.
Stressors are any physical, chemical, or biological agents that can cause stress.

Strontium is a chemical element with the symbol Sr and atomic number 38. An alkaline earth metal, strontium is a soft silver-white or yellowish metallic element that is highly reactive chemically. The metal turns yellow when it oxidizes in air.

Sun exposure is the amount of time a person is exposed to sunlight.

Thunder god vine is used in traditional Chinese medicine.

The thyroid is a butterfly-shaped gland that sits low on the front of the neck. The thyroid’s job is to make thyroid hormones, which are secreted into the blood and then carried to every tissue in the body. The thyroid is a butterfly-shaped gland in the front of the neck. It is one of the endocrine glands, which make hormones. The thyroid gland makes two main hormones: thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3). These hormones help to control the body's metabolism.

Toll-like receptor 4 is a protein that in humans is encoded by the TLR4 gene. TLR4 is a member of the toll-like receptor (TLR) family, which plays a fundamental role in pathogen recognition and activation of innate immunity. TLRs are highly conserved from Drosophila to humans and share structural and functional similarities. They recognize pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) that are expressed on infectious agents, and mediate the production of cytokines necessary for the development of effective immunity. The various TLRs exhibit different patterns of expression. This receptor is most abundantly expressed in placenta, followed by liver, kidney, and small intestine. It is also expressed at low levels in many other tissues, including thymus, spleen, lung, and peripheral blood leukocytes.

Toll-like receptors (TLRs) are a class of proteins that play a key role in the innate immune system. TLRs are receptors that recognize specific molecular patterns on pathogens, which leads to the activation of the immune response. TLRs are found on the surface of cells and are able to bind to pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs), which are molecules that are found on the surface of pathogens. TLRs are able to recognize a wide variety of PAMPs, which allows them to play a key role in the innate immune response to a variety of different pathogens.

TMD may vary slightly depending on the source. However, TMD generally refers to a group of conditions that affect the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) and the muscles that control jaw movement. TMD can cause pain and dysfunction in the jaw and surrounding facial tissues.

The Acerola plant is a small, deciduous tree that is native to tropical America. It has a short trunk and a dense, round crown. The leaves are simple, opposite, and ovate-shaped. They are dark green in color and have a glossy surface. The flowers are white or pink and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, red berry that is rich in vitamin C.

Acetaminophen poisoning is a condition that can occur when someone takes too much of the medication acetaminophen. Acetaminophen is a pain reliever and fever reducer that is available over the counter. When someone takes too much acetaminophen, it can cause liver damage. Symptoms of acetaminophen poisoning include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and confusion. If left untreated, acetaminophen poisoning can lead to liver failure and death.

Acetyl-L-carnitine is an amino acid that is produced naturally in the body. It plays a role in energy production and is involved in the transport of fatty acids into the mitochondria, where they are used for energy production.
Acidic diets are those that contain high levels of acid-forming foods, such as meat, dairy, and processed grains. These diets can lead to health problems, such as osteoporosis and kidney stones.
The ackee is a fruit that is native to West Africa. The fruit is yellow or red when ripe and has a large seed inside. The flesh of the fruit is soft and white.

This plant is a member of the buttercup family and is native to Europe, Asia and North America. It is a perennial herb with a rhizomatous root system and erect, branching stem that can grow up to 3 m tall. The leaves are palmate, deeply lobed and 20-30 cm long. The flowers are borne in racemose inflorescences and are bisexual, with 5 petals and 5 sepals. The petals are blue or purple, while the sepals are greenish-white. The fruit is a follicle that splits open at maturity to release the seeds.  This plant is poisonous and should not be ingested.

Acrodermatitis enteropathica is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the skin and intestines. People with this condition are unable to absorb zinc from the food they eat. This can lead to a zinc deficiency, which can cause a number of problems, including skin rashes, diarrhea, and hair loss.

Actinic keratoses are small, rough, scaly patches on the skin that develop from long-term sun exposure. They most often form on the face, lips, ears, back of the hands, and forearms, and can range in color from skin-toned to reddish-brown. While actinic keratoses are not cancerous, they can become cancerous over time.
Actinium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Ac and atomic number 89.

Active hexose correlated compound (AHCC) is a compound derived from mushrooms that is used as a dietary supplement. AHCC is claimed to boost the immune system, although there is no scientific evidence to support this claim.
Acute back pain is a health condition characterized by a sudden, sharp pain in the lower back. The pain is often the result of an injury, such as a muscle strain, and typically lasts for a few days.
Acute bronchitis is a condition in which the airways in your lungs become inflamed. This can lead to a cough, shortness of breath, and chest pain.
The Acute Coronary Syndrome (ACS) is a health condition that is characterized by a sudden and severe narrowing of the coronary arteries. This narrowing can lead to a heart attack.

Acute kidney injury (AKI) is a sudden episode of kidney failure or kidney damage that happens within a few hours or days. AKI causes a build-up of waste products in your blood and makes your kidneys unable to keep up with fluid removal. AKI can also cause other problems such as low blood pressure, anemia, and weak bones.

Acute liver failure is a sudden and severe deterioration of liver function that can lead to death. The liver is a vital organ that helps the body to process food, rid itself of toxins, and produce important nutrients. When it fails, the body cannot function properly. Acute liver failure can be caused by a variety of factors, including viral infections, certain medications, and liver disease. Treatment typically involves hospitalization and aggressive supportive care.

Acute mountain sickness (AMS) is a condition that can occur when you travel to high altitudes, usually 8,000 feet (2,438 meters) or higher. It causes a range of symptoms, including headache, nausea, vomiting, fatigue, and difficulty sleeping. In severe cases, it can lead to fluid in the lungs (high-altitude pulmonary edema) or fluid in the brain (high-altitude cerebral edema).

The Acute Radiation Syndrome (ARS) is a health condition that results from exposure to high levels of ionizing radiation. Symptoms of ARS include skin burns, hair loss, vomiting, diarrhea, and internal bleeding. ARS can be fatal if left untreated.

ARDS is a severe lung condition that occurs when the lungs are unable to provide enough oxygen to the body. The condition can be caused by a variety of factors, including pneumonia, sepsis, and trauma. ARDS can lead to respiratory failure and death.
Acute viral hepatitis is a viral infection that causes the liver to become inflamed. The most common types of viral hepatitis are hepatitis A, B, and C.
Adaptogens are a class of herbs that help the body adapt to stress by normalizing physiological processes.

Addison disease is a rare disorder that occurs when your body produces insufficient amounts of certain hormones. It primarily affects your adrenal glands, which are small glands located on top of your kidneys. The adrenal glands produce hormones that are essential to life, such as cortisol and aldosterone. Addison disease can be life-threatening if not treated.

The individual experiences significant distress that is out of proportion to the severity or intensity of the stressor. The stressor is typically a life event or change, such as the death of a loved one, divorce, or loss of a job. The individual may have difficulty functioning in social or work situations and may have symptoms such as anxiety, depression, or irritability.
Adrenal extract is a natural product made from the adrenal glands of animals. It is used as a dietary supplement and is claimed to have a variety of health benefits.

Adrenal insufficiency is a condition in which the adrenal glands do not produce enough of the hormone cortisol. Cortisol is necessary for many body functions, including maintaining blood pressure and blood sugar levels. Adrenal insufficiency can be caused by a variety of conditions, including Addison's disease, pituitary tumors, and certain medications. Symptoms of adrenal insufficiency include fatigue, weakness, weight loss, and low blood pressure.

Adrenoleukodystrophy (ALD) is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the adrenal glands, the leukocytes (white blood cells), and the myelin sheath (the fatty covering that insulates nerve cells). ALD is characterized by the progressive destruction of the myelin sheath, which leads to neurological problems and adrenal insufficiency.

Adrenomyeloneuropathy (AMN) is a progressive neurological disorder that affects the spinal cord and the adrenal glands. AMN is caused by mutations in the ABCD1 gene, which is responsible for producing a protein that is essential for the proper function of the nervous system. The ABCD1 gene is located on the X chromosome, which is why AMN is primarily seen in males. Symptoms of AMN typically begin in adolescence or early adulthood and include weakness and numbness in the legs, urinary incontinence, and progressive loss of vision. AMN is a progressive disorder, meaning that symptoms worsen over time. There is no cure for AMN, but treatment can help to manage symptoms and slow the progression of the disease.

This Adrue plant is a small, succulent plant that typically grows to only about 6 inches in height. It has small, fleshy leaves that are arranged in a rosette pattern. The leaves are green in color and have a slightly waxy texture. The flowers of this plant are small and white, and they bloom in the summertime.

The African Wild Potato is a perennial herb that grows to about 1 meter in height. The leaves are dark green and have a leathery texture. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a small, dark-colored berry.
Agaricus mushrooms are a genus of fungi that includes many edible species, such as the common button mushroom.

Agave plants are succulents that are native to the deserts of North America. They are characterized by their rosette shape and their sharp, spiny leaves. Agave plants can grow to be quite large, and they are often used as ornamental plants in gardens.

column1: Age-Associated Memory Impairment And Cognitive Decline (AAMCD)
column2: Age-associated memory impairment and cognitive decline (AAMCD) is a health condition characterized by a decline in memory and cognitive function with age. AAMCD can lead to problems with daily living and increased dependency on others.

Age-related cognitive decline is a gradual decline in cognitive abilities, such as memory and executive function, that occurs with age. Although it is a normal part of aging, it can be a source of frustration and concern for older adults and their loved ones. There are a number of ways to help manage age-related cognitive decline, including staying mentally and physically active, eating a healthy diet, and getting adequate sleep.

Age-related fatigue is a health condition characterized by a feeling of tiredness and exhaustion that is not relieved by rest. It is a common problem among older adults, and can be caused by a number of factors, including poor sleep, medical conditions, and medications.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a health condition that affects a person's central vision. The condition is caused by the deterioration of the macula, which is the part of the eye that is responsible for sharp, central vision. AMD typically affects older adults, and the risk of developing the condition increases with age. There are two types of AMD: dry AMD and wet AMD. Dry AMD is the more common type of the two, and it progresses slowly. Wet AMD is less common, but it can cause more rapid vision loss.

Age-related testosterone deficiency is a health condition that can occur in men as they age. Testosterone is a hormone that helps to regulate many body processes, including sexual function and muscle mass. As men age, they may produce less testosterone, which can lead to symptoms such as reduced sex drive, erectile dysfunction, and fatigue.

Agmatine is a compound that is formed from the amino acid arginine. It is found in foods such as meat, fish, and nuts. It is also produced by the body and is involved in many processes, including the regulation of blood pressure and the production of neurotransmitters.
Agoraphobia is a type of anxiety disorder in which you fear and avoid places or situations that might cause you to panic and make you feel trapped, helpless, or embarrassed.

Agrimony is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are alternate, oblong to lanceolate, and have serrated margins. The flowers are small, yellow, and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, dry, brownish-black seed.  Agrimony is native to Europe and Asia. It has been introduced to North America, where it is now found in the eastern United States and Canada.  Agrimony is used as an herbal remedy for a variety of conditions, including diarrhea, stomach upset, and mouth sores. It is also used as a gargle for sore throats and can be applied topically to wounds and skin irritations.
This is a health condition where someone has AIDS and also has problems with their thinking, memory, and behavior.
This is a health condition where a person experiences diarrhea as a result of their AIDS infection. The diarrhea may be watery and/or bloody, and can lead to dehydration if not treated properly.
This is a condition in which there is an abnormal amount of lipids in the blood, which can be a result of HIV infection and antiretroviral therapy.
This is a health condition where a person's immune system is weakened and they are more susceptible to infections.
This is a condition where the nerves are damaged due to AIDS. This can lead to problems with movement, sensation, and organ function.

There are a number of pregnancy complications that can occur in women with AIDS. These include premature labor, low birth weight, and congenital abnormalities. In addition, women with AIDS are at increased risk for developing toxoplasmosis, which can lead to serious health problems for both the mother and the child.
This health condition is characterized by a loss of body weight and muscle mass. It can be caused by HIV infection and other factors, such as cancer or malnutrition.

Ajuga Nipponensis is a perennial herbaceous plant that is native to Japan. It is a member of the mint family and has a square stem. The leaves are opposite, ovate to lanceolate in shape, and have toothed margins. The flowers are blue and borne in whorls. The plant blooms from May to June.
Alanine is an amino acid that is found in proteins. It is essential for the body to make proteins.

Albizia julibrissin is a species of flowering tree in the pea family, Fabaceae, that is native to southwestern and eastern Asia. The tree is known in English as the Persian silk tree or pink silk tree.

Albuminuria is a condition in which there is an abnormal amount of albumin in the urine. Albumin is a protein that is normally found in the blood. When there is an abnormal amount of albumin in the urine, it may be a sign of a kidney problem.

Alchemilla is a genus of herbaceous perennial plants in the family Rosaceae, subfamily Rosoideae. The genus name is derived from the Latin word alcaemilla, meaning "little magic plant". They are native to Europe and Asia, and are commonly known as lady's mantle. These plants are characterized by their deeply lobed leaves and greenish-yellow flowers. Lady's mantle is a popular garden plant, and many cultivars have been developed.

The person experiences a strong urge to drink alcohol and has difficulty controlling their consumption. They may continue to drink even though it is causing problems in their life. They may feel that they need to drink to cope with their problems.
Alcohol-related liver disease (ARLD) is a range of conditions caused by drinking alcohol. It can lead to fatty liver, alcoholic hepatitis, and cirrhosis.

Alcoholic hepatitis is a potentially life-threatening inflammation of the liver that occurs in people who drink excessive amounts of alcohol. Alcoholic hepatitis typically develops after years of heavy drinking and can lead to liver failure.

Alder buckthorn is a shrub or small tree that is native to Europe, Asia, and North Africa. It is a member of the buckthorn family, which includes a number of other plants that are used for their medicinal properties. Alder buckthorn is used to treat a variety of conditions, including constipation, diarrhea, and stomach upset. It is also used as a laxative and to promote weight loss.

The Aletris plant is a perennial herb that is native to North America. It is a member of the lily family and grows to a height of about two feet. The leaves are long and narrow, and the flowers are white or pale pink. The plant blooms in the summer and produces small, black berries.
The Alexander Technique is a method of re-education that helps people to unlearn harmful habits of movement and posture. It is named after its developer, F. Matthias Alexander.
Algal oil is a type of oil that is derived from algae.
Algin is a brown algae extract that is used as a food additive and in cosmetics. It is a polysaccharide that is composed of repeating units of beta-D-mannuronic acid and alpha-L-guluronic acid.

The alkaline diet is a diet that emphasizes foods that are low in acidity and high in alkalinity. The diet is based on the premise that consuming alkaline foods can help maintain the body's pH balance and improve overall health.

Alkanna is a small, woody shrub that typically grows to between 2 and 4 feet in height. It has small, oval-shaped leaves that are arranged in pairs along the stems. The flowers are small and yellow, and they bloom in the spring. The fruit is a small, dry capsule that contains seeds.
Allium vegetables are a type of vegetable that includes onions, garlic, shallots, and leeks.

The Allspice plant is a small evergreen tree that is native to the West Indies. Allspice is the dried, unripe fruit of the Allspice tree. The fruit is small and brown and has a pungent, spicy aroma. Allspice is used as a spice in many cuisines, including Caribbean, Indian, and Middle Eastern cuisine. Allspice can be used whole or ground.
Almond nuts are the edible seeds of the almond tree. They are rich in vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants, and have a variety of health benefits.
Alpha-alanine is an amino acid that is used in the biosynthesis of proteins.

Alpha-ketoglutarate (AKG) is a compound that is involved in the Krebs cycle, which is a series of reactions that occur in the cells of the body to produce energy. AKG is used by the body to make glutamine, a compound that is important for the health of the immune system.
Alpha-lactalbumin is a protein found in milk. It is responsible for the production of lactose, the sugar found in milk.

(Senecio pygmaeus) The Alpine Ragwort is a small, perennial plant that is native to the Alps. It has a rosette of basal leaves and a stem with small, yellow flowers. The plant grows to a height of 10-15 cm and has a spread of 5-10 cm.

Alpinia is a genus of flowering plants in the ginger family, Zingiberaceae. They are native to tropical and subtropical Asia, New Guinea, Melanesia, and Australia. A few species are naturalized in the Americas.  This particular Alpinia plant is a tropical plant that is native to Asia. It is a perennial plant that can grow up to 6 feet tall. The leaves are green and the flowers are white.

In general, Adf is an approach to fasting in which people eat normally on one day, followed by a day of fasting ( consuming only water and non-caloric beverages). This cycle is then repeated over the course of several days or weeks.

The Alternative Healthy Eating Index (AHEI) is a diet score that rates how well a person's diet aligns with scientific recommendations for a healthy diet. The AHEI was developed by a team of nutrition researchers at Harvard University in the early 2000s. The AHEI has been shown to be associated with a lower risk of chronic diseases such as heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes.

Aluminium is a chemical element with the symbol Al and atomic number 13. It is a silvery-white, soft, non-magnetic and ductile metal in the boron group. By mass, aluminium makes up about 8% of the Earth's crust; it is the third most abundant element after oxygen and silicon and the most abundant metal in the crust, though it is less common in the mantle below. The chief ore of aluminium is bauxite. Aluminium metal is so chemically reactive that native specimens are rare and limited to extremely low temperatures. Instead, it is found combined in over 270 different minerals.

Aluminum phosphide is a highly toxic chemical used as a fumigant to kill rodents and insects. It is also used in the production of fireworks. When exposed to air, aluminum phosphide reacts with moisture to release phosphine gas, which is highly toxic to humans and animals. Symptoms of aluminum phosphide poisoning include headache, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, chest pain, and shortness of breath. In severe cases, it can cause respiratory failure and death.

Alveolar osteitis, also known as dry socket, is a condition that can occur after a tooth is extracted. The socket, or hole, where the tooth was located fails to heal properly and becomes filled with debris. This can cause pain and irritation.

Alzheimer's disease is a progressive disorder that causes brain cells to waste away (degenerate) and die. Alzheimer's disease is the most common cause of dementia — a continuous decline in thinking, behavioral and social skills that disrupts a person's ability to function independently.

Amanita Mushroom Poisoning is a potentially fatal condition caused by the ingestion of Amanita mushrooms. Symptoms include vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and seizures. Treatment is typically supportive and includes IV fluids and close monitoring.

The Amaranth plant is a flowering plant that produces small, edible seeds. The plant is native to South America, but it is now grown in many parts of the world. The seeds of the Amaranth plant are a good source of protein and fiber, and they are often used as a gluten-free flour.
Amblyopia is a health condition that results in blurred vision in one eye.
Amenorrhea is the absence of menstruation. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including hormonal imbalances, stress, and certain medications.

The American Adder's Tongue is a plant that is native to North America. It is a member of the lily family and is also known as the false Solomon's seal. The plant grows to be about two feet tall and has a cluster of white flowers at the top. The leaves are long and narrow and the plant blooms in the spring.
The American chestnut is a large, monoecious deciduous tree of the beech family native to eastern North America. The American chestnut was once one of the most important trees in the forest.

The American Dogwood is a small deciduous tree that is native to the eastern United States. It has a spreading canopy of branches and small, white flowers that bloom in the spring. The tree gets its name from the red fruits that appear in the fall.

The American elder (Sambucus canadensis) is a shrub or small tree in the family Adoxaceae. It is native to most of North America, from Newfoundland and Labrador to Alaska and west to Colorado. The American elder is a deciduous plant, meaning it loses its leaves in the fall. The leaves are opposite, simple, and serrated. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a black berry.
The American hellebore is a perennial plant that grows in the eastern United States. It has dark green leaves and white flowers that bloom in the spring.

Hedera helix, commonly known as English ivy, is a vigorous, aggressive, fast-growing, woody evergreen vine that is primarily grown as a ground-cover or ornamental climber. Left unchecked, it can grow upwards of 50 feet (15 m) in height. It climbs by means of small, black, disk-like holdfasts (also called sucker disks) and can clinging to any surface. The leaves are alternate, simple, and ovate to heart-shaped with a toothed margin. The leaf surface is variable in appearance. Young leaves are often glossy and dark green, while mature leaves can be dull and light green. The flowers are small, greenish-white, and borne in clusters in late summer to early fall. The fruit is a small, black, berry-like drupe.  English ivy is native to Europe, western Asia, and northern Africa. It has been introduced to North America and can be found growing in the wild in some areas of the eastern and western United States. This plant is considered an invasive species in some parts of the world.

The American mistletoe is a perennial evergreen plant that grows on trees and shrubs. It has dark green, leathery leaves and produces small, white berries. The berries are poisonous to humans but are eaten by birds, which spread the plant's seeds. American mistletoe is native to the eastern United States and Canada.

The American pawpaw (Asimina triloba) is a small deciduous tree native to the eastern United States and Canada. The pawpaw is the largest edible fruit indigenous to the continent, and has been cultivated since pre-Columbian times.

American spikenard is a perennial herb that grows up to 3 feet tall. The leaves are large and ovate, and the flowers are small and white. The plant is native to North America and is found in woods and thickets.

The American White Water Lily is a perennial aquatic plant that is native to North America. It is found in slow-moving waters, such as ponds, lakes, and streams. The plant has large, round leaves that float on the water's surface. The flowers are white and have yellow centers. The plant blooms from June to August.
Americium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Am and atomic number 95.
Amino acid therapy is a type of alternative therapy that uses amino acids to treat a variety of conditions.
Aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity is a condition that can occur when someone is taking aminoglycoside antibiotics. These antibiotics can damage the kidneys and cause kidney failure.
Aminoglycoside ototoxicity is a health condition caused by the use of aminoglycoside antibiotics. These antibiotics can damage the inner ear and cause hearing loss.
This is a condition where the kidneys are damaged by the use of Amphotericin B.

Amyloidosis is a rare disease that occurs when a protein called amyloid builds up in the body. Amyloid is a normal protein that is found in many tissues of the body, but in amyloidosis, amyloid builds up in the tissues and organs, and can cause them to malfunction. Amyloidosis can affect any organ or tissue in the body, but most often affects the heart, kidneys, liver, spleen, and nervous system.

Anabolic steroid addiction is a condition characterized by the compulsive use of anabolic steroids despite the negative consequences. Anabolic steroids are synthetic hormones that mimic the effects of testosterone. They are often used by bodybuilders and athletes to increase muscle mass and strength. However, anabolic steroids can have serious side effects, including liver damage, heart disease, and aggressive behavior. People with anabolic steroid addiction may continue to use the drugs even after they experience these negative effects.
Anal fissures are small tears in the skin around the anus. They can be caused by straining during a bowel movement, pregnancy, childbirth, or constipation. Anal fissures can be painful and may bleed.

Anal pruritus is a condition characterized by itching in the anal area. The exact cause of anal pruritus is unknown, but it is thought to be related to a number of factors, including hygiene, diet, and anal skin conditions. Treatment of anal pruritus typically involves a combination of self-care measures and medical treatment.

Andarine is a selective androgen receptor modulator (SARM) that is used to increase muscle mass and bone density. It is currently being studied as a treatment for conditions such as muscle wasting and osteoporosis.

The Andiroba tree is a large tropical tree that can grow up to 50 meters tall. It has a straight trunk with a diameter of up to 2 meters. The bark is smooth and grayish-brown in color. The leaves are simple, oblong-shaped, and measure up to 30 centimeters long. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a large, fleshy drupe that measures up to 10 centimeters in diameter.

This Andrachne plant is a small, woody shrub that typically grows to 2-3 feet tall. It has small, dark green leaves and white flowers that bloom in the spring. The Andrachne plant is native to the Mediterranean region and is often used as an ornamental plant in gardens.

Androgen deprivation therapy (ADT) is a treatment for prostate cancer that involves lowering the levels of androgens (male hormones) in the body. This can be done by using drugs that block the production or action of androgens, or by surgically removing the testicles (orchiectomy).

Androgenic alopecia (AGA) is a health condition characterized by the gradual thinning of hair on the scalp. This condition is also known as male pattern baldness. AGA is caused by the action of the hormone dihydrotestosterone (DHT) on the hair follicles. DHT is a by-product of the hormone testosterone. In men, DHT is responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics such as facial hair and a deep voice. DHT also plays a role in the development of AGA.
Androstenediol is a steroid hormone that is produced in the adrenal glands and the gonads. It is a precursor to testosterone and other androgen hormones.
Androstenedione is a hormone that is produced in the body. It is a precursor to testosterone and other androgens.
Androstenetrione is a prohormone that is structurally similar to testosterone. It is often used by bodybuilders to help increase muscle mass and strength.
Androsterone is a hormone that is produced in the body. It is a precursor to testosterone and is involved in the development of male characteristics.
Andvaline is a naturally occurring amino acid that is found in the body. It is a precursor to the neurotransmitter dopamine and is involved in the metabolism of fats and proteins.

This Angel's Trumpet plant is a beautiful, fragrant, and easy to grow plant that is perfect for any garden. It has large, trumpet-shaped flowers that bloom in the summer and fall. The flowers are white, pink, or purple and have a sweet fragrance. The plant is native to South America, but it can be grown in any climate.

This Angelica Archangelica plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to 2.5 m tall. The leaves are large and lobed, and the flowers are small and white. The plant is native to Europe and Asia, and is often used in herbal medicine.

Angelman Syndrome is a rare neurogenetic disorder that is characterized by developmental delays, intellectual disability, speech impairment, and problems with movement and balance. Individuals with Angelman Syndrome often have a happy disposition and frequently smile and laugh.
Angioplasty is a medical procedure used to widen narrowed or blocked blood vessels. This procedure is also known as percutaneous transluminal coronary angioplasty (PTCA).

Angular cheilitis is a condition that causes red, swollen patches in the corners of your mouth. The patches can be painful and can make it hard to eat. Angular cheilitis is usually caused by a fungal infection or by bacteria. It is more common in people who have diabetes or who wear dentures.
Animal fat is a type of fat that is derived from the tissues of animals. It is a source of energy and essential nutrients, and can be used to produce soap, cosmetics, and other products.
Animal-assisted therapy is a type of therapy that uses animals to help people cope with physical or mental health conditions.

Anise is an herbaceous annual plant in the family Apiaceae, native to the eastern Mediterranean region and Southwest Asia. Anise grows to 20–50 cm (8–20 in) tall, with finely divided, feathery leaves. The flowers are white, with five petals, and borne in umbels. The fruit is an oblong, dry schizocarp, which is brown or yellow-brown in color.  Anise is used as a spice, either whole or ground, for flavoring food and drink. It is an ingredient in some traditional desserts, including black jelly beans and Italian anisette cookies. It is also used in some savory dishes, such as the French dish of quenelles.

Ankylosing spondylitis is a form of arthritis that primarily affects the spine. The condition causes the vertebrae to fuse together, which can lead to a hunched-over posture. Ankylosing spondylitis can also cause pain and stiffness in other joints, such as the hips, knees, and shoulders. The exact cause of the condition is unknown, but it is thought to be related to a combination of genetic and environmental factors.
Anodyne therapy is a type of infrared light therapy that is used to relieve pain.
This is a condition where the heart muscle is damaged by an anthracycline drug. This can lead to heart failure and death.
The anti-inflammatory diet is a diet that is designed to help reduce inflammation in the body.
AAD is a condition that can occur when someone takes antibiotics. The antibiotics can kill the good bacteria in the intestines, which can lead to diarrhea.

Anticholinergic drugs are a type of medication that work by blocking the neurotransmitter acetylcholine. This action prevents the neurotransmitter from binding to its receptors, which results in a decrease in the number of nerve impulses that are sent to the brain.

AISD is a condition where a person experiences sexual dysfunction as a result of taking antidepressants. This can include problems with arousal, orgasm, and libido. AISD can be a side effect of many different types of antidepressants, and it can occur in both men and women.
A metalloid element with the atomic symbol Sb, atomic number 51, and atomic weight 121.7.
Antineoplastons are a group of naturally occurring peptides and amino acid derivatives that were first isolated from human urine in the 1970s by Japanese scientist Dr. Satoshi Ōmura.

Antiphospholipid syndrome-associated miscarriage is a health condition in which a woman who has antiphospholipid syndrome (APS) has a miscarriage. APS is a disorder in which the body produces antibodies that attack phospholipids, a type of fat found in the cell membranes. These antibodies can cause blood clots to form in the arteries and veins, which can lead to a miscarriage.

Antipsychotic-induced hyperprolactinemia is a condition in which there is an increase in the level of the hormone prolactin in the blood. This can be caused by certain antipsychotic medications. Symptoms of this condition can include breast enlargement, milk production, and irregular menstrual periods.
This health condition is characterized by a range of metabolic side effects that can be caused by antipsychotic medication. These side effects can include weight gain, diabetes, and high cholesterol.
This is a condition where the nerves are damaged by antiretroviral drugs used to treat HIV. This can lead to pain, numbness, tingling, and weakness.
This is a health condition where a person experiences diarrhea as a result of taking antiretroviral medication. The diarrhea may be mild or severe, and can lead to dehydration if not treated.
This is a health condition where the body becomes resistant to insulin after taking antiretroviral medications. This can lead to high blood sugar levels and diabetes.
This is a condition where a person experiences nausea and vomiting due to the use of antiretroviral drugs.

This is a health condition characterized by a range of adverse effects that may occur as a result of antituberculosis treatment. These effects can include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and rash. In severe cases, the adverse effects can lead to hospitalization or death.
Anxiety is a feeling of worry, nervousness, or unease, typically about an imminent event or something with an uncertain outcome.
Apitherapy is the use of bee products, including honey, pollen, propolis, and royal jelly, for medicinal purposes.

Aplastic anemia is a rare blood disorder in which the bone marrow and the hematopoietic stem cells that reside there are damaged. This damage leads to a decrease in the production of all blood cells, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.
Apoaequorin is a protein that is found in the jellyfish Aequorea victoria. This protein is what gives the jellyfish its bioluminescent properties.
Apple cider vinegar is a type of vinegar made from fermented apple juice.
Apple polyphenols are a type of phytonutrient that are found in apples. They are thought to have health benefits, including reducing the risk of heart disease and cancer.
Applied kinesiology is a system that evaluates structural, chemical, and mental aspects of health using manual muscle testing with other standard methods of diagnosis.
A apricot is a fruit that is similar to a peach. It has a soft, orange flesh and a pitted center.

The apricot kernel is the hard, inner pit of the apricot. It is oval in shape and contains a single seed. The kernel is surrounded by a thin, fleshy layer called the endocarp. The endocarp is edible, but it is often removed before eating.

column1: Connective Tissue Disease-Associated Interstitial Lung Disease (CT-ILD)
column2: This is a connective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease (CT-ILD) health condition. It is characterized by the presence of interstitial lung disease (ILD) in patients with connective tissue diseases (CTDs). CTDs are a group of disorders that affect the connective tissues of the body, including the lungs. ILD is a type of lung disease that affects the interstitial tissues of the lungs. These tissues are responsible for supporting the alveoli, the tiny air sacs in the lungs where oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged. ILD can cause the interstitial tissues to become inflamed and scarred, which can lead to difficulty breathing. CT-ILD is a rare condition, and its exact cause is unknown. However, it is believed to be caused by an autoimmune reaction to the connective tissues in the lungs. Treatment for CT-ILD typically involves the use of immunosuppressive medications to control the autoimmune reaction.

Contact dermatitis is a skin condition that occurs when the skin comes into contact with a substance that irritates it or causes an allergic reaction. The skin may become red, itchy, and inflamed. In severe cases, blisters may form.
