Crigler-Najjar syndrome type 2 is a rare inherited disorder that affects the liver's ability to process bilirubin. People with this condition have high levels of bilirubin in their blood, which can lead to jaundice, anemia, and other serious health problems. There is no cure for Crigler-Najjar syndrome, but treatment can help manage the symptoms and improve the person's quality of life.
This Critical Illness (trauma) health condition is a condition where a person has a physical or psychological injury as a result of a traumatic event.
This Croton plant has glossy, dark green leaves with yellow and orange margins. It is a compact, bushy plant that can reach up to 3 feet in height.
Crystal therapy is a type of alternative medicine that uses crystals or gemstones to promote healing. Crystal therapy is also known as crystal healing or gemstone therapy.
Cubebs are the dried, unripe berries of the plant Piper cubeba. They have a pungent, peppery flavor and are used as a spice in many cuisines.
A cucumber is a long, green, cylindrical fruit that is related to squash, melons, and pumpkins.

This cudweed plant is a small, perennial herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It has small, white flowers that bloom in the summer and fall. The leaves are oblong and have toothed margins. The plant grows to be about 10-15 cm tall.
This cumin plant has long, slender leaves and small, white flowers. The fruits of the plant are small, dark-brown seeds.
Curanderismo is a traditional healing system that combines herbal medicine, spiritual rituals, and folk beliefs. It is practiced in Mexico and other parts of Latin America.
A radioactive transuranic chemical element with the symbol Cm and atomic number 96.

This plant is a small, yellow-flowered herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the buttercup family, and its scientific name is Ranunculus sceleratus. The plant is considered to be a weed in many parts of the world, and it is often found in disturbed habitats such as roadsides and fields. The plant has a long taproot, and its leaves are deeply lobed. The flowers are small and yellow, and they bloom in the spring.

Cushing Syndrome is a hormonal disorder that occurs when the body produces too much of the hormone cortisol. This can happen when the body is exposed to too much stress, or when there is a tumor on the adrenal gland that is producing too much cortisol. Symptoms of Cushing Syndrome include weight gain, thinning skin, easy bruising, and changes in mood.

Cutaneous lupus erythematosus (CLE) is a type of lupus that affects the skin. It can cause a wide range of skin problems, from mild rashes to ulcers. In some people, CLE can also cause problems with the joints, kidneys, and other organs.

Cutaneous necrotizing venulitis is a condition characterized by inflammation and necrosis of small veins in the skin. It typically presents as a rash with small, red, and painful bumps. The bumps may eventually blister and ulcerate. Cutaneous necrotizing venulitis is a rare condition that can be associated with autoimmune diseases, such as lupus erythematosus, or with certain medications, such as penicillin. Treatment typically involves discontinuing the offending medication and using topical or systemic steroids to control the inflammation.

Cutaneous sporotrichosis is a fungal infection of the skin that typically affects the fingers, hands, or arms. The infection usually starts as a small, red, painful bump that develops into a pus-filled lesion. Sporotrichosis is caused by the fungus Sporothrix schenckii, which is found in soil and plant matter. The fungus can enter the skin through cuts or scratches. The infection is not contagious and can be treated with antifungal medications.

Cyanide poisoning is a health condition that can occur when someone is exposed to high levels of cyanide. Symptoms of cyanide poisoning include headache, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, chest pain, and shortness of breath. Cyanide poisoning can be fatal if not treated immediately.

Cyanostane is a synthetic anabolic-androgenic steroid (AAS) and a 17α-alkylated prohormone of the potent AAS stanozolol. It was first described in the early 2000s and has since been sold as a designer drug.

Cyclamen is a genus of 23 species of flowering plants in the family Primulaceae. Cyclamen species are native to Europe, the Mediterranean Basin, and Africa, from Morocco and Portugal in the west to Ethiopia in the east. They grow from tubers and are valued for their flowers with upswept petals and variably patterned leaves.  This particular species of Cyclamen has dark green leaves with silver-white marbling, and pink flowers with white centers. It is a low-growing plant, reaching only 6-8 inches in height.
Cyclic vomiting syndrome (CVS) is a condition that causes episodes of vomiting and nausea. These episodes can last for a few hours to several days. CVS is more common in children than adults.

Cyclosporine-induced hypertension is a condition in which high blood pressure is caused by the use of the medication cyclosporine. Cyclosporine is a medication that is used to suppress the immune system and is often used in transplant patients.

Cyclosporine-induced nephrotoxicity is a condition that can occur in people who take the medication cyclosporine. Cyclosporine is a medication that is used to suppress the immune system. It is often used in people who have had organ transplants.  Cyclosporine-induced nephrotoxicity occurs when the kidney is damaged by the medication cyclosporine. This can lead to a decrease in kidney function. Symptoms of cyclosporine-induced nephrotoxicity may include:  -High blood pressure  -Swelling of the ankles, feet, or legs  -Weight gain  -Fatigue  -Nausea  -Loss of appetite  -Confusion  -Difficulty urinating  If you experience any of these symptoms, you should contact your doctor.
A cypress is a coniferous tree in the family Cupressaceae, native to the Mediterranean region.
Cysteine is a non-essential amino acid that is involved in the formation of protein structures. It is also a precursor for the synthesis of glutathione, a important antioxidant.

Cystinosis is a rare, inherited disorder that causes an amino acid called cystine to build up in the cells of the body. Cystine is a building block of proteins. The build-up of cystine in the cells damages many organs in the body, including the kidneys, liver, eyes, muscles, and brain.
Cystinuria is a rare inherited disorder that causes an abnormal buildup of the amino acid cystine in the urine. This can lead to the formation of kidney stones.

Cystitis is a condition that results when the bladder becomes inflamed. The most common symptom is a burning sensation when urinating. Other symptoms may include pain in the lower abdomen, cloudy or bloody urine, and a strong urge to urinate. Cystitis is most often caused by a bacterial infection, but it can also be caused by a viral infection, an allergic reaction, or irritation from a foreign object in the urinary tract. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and pain relief.

D-Mannose is a simple sugar that is found in some plants, including cranberries. It is sometimes used as a dietary supplement, and it has been claimed to have a range of health benefits, including the ability to treat urinary tract infections (UTIs).
The 'Tahiti' daffodil is a hybrid that was bred in the Netherlands. It is a large-cupped daffodil with white petals and a yellow cup. The 'Tahiti' daffodil is fragrant and blooms in mid-spring.
Dairy products are defined as foods that are made from milk or milk products.

The Damiana plant is a small shrub that is native to Mexico, Central America, and the West Indies. It has small, green leaves and yellow or white flowers. The plant has a strong, sweet smell, and the leaves can be used to make tea.
Dark chocolate is a type of chocolate that contains a higher percentage of cocoa solids, and often less sugar, than other types of chocolate.
Darmstadtium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Ds and atomic number 110. It is an extremely radioactive metal that decays into other elements very quickly.
The Dash Diet is a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and low-fat dairy foods that is designed to lower blood pressure.
The date palm is a species of palm tree that is cultivated for its edible fruit. The fruit of the date palm is called a date, and the tree is sometimes referred to as a date palm.

This Datura wrightii plant is a beautiful, fast-growing, and fragrant annual that can reach up to 3 feet in height. The large, white, trumpet-shaped flowers have purple streaks and are up to 6 inches long. The flowers bloom in the summer and are followed by large, spiny seed pods. This plant is native to the southwestern United States and northern Mexico.
Deanol is a substance that is found in the brain and is involved in the metabolism of choline. It is also a precursor to acetylcholine, which is a neurotransmitter.
Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) is a hormone that is produced by the adrenal glands. It is a precursor to testosterone and other androgens.

Delayed Sleep Phase Syndrome (DSPS) is a sleep disorder in which a person's natural sleep/wake cycle is delayed by two or more hours. This can make it difficult for a person to fall asleep at their desired bedtime and wake up at their desired time in the morning.

Delirium is a sudden, severe change in mental status that can happen when a person is sick or injured. It can also happen when a person is taking certain medications or has a medical condition that affects the brain.
Delta-9-Tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) is the main active ingredient in cannabis. It is a psychoactive compound that produces the "high" feeling associated with marijuana use.
This Dendrobium plant is a small, deciduous orchid that is native to Southeast Asia. It has long, thin leaves and small, white flowers.

Dengue fever is a viral infection that is transmitted by mosquitoes. It is a leading cause of death in many tropical and subtropical countries. Symptoms of dengue fever include fever, headache, muscle and joint pain, and a rash. Treatment is typically with rest and fluids. There is no specific antiviral treatment for dengue fever.

Dental hypersensitivity is a condition in which the teeth become extremely sensitive to hot, cold, or sweet foods and drinks. The condition can also be triggered by changes in temperature or humidity.
Dental plaque is a sticky film of bacteria that forms on teeth. It is a major cause of tooth decay and gum disease.

Denture stomatitis is an inflammation of the mucous membranes lining the mouth, which can occur in people who wear dentures. The condition is typically characterized by redness, soreness, and a burning sensation in the mouth. In some cases, the inflammation may also lead to the formation of ulcers. Denture stomatitis is generally caused by the accumulation of bacteria on the dentures, which can occur if the dentures are not cleaned properly. Treatment of the condition typically involves the use of antibacterial mouthwashes or topical creams. In severe cases, the dentures may need to be removed and replaced.

Dermatitis is a general term for inflammation of the skin. It can be caused by a number of different things, including allergies, irritants, and infections. Symptoms of dermatitis include redness, itching, and swelling.

(Lomatium californicum)  The Desert Parsley is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are deeply divided and the flowers are small, white, and borne in umbels. The fruit is a small, dry, brownish-black seed. This plant is native to the southwestern United States and northern Mexico.
Detoxification footpads are pads that are placed on the feet before bedtime. They are said to help remove toxins from the body and improve overall health.

Developmental coordination disorder (DCD) is a condition that affects movement and coordination. It can make everyday activities, such as getting dressed or brushing your teeth, difficult to do. DCD can also affect your ability to play sports or ride a bike. The cause of DCD is unknown, but it is thought to be due to a problem with the way the brain processes information about movement.

Devil's Club is a large, woody shrub that can grow up to 8 feet tall. It has large, lobed leaves and clusters of small, white flowers. The plant is native to North America and can be found in forests and woodlands. Devil's Club is sometimes used as an herbal remedy for various ailments.
Dextrose is a simple sugar that is derived from corn and is used as a sweetener.
A diabetic foot ulcer is a sore on the foot that does not heal. Diabetic foot ulcers are a serious complication of diabetes.

Diabetic ketoacidosis is a serious complication of diabetes that occurs when your body produces high levels of blood acids called ketones. The condition develops when your body can't produce enough insulin. Insulin normally plays a key role in helping sugar (glucose) enter your cells, where it's used for energy.

This is a condition where there is damage to the small blood vessels in the body, which can lead to problems with blood flow and circulation. This can cause problems with the organs and tissues in the body, and can lead to complications such as heart disease, stroke, and kidney disease.
A diacylglycerol is a molecule that has two fatty acids attached to a glycerol.
A diet soda is a carbonated soft drink that is sweetened with artificial sweeteners.

column1: Dietary Approaches To Stop Hypertension Diet
column2: The Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension Diet, also known as the DASH Diet, is a diet that is high in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains, and low in saturated fat, cholesterol, and salt. The DASH Diet has been shown to lower blood pressure in people with high blood pressure, and is recommended by the American Heart Association and the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute as a way to prevent and treat hypertension.

Dietary fat is a type of nutrient that is found in food. It is a macronutrient, which means that the body needs it in large amounts. Dietary fat is essential for many bodily functions, including the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins, the production of hormones, and the insulation of body organs.
Digestive enzymes are enzymes that break down food into smaller molecules that can be absorbed into the body.

Diindolylmethane is a compound that is found in cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, cabbage, and kale. It has been shown to have a variety of health benefits, including the ability to reduce the risk of certain types of cancer.
Diiodothyronine is a thyroid hormone that is responsible for the regulation of metabolism. It is produced by the thyroid gland and is released into the bloodstream.

Dilated cardiomyopathy is a condition in which the heart muscle becomes weakened and stretched. This can cause the heart to become enlarged and unable to pump blood effectively. Dilated cardiomyopathy is a serious condition that can lead to heart failure.

Dill is an annual herb in the celery family. It is native to the Mediterranean region and has naturalized in many other areas, including northern Europe, Africa, and North America. Dill grows to 30–60 cm (12–24 in) tall, with slender hollow stems and alternate, finely divided, softly delicate leaves 10–20 cm (4–8 in) long. The flowers are white to yellow, in small umbels 2–9 cm (0.8–3.5 in) diameter. The fruit is a slender, oval, brownish achene 4–7 mm (0.16–0.28 in) long.  Dill is a popular culinary herb used in pickles, salads, and sauces. It has a distinctive flavor that is both sweet and savory. Dill is also used in herbal medicine to treat digestive disorders and to promote lactation.

Dimethyl fumarate-induced side effects are a group of symptoms that can occur in people who take dimethyl fumarate, a medication used to treat certain medical conditions. The most common side effects include flushing, itching, and gastrointestinal problems.

Dimethylglycine (DMG) is a compound that is naturally produced in the body. It is involved in many biochemical processes, including the production of energy, the metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and the synthesis of DNA and RNA. DMG is also a potent antioxidant and has been shown to protect cells from damage caused by free radicals.
Dimethylhexylamine (DMHA) is a stimulant that is structurally similar to octodrine and has similar effects. It is often used as a pre-workout supplement to increase energy and focus.

Dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO) is a clear liquid solvent that is used in a variety of industrial and commercial applications. It is a polar solvent, meaning that it has a dipole moment, and is miscible with water.

Dioscorea dumetorum is a species of yam in the genus Dioscorea. It is native to tropical Africa, where it is found in countries such as Angola, Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, the Central African Republic, the Republic of the Congo, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ivory Coast, Gabon, Ghana, Guinea, Liberia, Mali, Nigeria, Senegal, Sierra Leone, Togo, and Uganda. It is also found in the Indian Ocean island nation of the Comoros.  Dioscorea dumetorum is a herbaceous vine that can grow up to 10 m (33 ft) in length. The leaves are ovate to elliptical in shape and measure up to 20 cm (8 in) long and 15 cm (6 in) wide. The flowers are small and greenish-white in color, and they are borne in inflorescences that are up to 30 cm (12 in) long. The fruit is a small, fleshy berry that is green or yellow in color.

Diosmin is a flavonoid that is found in citrus fruits. It is used as a dietary supplement and is thought to have a variety of health benefits, including reducing inflammation, improving circulation, and protecting against cancer.
A disaccharide is a carbohydrate that is composed of two monosaccharides that are joined by a covalent bond.

Diverticulitis is a condition in which the diverticula, or small pouches, in the lining of the intestine become inflamed. This can cause abdominal pain, cramping, diarrhea, and constipation. In severe cases, it can lead to life-threatening complications such as perforation of the intestine, abscesses, and sepsis.

The Divi-Divi tree (Caesalpinia coriaria) is a small, drought-tolerant tree that is native to the Caribbean island of Aruba. The tree gets its name from the way its branches grow - they twist and turn in a way that makes them look like they are divining the future. The Divi-Divi tree is the national tree of Aruba, and its wood is used to make furniture and other wood products.

Docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) is an omega-3 fatty acid that is found in cold-water fish. It is also found in some algae and other marine plants. DHA is important for the proper development of the brain, eyes, and nervous system.

(Cuscuta epithymum)  This dodder plant is a small, twining, annual herb that is native to Europe, Asia, and Africa. It has small, white flowers that bloom in summer. The plant gets its name from the Greek word for "ivy", because it resembles ivy in its growth habit.
Dolomite is a mineral composed of calcium magnesium carbonate CaMg(CO3)2.

Dracaena is a genus of about 120 species of tree-like plants in the family Asparagaceae, native to tropical Africa, southern Asia, and the islands of the western Pacific. The vast majority of the species are found in tropical Africa, with only a few in southern Asia and one in the Solomon Islands. The genus includes many common houseplants, including Dracaena fragrans (the "corn plant"), which is widely grown as an ornamental plant.  The leaves of Dracaena are simple, with entire margins and an apical tip. The flowers are small and borne in inflorescences that are either terminal or axillary. The fruit is a fleshy berry.

The dragon fruit is a tropical fruit that is native to Central and South America. The fruit is oval in shape and has a bright pink or red skin. The flesh of the fruit is white or pink and is filled with small black seeds. The fruit has a sweet taste and is often used in desserts or as a decoration on cakes and other pastries.
This is a condition where hearing loss is caused by exposure to certain drugs.
This is a condition where high blood pressure is caused by taking certain medications.

This is a condition where the kidneys are damaged as a result of taking certain medications. The medications may be over-the-counter or prescription drugs. The damage may be temporary or permanent. Symptoms may include decreased urine output, swelling in the legs and feet, and fatigue.
This condition is caused by damage to the nerves from certain drugs. The drugs may be used to treat cancer, HIV, or other conditions. The damage can cause pain, numbness, tingling, or weakness.
This is a condition where the sodium channels in the body are blocked by a drug. This can lead to problems with the electrical signals in the body and can cause symptoms like seizures.

Dry gangrene is a type of gangrene that occurs when blood flow to an area of tissue is cut off. Dry gangrene usually affects the extremities, such as the toes, fingers, or hands. The affected tissue becomes dry, hard, and dark.

Dry mouth is a condition in which there is a decrease in saliva production. This can lead to problems with speaking, eating, and swallowing. Dry mouth can also cause an increase in cavities and gum disease.
Dry skin is a condition where the skin feels dry, tight, and sometimes itchy. The skin may also flake or peel.
Dubnium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Db and atomic number 105.

Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy is a progressive muscle disorder that is caused by a mutation in the dystrophin gene. This disease primarily affects boys and is characterized by muscle weakness and wasting. There is currently no cure for Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy, but there are treatments available to help manage the symptoms.

The Duckweed plant is a small, floating aquatic plant that is found in ponds and other bodies of water. The plant has small, green leaves that are arranged in a rosette pattern. The leaves are attached to the stem by a small stalk. The plant reproduces by producing small, green flowers that float on the surface of the water. The flowers produce small, green fruits that contain the seeds of the plant.

Dumping syndrome is a condition that can occur after surgery to remove part of your stomach or after surgery to bypass your stomach to help you lose weight. It happens when food moves too quickly from your stomach to your small intestine.

Durabolin is a brand name for the anabolic steroid nandrolone. Nandrolone is a synthetic hormone that resembles testosterone. Durabolin is used to promote muscle growth and increase strength. It is also used to treat anemia and osteoporosis.

The durian is the fruit of trees of the genus Durio, belonging to the family Malvaceae. There are about 30 recognised Durio species, at least nine of which produce edible fruit, and over 300 named varieties in Thailand. Durio zibethinus is the only species available in the international market: other species are sold in their local regions.

This Dusty Miller plant has beautiful, silvery-gray leaves that are covered in a fine powdery substance. The leaves are deeply lobed and have a ruffled appearance. The plant produces small, yellow flowers that bloom in the summer.

The Dwarf Elder is a small, deciduous shrub that typically grows to 3-6’ tall and to 4-8’ wide. It is native to woodlands, hedgerows and scrub in Europe, Asia and North Africa. It typically occurs in moist, well-drained soils, but will tolerate some drought once established. It has ovate to elliptic, dark green leaves (to 3” long) with toothed margins. Tiny, white flowers in flat-topped clusters (cymes) bloom in late spring to early summer. Flowers are followed by small, black berries (to 1/3” diameter) which ripen in late summer to fall. Berries are poisonous if ingested in large quantities. Genus name comes from the Greek words sambuca meaning a musical instrument and ospera meaning elder. Specific epithet means small.
A Dwarf Pine Needle is a small, evergreen needle-like leaf that is found on some types of pine trees.

Dyer's broom is a perennial herb in the family Fabaceae. The plant is native to Europe, Asia, and North Africa. It is also naturalized in Australia, New Zealand, and North America. The plant grows to 1-2 m tall, with yellow flowers blooming in the spring. The plant is used as a dyestuff and in herbal medicine.

Dymethazine is a prodrug of methasterone, meaning it is converted into methasterone in the body. Methasterone is a powerful anabolic steroid with a similar structure to testosterone. It is used by bodybuilders and athletes to increase muscle mass and strength.
Dysmenorrhea is a condition that causes pain during menstruation. The pain can be mild to severe and can last for a few hours to a few days.
Dysplastic nevi are moles that do not look like common moles. They are usually larger than common moles and have an irregular shape. They may be flat or raised and can have a mixture of colors.
Dyspraxia is a condition that affects a person's ability to plan and coordinate movement. It can also affect a person's speech and language skills.

Dysprosium is a chemical element with the symbol Dy and atomic number 66. It is a rare earth element with a metallic silver luster. Dysprosium is never found in nature as a free element, but it is found in various minerals, such as xenotime.

Dysthymia is a health condition characterized by a persistent low mood. Symptoms of dysthymia include feelings of sadness, hopelessness, and low self-esteem. Dysthymia is a less severe form of depression, but it can last for years.

Dystonia is a neurological movement disorder that is characterized by involuntary muscle contractions and abnormal postures. The disorder can be caused by genetic factors, brain injury, or certain medications. Symptoms of dystonia can vary from mild to severe, and may include muscle spasms, cramping, and tremors. There is no cure for dystonia, but treatments are available to help manage the symptoms.
Ear candling is a practice that involves placing a lit, cone-shaped candle in the ear canal in order to remove earwax or relieve ear pain.

Early-Onset Puberty is a health condition where a child begins to show signs of puberty at an unusually young age. This can be caused by a number of factors, including certain medical conditions, certain medications, and exposure to certain chemicals. Early-Onset Puberty can cause a number of physical and emotional problems for children, so it is important to get a diagnosis and treatment as soon as possible.

The Eastern Hemlock is a species of coniferous tree that is native to eastern North America. The tree is also known as the Tsuga canadensis, and it is the state tree of Pennsylvania. The Eastern Hemlock can grow to be over 150 feet tall, and it has a lifespan of over 600 years. The tree is an important source of food and shelter for many animals, and it is also used in the production of paper and lumber.
The Eastern Red Cedar is a species of juniper that is native to eastern North America.
An eating disorder is a mental disorder defined by abnormal eating habits that negatively affect a person's physical or mental health.

Ebola Virus Disease (EVD) is a rare and deadly disease caused by infection with one of the Ebola virus strains. Ebola virus was first identified in 1976 near the Ebola River in what is now the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Since then, outbreaks have occurred sporadically in Africa. The largest and most complex outbreak to date is the ongoing outbreak in West Africa, which began in December 2013.

Ecdysteroids are a class of natural products that function as hormones and pheromones in insects and other arthropods. They are structurally related to the sterols and are synthesized from cholesterol.

Ecklonia cava is a species of brown algae that is found in the waters off the coast of Korea. It is used in traditional Korean medicine for a variety of purposes, including the treatment of skin conditions and the promotion of hair growth.

Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, is a chronic inflammatory skin condition that results in dry, itchy skin. Eczema is a common condition, and it is often seen in children. However, it can occur at any age. There is no cure for eczema, but there are treatments that can help to control the symptoms.
Edible oil is a type of oil that is safe to consume. It is typically used in cooking and can be found in a variety of food products.

The Egfr Inhibitor-Induced Acneiform Rash is a skin condition that is characterized by the development of acne-like lesions on the skin. This condition is typically caused by the use of certain medications, such as EGFR inhibitors, that can lead to the overproduction of sebum. The resulting excess sebum can then block the pores and lead to the development of acne-like lesions. In some cases, the Egfr Inhibitor-Induced Acneiform Rash can also be associated with other symptoms, such as itching, redness, and swelling.

An egg allergy is a condition in which a person has an adverse reaction to proteins found in chicken eggs. Symptoms of an egg allergy can range from mild (such as hives or itching) to severe (such as anaphylaxis, a potentially life-threatening condition).
Eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) is an omega-3 fatty acid found in fish oil. EPA is beneficial for heart health and has anti-inflammatory properties.
Eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) is an omega-3 fatty acid found in fish oil. EPA is beneficial for heart health and has anti-inflammatory properties.

Einsteinium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Es and atomic number 99. It is the seventh transuranic element, and an actinide. Einsteinium was discovered as a component of the debris of the first hydrogen bomb explosion in 1952, and named after Albert Einstein.

Elderflower is a flowering plant in the family Adoxaceae. It is a deciduous shrub that grows to a height of 2-5 m (6.6-16.4 ft). The leaves are opposite, simple, and 10-25 cm (3.9-9.8 in) long. The flowers are white, borne in corymbs of 10-30 blooms. The fruit is a black berry 5-10 mm (0.20-0.39 in) in diameter.

Elecampane is a tall herbaceous perennial plant with yellow flowers and large, aromatic leaves. The plant is native to Europe and Asia, and has been introduced to North America. Elecampane is a member of the daisy family (Asteraceae). The plant grows to a height of 2-3 m (6.6-9.8 ft). The leaves are large, up to 30 cm (12 in) long and 20 cm (8 in) wide, and are deeply lobed with toothed margins. The flowers are yellow, 10-15 cm (4-6 in) in diameter, and are borne in clusters of 2-5 on the ends of the stems. The fruit is a dry, brown achene.  Elecampane is used as an herbal medicine. The roots and leaves are used to make teas and tinctures. Elecampane is used to treat respiratory conditions such as bronchitis, coughs, and asthma. The plant is also used as a digestive aid and to treat stomach conditions such as indigestion and heartburn. Elecampane is also used as a diuretic and to treat urinary tract infections.
Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is a psychiatric treatment in which seizures are induced in patients to provide relief from mental illness.
Elemi is a resin that is obtained from the tree Canarium luzonicum, which is native to the Philippines. The resin is used as a fixative in perfumes and as a incense.

The Elm Bark plant is a deciduous tree that can grow to be up to 50 feet tall. It has a spreading canopy with dark green, leathery leaves that are 3-6 inches long. The tree produces small, greenish-yellow flowers in the spring, which are followed by small, brown fruits. The tree's bark is dark brown or black and is deeply furrowed.
Emergence delirium is a condition that can occur after surgery, when a person is coming out of anesthesia. It is characterized by confusion, agitation, and sometimes hallucinations.

Emotional Freedom Techniques (EFT) is a form of psychological acupressure, based on the same energy meridians used in traditional acupuncture, that uses tapping on the body to help clear emotional blockages.

Emu oil is a natural oil derived from the fat of the emu bird. It has been used for centuries by Aboriginal Australians for its healing properties. Emu oil is high in omega-3 fatty acids, which are known to be beneficial for the skin. It is also a natural anti-inflammatory, making it ideal for treating conditions such as eczema and psoriasis.

Encephalitis is a serious and potentially life-threatening inflammation of the brain. Symptoms can include headache, fever, confusion, drowsiness, and seizures. Encephalitis can be caused by a viral infection, such as the flu, or by a bacterial infection, such as meningitis. Treatment typically involves hospitalization and aggressive supportive care. In some cases, antiviral or antibacterial medications may be used.

End-stage renal disease is a health condition in which the kidneys are no longer able to function properly. This can lead to a build-up of toxins in the body, as well as fluid retention and high blood pressure. Dialysis or a kidney transplant may be required in order to treat this condition.

Endometrial hyperplasia is a condition in which the endometrium, the lining of the uterus, becomes thickened. This can be caused by a variety of factors, including hormone imbalances, obesity, and certain medications. In some cases, endometrial hyperplasia can lead to cancer of the uterus.

Endometritis is a condition in which the endometrium, the layer of tissue that lines the uterus, becomes inflamed. Endometritis can cause pain, bleeding, and discharge from the vagina. It can also lead to fertility problems.

This is a health condition where the patient experiences adverse effects from an endoscopy procedure. These adverse effects can include pain, bleeding, infection, and perforation of the gastrointestinal tract.

The Endotracheal Intubation-Associated Adverse Effects health condition is characterized by a number of potential adverse effects that may occur as a result of endotracheal intubation. These adverse effects include but are not limited to airway trauma, esophageal perforation, and vocal cord paralysis.
Energy drinks are beverages that contain caffeine and other ingredients that are claimed to help with mental and physical stimulation.
Energy therapy is a type of alternative medicine that uses the body's energy field to promote healing. Energy therapies include acupuncture, acupressure, and qigong.

This English Adder's Tongue plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 1-2 feet in height. The leaves are lanceolate to ovate in shape and are green to dark green in color. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters on the ends of the stems. The fruit is a small, black berry.

This English Horsemint plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lanceolate and toothed, and the flowers are white with purple spots. This plant blooms in the summer and is found in dry, open areas.

This English Ivy plant is an evergreen vine that can grow to be up to 100 feet long. It has dark green, glossy leaves that are 3-6 inches long and 2-4 inches wide. The leaves are arranged in pairs along the stem, and they have a slightly toothed margin. This plant produces small, greenish-white flowers in the spring, and these are followed by black berries.

The English walnut is a species of walnut that is native to the eastern Mediterranean region, including Turkey, Greece, and Cyprus. The English walnut is a large deciduous tree that can grow to a height of 30 m (100 ft) and a width of 20 m (66 ft). The English walnut has a round, brown fruit that is enclosed in a green, leathery husk. The fruit is edible and has a sweet, nutty flavor.

Enzyme therapy is the use of enzymes to treat a variety of medical conditions. Enzymes are proteins that catalyze chemical reactions in the body. They are involved in many biochemical processes, including digestion, metabolism, and cellular repair. Enzyme therapy can be used to treat conditions such as allergies, arthritis, cancer, and cardiovascular disease.

Epiandrosterone is a naturally occurring steroid hormone. It is a metabolite of testosterone and dihydrotestosterone. Epiandrosterone is found in small amounts in the human body. It is also found in some plants and animals.

Epistane is a synthetic anabolic-androgenic steroid (AAS) and a derivative of dihydrotestosterone (DHT). It was first developed in the 1960s and has since been used by bodybuilders and athletes for its muscle-building and performance-enhancing effects. Epistane is not approved for use in humans by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and is considered a controlled substance in the United States.

Equol is a compound that is produced when certain types of bacteria break down the plant compound daidzein. Daidzein is found in soybeans and other legumes. Some research suggests that equol may have health benefits, including reducing the risk of certain types of cancer and improving bone health.

Erbium is a chemical element with the symbol Er and atomic number 68. A silvery-white solid metal when artificially isolated, natural erbium is always found in chemical combination with other elements. It is a lanthanide, a rare earth element, originally found in the gadolinite mine in Ytterby in Sweden, and named after the village.

Erectile dysfunction (ED) is a sexual health condition that affects a man’s ability to get or maintain an erection. It can be caused by physical or psychological factors, or a combination of both. ED can be a short-term or long-term problem.
Ergogenic aids are substances that can increase athletic performance.

Ergothioneine is a naturally occurring amino acid that is found in a variety of foods, including mushrooms, wheat germ, and black beans. It is also produced by the body in small amounts. Ergothioneine has antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties and is thought to play a role in protecting cells from damage.

Eryngo is a plant that typically grows in the Mediterranean region. It has a long, thin stem and small, white flowers. The plant is used in traditional medicine to treat a variety of conditions, including respiratory problems and digestive issues.

Erythema is a redness of the skin that is caused by inflammation or injury. It can occur as a result of infection, allergic reaction, or other irritation of the skin. Erythema may also be caused by exposure to certain chemicals or ultraviolet light.

Erythropoietic Protoporphyria (EPP) is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the production of heme, a substance that gives blood its red color. People with EPP have an enzyme deficiency that causes an accumulation of protoporphyrin in the body's red blood cells and tissues. Protoporphyrin is a precursor to heme. When exposed to sunlight, protoporphyrin absorbs light and produces free radicals that damage cells. This can lead to pain, swelling, and redness of the skin (photosensitivity). In severe cases, it can lead to scarring and disfigurement. There is no cure for EPP, but avoidance of sunlight and use of sunscreens and other protective measures can help to prevent or minimize symptoms.

Esophageal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the esophagus, the long, thin tube that carries food and liquids from the throat to the stomach. Esophageal cancer can occur anywhere along the esophagus, but it is most common in the lower part of the esophagus, near the stomach. Esophageal cancer is usually found in people over the age of 50.
Esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) is a diagnostic procedure that allows the doctor to look at the lining of the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum (the first part of the small intestine).
Essential oils are concentrated, volatile oils that are extracted from plants. They are used in a variety of ways, including aromatherapy, massage, and skin care.

Essential tremor is a neurological condition that causes a person's hands, head, trunk, voice, or legs to shake uncontrollably. The tremor is often worse when the person is under stress or when they are trying to do something with their hands. Essential tremor is the most common type of tremor, and it usually affects people over the age of 40.
This plant is a low-growing, spreading, evergreen perennial. It has small, blue-green leaves and yellow flowers that appear in spring. The flowers are followed by small, round, green fruits.

Euphorbia hirta is a small, annual herb that grows to about 30 cm in height. The leaves are opposite, oblong to lanceolate in shape, and have toothed margins. The flowers are small and greenish-white, borne in clusters at the leaf axils. The fruits are tiny, dry, and spherical.

Berberis thunbergii, also known as Japanese barberry, is a species of barberry native to central and northern Japan, Korea and China. It is also naturalized in much of North America and Europe. It is a deciduous shrub growing to 1–2 m (3–7 ft) tall and wide, with small, ovate to oblong leaves 3–7 cm (1.2–2.8 in) long and 2–3 cm (0.79–1.2 in) broad. The flowers are yellow, 4–6 mm (0.16–0.24 in) diameter, produced in racemes 3–5 cm (1.2–2.0 in) long in late spring to early summer. The fruit is an oblong red berry 5–8 mm (0.20–0.31 in) long, ripening in late summer to autumn.

Rhamnus frangula, commonly known as European buckthorn or common buckthorn, is a species of flowering plant in the buckthorn family Rhamnaceae. It is a small to medium-sized deciduous shrub or tree growing to 5–10 m (16–33 ft) tall, with a trunk up to 20 cm (8 in) diameter. The bark is dark brown to blackish, with small fissures. The branchlets are slender, often spiny, and covered with small dark brown scales. The leaves are alternate, simple, 3–10 cm (1.2–3.9 in) long and 1–3 cm (0.39–1.18 in) broad, with a serrated margin and an acute apex. They are dark green above, paler and glaucous below, and turn red or purple in autumn. The flowers are small, yellow-green, with four petals, produced in clusters of 2–5 together in the leaf axils in early spring. The fruit is a small dark purple drupe, ripening in autumn and containing a single seed.
The European chestnut (Castanea sativa) is a species of chestnut native to southern Europe, north Africa, and western Asia. The tree is widely cultivated for its edible nuts.

European Five-Finger Grass is a perennial plant that is native to Europe. It has long, slender leaves that are arranged in a fan-like shape. The leaves are green in color and have a white stripe running down the center. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters at the end of the leaves. The plant blooms in the summer.

The European mandrake is a perennial herb that grows to a height of 30-60 cm. It has a reddish-brown stem and dark green leaves. The flowers are small and white, and they bloom in the summer. The fruit is a small, blackberry-like drupe.
Europium is a chemical element with the symbol Eu and atomic number 63. It was isolated in 1901 and is named after the continent of Europe.

Eurycoma longifolia is a tall, slender plant that can grow up to 20 feet in height. The leaves are long and narrow, and the flowers are small and white. The fruit of the plant is a small, black berry.

The Eustachian tube is a small passageway that connects the back of the nose to the middle ear. It helps to equalize the pressure in the middle ear and drain fluid from the ear. Eustachian tube dysfunction (ETD) occurs when the Eustachian tube does not open or close properly. This can cause a feeling of fullness or pressure in the ear, muffled hearing, and pain.

The Evodia plant is a small tree that can grow to about 15 feet tall. It has dark green leaves and small white flowers. The fruit of the Evodia plant is a small, red berry.

Exercise-induced asthma is a condition in which the airways narrow and swell and produce extra mucus during or after exercise. This can cause wheezing, coughing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath.

Exercise-induced dehydration is a condition where the body loses more fluids than it takes in during physical activity. This can lead to dehydration, which can cause symptoms like thirst, fatigue, and cramps.

Exercise-induced hypoxemia is a condition in which the blood oxygen level drops during exercise. This can be due to a number of factors, including the body's inability to properly use oxygen during exercise, or to an increase in the amount of carbon dioxide in the blood.

Exercise-induced muscle damage (EIMD) is a condition that can occur when muscles are subjected to unaccustomed or excessive exercise. The condition is characterized by muscle soreness, stiffness, and weakness. EIMD can occur in both novice and experienced athletes.

Exercise-induced muscle soreness is a condition that can occur after strenuous exercise. Symptoms may include muscle pain, stiffness, and swelling. Treatment typically involves rest, ice, and over-the-counter pain medications.

Exercise-induced respiratory infections are a type of infection that can occur after strenuous exercise. These infections can cause symptoms such as coughing, wheezing, and difficulty breathing. In some cases, exercise-induced respiratory infections can lead to more serious health problems, such as pneumonia.
Exfoliative cheilitis is a condition that causes the lips to become dry, cracked, and peeling. It can be painful and may make it difficult to eat or drink.
Expressive therapies are a form of psychotherapy that uses the arts or other creative outlets to help people express their emotions and address psychological issues.

Extravasation is a medical emergency that occurs when intravenous (IV) fluids or medications leak out of the vein and into the surrounding tissue. This can cause pain, swelling, and tissue damage. If not treated immediately, extravasation can lead to serious complications, such as tissue necrosis (death) and sepsis (a potentially life-threatening infection).
Eye trauma is an injury to the eye that can result in severe vision problems or even blindness. It can occur due to a variety of causes, including accidents, sports injuries, and violence.

The Eyebright plant is a small, annual herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It has a slender, erect stem and small, white flowers that grow in clusters. The leaves are lance-shaped and the plant produces a small, black fruit. Eyebright is commonly used in herbal medicine as an astringent and anti-inflammatory agent.
Facening is the process of preparing a surface for finishing by removing irregularities and creating a smooth, level surface.

Fadogia agrestis is a plant in the Rubiaceae family. It is native to Africa and has been used traditionally in herbal medicine. The plant is a small shrub with green leaves and white flowers. The fruit of the plant is a small, red berry.

This False Unicorn plant is a perennial herb that is native to North America. It grows to a height of 2-3 feet and has dark green, lance-shaped leaves. The flowers are small and white, and they bloom in the summer. The fruit is a small, black berry.

Familial Dysautonomia is a rare genetic disorder that affects the autonomic nervous system. The autonomic nervous system controls involuntary functions of the body such as blood pressure, heart rate, digestion, and sweating. People with Familial Dysautonomia have problems with these functions and often experience symptoms such as lightheadedness, fainting, nausea, and vomiting. There is no cure for Familial Dysautonomia, but treatments can help manage the symptoms.
Familial Hypercholesterolemia is an inherited disorder that causes high levels of cholesterol in the blood. This can lead to early heart disease and death.

Familial hypophosphatemia is a genetic disorder that results in low levels of phosphate in the blood. Phosphate is a mineral that is essential for many body processes, including the development and maintenance of bones and teeth, muscle contraction, and cell signaling. Individuals with familial hypophosphatemia may have skeletal abnormalities, muscle weakness, and/or developmental delays. The severity of the condition varies from person to person. There is no cure for familial hypophosphatemia, but treatment can help manage symptoms and prevent complications.

Familial Mediterranean Fever (FMF) is a rare, inherited autoinflammatory disorder characterized by recurrent episodes of fever and inflammation in the abdomen, chest, or joints. FMF is caused by mutations in the MEFV gene, which encodes the protein pyrin. Pyrin is a key regulator of the inflammatory response, and mutations in the MEFV gene lead to uncontrolled inflammation. FMF is most common in people of Mediterranean descent, and the disorder is typically diagnosed in childhood. There is no cure for FMF, but treatments are available to manage the symptoms and prevent complications.

FSP is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system. It is characterized by muscle weakness and stiffness (spasticity). FSP is caused by mutations in the genes that encode for the proteins involved in the nervous system. These mutations can be passed down from generation to generation. There is no cure for FSP, but there are treatments that can help manage the symptoms.

Fanconi syndrome is a rare disorder that affects the kidneys and the bones. It is characterized by the inability of the kidneys to reabsorb certain nutrients, such as glucose and amino acids, from the urine back into the bloodstream. This results in the loss of these nutrients in the urine. Additionally, Fanconi syndrome can cause bone abnormalities, such as osteoporosis.
Fasciolosis is a parasitic disease caused by the fluke Fasciola hepatica. Symptoms include abdominal pain, diarrhea, and jaundice. If left untreated, the disease can lead to liver failure.

Fat redistribution syndrome (FRS) is a condition that can occur in people who are taking certain antiretroviral medications for the treatment of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection. FRS is characterized by a build-up of fat in areas of the body where it is not typically found, such as the neck, breasts, and back, and a loss of fat from other areas, such as the face, arms, and legs. FRS can also cause changes in body shape and size, as well as other symptoms, such as fatigue and joint pain.

The Fat Smash Diet is a weight loss program that is divided into four phases. The first phase is a nine-day detox phase that is followed by a three-week maintenance phase. The second phase is a two-week weight-loss phase, and the third phase is a four-week maintenance phase. The fourth and final phase is a lifelong maintenance phase.

The Fear Of Flying health condition is a phobia that is characterized by an intense fear of flying. This phobia can cause a person to experience a range of symptoms, including anxiety, panic, and avoidance.
A febrile seizure is a seizure that occurs in children when they have a fever.

Fecal incontinence is the inability to control one's bowel movements, resulting in involuntary soiling. The condition may be caused by a variety of factors, including muscle or nerve damage, anal or rectal surgery, or constipation. Fecal incontinence can be a debilitating condition that can cause great embarrassment and social isolation.
The Feingold Diet is a diet that eliminates foods that contain artificial colors, flavors, and preservatives.
The Feldenkrais Method is a system of physical movement and mental exercises designed to improve human functioning by increasing awareness of the body and improving coordination and movement.

Feng Shui is a Chinese philosophical system of harmonizing everyone with their surrounding environment. It is based on the idea that everything in a person's surrounding environment affects their energy flow, which in turn affects their mood and overall well-being.

Fennel is a perennial herb with a tall, green stem and feathery leaves. The leaves are used to flavor soups and stews, and the stem can be eaten raw or cooked. Fennel has a sweet, anise-like flavor and is often used in Italian and French cuisine.

Fenofibrate (Tricor)-induced hyperhomocysteinemia is a health condition characterized by high levels of homocysteine in the blood. Fenofibrate is a medication used to treat high cholesterol and triglyceride levels. This condition can increase the risk for heart disease and stroke.

Fermium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Fm and atomic number 100. It is the heaviest element that can be formed by neutron bombardment of lighter elements, and hence the last element that can be prepared in macroscopic quantities.
Ferulic acid is a plant-based compound that has been shown to have antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anticancer properties.

FASD is a range of conditions that can occur in a person whose mother drank alcohol during pregnancy. FASD is the leading known cause of preventable mental and physical birth defects in the United States.

Fetal and premature infant mortality is the death of a fetus or premature infant before the age of one. The cause of death may be due to a number of factors, including congenital anomalies, pregnancy complications, or neonatal complications.

Fetal bone mineralization is a health condition where the bones of a fetus do not develop properly. This can lead to a number of problems, including deformities, fractures, and problems with the nervous system.

Fever Bark is a small tree that grows to about 15 feet tall. The leaves are oblong and have a smooth margin. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a small, red berry.
Ficin is a proteolytic enzyme that is obtained from the latex of the fig tree. It is used to treat various conditions, including warts and cancer.

The scabious plant is a member of the daisy family and is native to Europe. It is a herbaceous perennial that grows to a height of 30-60 cm. The leaves are opposite, lanceolate, and have a toothed margin. The flowers are white with a yellow center and are borne in clusters. The plant blooms from June to August.

The Figwort is a perennial herb that grows to a height of 2-3 feet. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are small and tubular. The flowers are borne in clusters and are typically white or pink in color. The fruit is a small, blackberry-like drupe.
A fir is a coniferous tree in the genus Abies.

Fireweed is a perennial herb in the rose family that is native to North America, Europe, and Asia. It gets its name from the fact that it often grows in areas that have been burned by wildfires. The plant has long, thin leaves and small pink or white flowers that bloom in the summer. Fireweed is often used as an ornamental plant in gardens.
Fish oils are oils that are extracted from fish. They are a source of omega-3 fatty acids, which are beneficial for human health.
Flatulence is the release of gas from the stomach through the nose and mouth. The gas is made up of food, bacteria, and air.

Flavonoids are a class of phytonutrients (plant chemicals) found in almost all fruits and vegetables. They are what give fruits and vegetables their vibrant colors. Flavonoids are also found in tea, red wine, and dark chocolate.

Flerovium is a superheavy artificial chemical element with an atomic number of 114. The name "flerovium" was proposed by the discoverers in honor of the Soviet nuclear physicist Georgy Flyorov.
Fluoride is a mineral that is found in many foods and in water. Fluoride helps to keep teeth healthy and strong.
Fluorine is a chemical element with the symbol F and atomic number 9. It is the lightest halogen and exists as a highly toxic pale yellow diatomic gas at standard conditions.
Fluorosis is a health condition that is caused by exposure to too much fluoride. Symptoms include white spots on the teeth, bone pain, and joint stiffness.

The fly agaric mushroom is a large, white mushroom with red spots. It is found in woods and fields in Europe and North America. The mushroom is poisonous to humans and can cause vomiting, diarrhea, and even death.

Folate deficiency is a health condition where there is not enough folate in the body. Folate is a water-soluble vitamin and is found in leafy green vegetables, legumes, nuts, and fortified foods. There is no one answer to this question as the description of a foot pain health condition will vary depending on the specific condition. However, some common symptoms of foot pain conditions include pain and discomfort in the feet, difficulty walking, and swelling.

This Frailty health condition is characterized by a loss of muscle mass and a decrease in the body's ability to produce new muscle. This can lead to weakness, fatigue, and a decrease in the ability to perform everyday activities.

Francium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Fr and atomic number 87. It used to be known as eka-caesium. It is the second-least electronegative element, behind only caesium, and is the second rarest naturally occurring element (after astatine).
Frankincense is a resin that is obtained from the Boswellia tree. It has a sweet, woody aroma and is used in incense, perfumes, and cosmetics.

Friedreich ataxia is a rare, inherited neurological disorder that causes progressive damage to the nervous system. Fringetree is a small deciduous tree that is native to eastern North America. It typically grows to a height of 15-20 feet and has a spreading canopy. Fructooligosaccharides (FOS) are short-chain carbohydrates that are found in a variety of fruits and vegetables. They are made up of fructose molecules that are bonded together. FOS are considered to be prebiotics, which means that they help promote the growth of healthy bacteria in the gut.

A fruit is a seed-bearing structure that develops from the ovary of a flowering plant. Fruits are the means by which angiosperms disseminate seeds. Edible fruits, in particular, have propagated with the movements of humans and animals in a symbiotic relationship as a means for seed dispersal and nutrition; in fact, humans and many animals have become dependent on fruits as a source of food.

Fulvic acid is a natural substance that is derived from decomposing organic matter. It is a brownish-yellow liquid that is rich in minerals and other nutrients. Fulvic acid has been used for centuries as a natural remedy for a variety of ailments.

The Fumitory plant is a small, annual herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It has a slender, branching stem that can grow up to 60 cm tall. Functional gastrointestinal disorders are a group of conditions that affect the gastrointestinal tract, including the esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine/colon, rectum, and anus. Furuncles are pus-filled bumps that form under the skin when hair follicles become infected. They are also known as boils. Boils can occur on the face, neck, armpits, buttocks, and thighs. Galactosemia is a rare genetic disorder that prevents the body from metabolizing galactose, a sugar found in milk and other dairy products. People with galactosemia cannot convert galactose to glucose, so it builds up in their blood and can damage their liver, kidneys, and brain.

Gallbladder cancer is a rare cancer that starts in the cells of the gallbladder. The gallbladder is a small, pear-shaped organ that stores bile, a digestive fluid that is produced by the liver.

The Gallbladder is a small organ located under the liver. It stores bile, which is produced by the liver, and releases it into the small intestine to help with the digestion of fats. Gallbladder disease is a general term used to describe any disorder that affects the gallbladder.

Gallium is a chemical element with the symbol Ga and atomic number 31. Gallium is a soft, silvery metal, and elemental gallium is a brittle solid at low temperatures, and a liquid at temperatures greater than 29.76 °C (85.57 °F).

Gallstones are small, hard deposits that form in the gallbladder. The gallbladder is a small, pear-shaped organ on the right side of the abdomen. The gallbladder stores bile, a yellowish-brown fluid that helps the body break down fat.

This Galphimia Glauca plant is a succulent that is native to Mexico. It has long, thin, green leaves that are arranged in a rosette pattern. Gamma-Hydroxybutyrate (GHB) is a central nervous system (CNS) depressant that is commonly referred to as a “club drug” or “date rape” drug. GHB is often used in combination with other drugs, such as alcohol, and has been associated with sexual assault.

Gamma-oryzanol is a natural substance found in rice bran oil. It is a mixture of plant sterols and ferulic acid esters. Gamma-oryzanol has been used in alternative medicine as a possibly effective aid in treating high cholesterol.

This Gardenia plant is a shrub that can grow to be about 6 feet tall. It has dark green, glossy leaves and white, fragrant flowers. The flowers bloom in the spring and summer.

Gastritis is a condition that occurs when the lining of the stomach becomes inflamed or irritated. The lining of the stomach is protected by a layer of mucus that helps to prevent the stomach acid from causing irritation. When this mucus layer is damaged, it can allow the stomach acid to come into contact with the lining of the stomach, causing inflammation. Gastritis can be caused by a number of different things, including infection, stress, and certain medications.
Gastroenteritis-induced nausea and vomiting is a condition in which the stomach and intestines are inflamed, causing nausea and vomiting.
Gastrointestinal bleeding is any bleeding that starts in the gastrointestinal tract. This bleeding may be visible as black stools, or it may be invisible, such as bleeding from a ulcer.
Gastrointestinal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the gastrointestinal tract, which includes the esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine, rectum, and anus.
Gastroparesis is a condition in which the stomach muscles are weak and do not work properly. This can cause the stomach contents to empty very slowly or not at all.

This Gelsemium plant is a climbing vine that can reach up to 30 feet in length. It has dark green, glossy leaves and small, yellow flowers that bloom in the spring and summer. The Gelsemium plant is native to the southeastern United States and is often used as an ornamental plant in gardens.

Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is an anxiety disorder that is characterized by excessive worry and anxiety that is difficult to control. People with GAD often have difficulty sleeping, and may experience symptoms such as muscle tension, irritability, and restlessness.

Gentian is a genus of flowering plants belonging to the family Gentianaceae. The genus name is derived from Gentius, an Illyrian king. The family Gentianaceae consists of about 90 genera and 1,750 species of flowering plants distributed throughout the world. Gentians typically have opposite, simple leaves and showy, trumpet-shaped flowers that are usually blue, but can also be white, yellow, or pink. The flowers are bisexual and zygomorphic, and the calyx is deeply 5-lobed. The corolla is tubular or funnel-shaped, and the Stamens are inserted near the base of the corolla tube. Gentians are found in a wide variety of habitats, including alpine and subalpine regions, woodlands, grasslands, and swamps.

This German Chamomile plant has small, daisy-like flowers that are white with a yellow center. The plant grows to about 2 feet tall and has a strong, sweet scent. Chamomile is native to Europe and Asia and has been used for centuries as a medicinal herb. Chamomile tea is made from the dried flowers and is used to treat a variety of ailments including anxiety, insomnia, and stomach upset.

This German Ipecac plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are white. Kearns-Sayre syndrome (KSS) is a rare disorder that affects many parts of the body. The most common features are problems with the eyes and heart. People with KSS often have a slow heart rate (bradycardia) and an abnormal heart rhythm (arrhythmia). They may also have trouble seeing in low light (nystagmus) and may go blind at an early age. KSS can also cause problems with the nervous system, muscles, and other organs.

Keloids are raised, thickened scars that form when the body overproduces collagen in the healing process. They can occur after any type of skin injury, including burns, acne, piercings, and vaccinations. Keloids can be itchy, painful, and unsightly.
Keratin is a protein that is found in the outer layer of skin, hair, and nails. It helps to protect these tissues from damage.

A ketogenic diet is a high-fat, adequate-protein, low-carbohydrate diet that in medicine is used primarily to treat difficult-to-control (refractory) epilepsy in children. The diet forces the body to burn fats rather than carbohydrates. Normally, the carbohydrates contained in food are converted into glucose, which is then transported around the body and is particularly important in fueling brain function. However, if there is very little carbohydrate in the diet, the liver converts fat into fatty acids and ketone bodies. The ketone bodies pass into the brain and replace glucose as an energy source. An elevated level of ketone bodies in the blood, a state known as ketosis, leads to a reduction in the frequency of epileptic seizures.

The Khat plant is a small, evergreen shrub that grows to a height of 2-3 m. The leaves are simple, opposite, and oblong-shaped with a serrated margin. The flowers are small, white, and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, black berry.
Kidney cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the cells of the kidney. The two most common types of kidney cancer are renal cell cancer and transitional cell cancer.

Kidney stones are small, hard deposits that form in the kidney. They are made up of minerals and acid salts and can vary in size from a grain of sand to a pea. Kidney stones can cause severe pain and can lead to kidney damage or infection.
Kidney transplant-related bone loss is a condition in which the bones become weaker and more fragile due to the loss of kidney function. This can lead to fractures and other problems.
Kinetin is a plant hormone that promotes cell division and cell growth.
Kirlian photography is a type of photography that captures the aura or life force of an object.
The kiwi is a flightless bird that is native to New Zealand.

Klinefelter syndrome is a condition that affects males. It is caused by the presence of an extra X chromosome in the cells. Males with Klinefelter syndrome often have difficulty with reading and writing. They may also have problems with social skills and may be taller than average.

Knee joint pain is a common condition that can be caused by a variety of factors. The pain may be localized to the knee joint or may radiate to other areas of the body. Joint pain is often accompanied by swelling, stiffness, and decreased range of motion.

Fallopia japonica, commonly known as Asian knotweed or Japanese knotweed, is a large, herbaceous perennial plant of the knotweed and buckwheat family Polygonaceae. It is native to East Asia in Japan, China and Korea. In North America and Europe the species is very successful as an invasive species and it is considered a noxious weed or even a invasive species. The species is a rhizomatous perennial herb that forms large clumps. The leaves are broad oval with a truncate base and slightly cordate apex, 7–14 cm long and 5–12 cm broad, with an entire margin. The flowers are small, cream or white, produced in erect racemes 6–15 cm long in late summer and early autumn. The fruit is a small winged nut that is dispersed by the wind.
Koch's Glycoside is a natural plant compound that has been shown to have anti-cancer properties. It is found in the leaves of the plant Camellia sinensis, which is also known as the tea plant.
Kohlrabi is a vegetable that is part of the cabbage family. It is a round, bulbous vegetable that has a light green or white color. The taste of kohlrabi is similar to that of a cabbage or broccoli.

The kola nut is the fruit of the kola tree, a species in the Sterculiaceae family. The tree is native to the tropical rainforests of Africa. The kola nut has a bitter taste and contains caffeine. It is chewed as a stimulant and is also used in traditional medicine.
Kombucha is a fermented tea drink that is said to have many health benefits.
The Korean Pine is a species of pine that is native to Korea and northeastern China.

Kousso (Hagenia abyssinica) is a flowering plant in the family Brassicaceae. It is native to Ethiopia, Kenya, and Somalia. The leaves are used to make a tea which is used as a traditional medicine for a variety of conditions including malaria, diarrhea, and stomachache. The plant is also used as a natural insecticide.

Krebiozen is a drug that was developed in the 1950s as a possible treatment for cancer. It is derived from a compound found in the urine of horses. Early clinical trials showed promise, but later studies were unable to replicate these results. Krebiozen is no longer used as a cancer treatment.

Krypton is a chemical element with the symbol Kr and atomic number 36. It is a colorless, odorless, tasteless noble gas that occurs in trace amounts in the atmosphere and is often used with other noble gases in fluorescent lamps.

L-Carnitine is an amino acid that is essential for the transport and breakdown of fats in the body. A deficiency of this amino acid can lead to a build-up of fat in the liver and muscles, and can also cause problems with heart function.

L-Ornithine-L-Aspartate (L-O-L-A) is a dipeptide of the amino acids ornithine and aspartate. It is a white, powdery substance that is soluble in water. L-O-L-A is used as a dietary supplement and is claimed to have a variety of health benefits, including reducing fatigue, improving mental function, and aiding in weight loss.
Labdanum is a sticky resin that is produced by the leaves and twigs of certain Mediterranean shrubs. It is used in perfumes and as a flavoring agent.
Labor pain is the pain that a woman experiences during childbirth. It is caused by the stretching and contractions of the uterus during labor.
Laburnum is a genus of two species of small trees in the subfamily Faboideae of the pea family Fabaceae. The species are native to the mountains of central Europe.
Lactase is an enzyme that breaks down lactose, a sugar found in milk and other dairy products.

Lacticaseibacillus casei is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the Lactobacillaceae family. This bacterium is known to produce lactic acid, and has been isolated from dairy products and the human gastrointestinal tract.

Lacticaseibacillus paracasei is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the Firmicutes. L. paracasei is a lactic acid bacterium that is used in the food industry for its ability to produce lactic acid. L. paracasei is also used as a probiotic to promote gut health.

Lacticaseibacillus rhamnosus is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, non-spore-forming bacterium. L. rhamnosus is a homofermentative bacterium, meaning that it produces lactic acid as its primary end product of fermentation.

Lactiplantibacillus pentosus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the Lactobacillaceae family. This bacterium is found in the gastrointestinal tract of humans and animals. Lactiplantibacillus plantarum is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the Lactobacillaceae family. This bacterium is found in the plantar surface of the foot and is a normal inhabitant of the human gastrointestinal tract. Lactobacillus acidophilus is a type of bacteria that is commonly found in the gut. These bacteria are important for maintaining a healthy gut flora.

Lactobacillus crispatus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a member of the Lactobacillus genus. L. crispatus is found in the vaginal microbiota of healthy women and is thought to play a role in maintaining vaginal health.

Lactobacillus delbrueckii is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is typically found in the gastrointestinal tract. L. delbrueckii is used in the production of yogurt, cheese, and other fermented dairy products.

Lactobacillus gasseri is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is typically found in the human gastrointestinal tract. L. gasseri has been shown to have several health benefits, including weight loss, improved digestion, and reduced inflammation.

Lactobacillus helveticus is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is typically found in the gastrointestinal tract. L. helveticus is used in the production of Swiss-type cheeses. It is also used as a probiotic to promote gut health.

Lactobacillus jensenii is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is non-spore-forming and non-motile. This bacterium is a normal inhabitant of the human gastrointestinal tract and is also found in the vaginal microbiota.
Lactobacillus johnsonii is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is a normal inhabitant of the human gastrointestinal tract.
Lactoferrin is a protein found in milk and other bodily fluids that helps to fight infection. It is a part of the immune system.

Lactose intolerance is a condition in which people have difficulty digesting lactose, a sugar found in milk and other dairy products. People with lactose intolerance are unable to break down lactose into simpler sugars, so it stays in the intestine and causes gas, bloating, and other symptoms.

The Lady Fern is a perennial plant that grows in moist, shady areas. It has a rhizome root system and produces fronds that can reach up to three feet in length. (Galium verum)  Lady's Bedstraw is a perennial herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the Rubiaceae family and grows to a height of 30-60 cm (12-24 in). Lamellar ichthyosis is a rare, genetic skin disorder that is present at birth. The skin is thick and scaly, and the scales are large and plate-like. Lanthanum is a chemical element with the symbol La and atomic number 57. It is a soft, ductile, silvery-white metal that tarnishes rapidly when exposed to air and is soft enough to be cut with a knife.

This Larch Arabinogalactan plant extract is a brown powder that is derived from the inner bark of the larch tree. It is a source of dietary fiber and is commonly used as a food additive or dietary supplement.

Laryngeal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the larynx, or voice box. The larynx is a small, tube-like organ in the throat that helps to produce sound. Laryngeal cancer can cause problems with speaking, swallowing, and breathing. It is most often diagnosed in people over the age of 55.

Laser skin resurfacing is a cosmetic procedure that uses a laser to improve the appearance of your skin. It can be used to treat wrinkles, fine lines, acne scars, and other skin imperfections.
This Lathyrus plant is a climbing vine that can grow up to 10 feet in length. The leaves are dark green and the flowers are white or pink. The plant blooms in the spring and summer.

Latilactobacillus sakei is a species of lactic acid bacteria. It is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacterium that is typically found in fermented foods. L. sakei is used in the production of sake, a Japanese rice wine. It is also used as a probiotic to promote gut health.
This is a Laurelwood plant. It is an evergreen shrub that can grow up to 10 feet tall. It has dark green leaves and produces small white flowers.

Lawrencium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Lr and atomic number 103. The definition of lead is a metal that is very poisonous and is used in making bullets and other things.

Lead toxicity is a health condition caused by exposure to lead. Lead is a heavy metal that can be found in the environment, in certain products, and in the body. Leber hereditary optic neuropathy (LHON) is a rare, inherited form of vision loss that affects the optic nerve. The optic nerve is the bundle of nerve fibers that transmits visual information from the eye to the brain. LHON typically affects young adults and is characterized by a sudden, painless loss of central vision. In some cases, LHON can lead to complete blindness. There is no known cure for LHON, but treatment options are available to help improve vision and prevent further vision loss.

Leg cramps are sudden, often painful spasms of the muscles in the leg. They can occur in the calf, foot, or thigh. Leg cramps are usually harmless and go away on their own. However, they can be a sign of an underlying medical condition.
A legume is a plant in the family Fabaceae (or Leguminosae), or the fruit or seed of such a plant.

Leishmania lesions are skin ulcers that are caused by the Leishmania parasite. The ulcers are typically red and raised, and they may be painful. They can occur on any part of the body, but they are most common on the legs and arms.
A lemon is a citrus fruit that is used to add flavor to food or to make a drink more refreshing.

The lemon eucalyptus is a fast-growing tree that can reach up to 50 feet in height. The tree has a straight trunk with smooth, gray bark. This is a small, woody shrub that typically grows to 3-6’ tall and as wide. It is native to the Mediterranean region. It has ovate, toothed, green leaves that are aromatic when crushed. Lepidium meyenii, also known as maca or Peruvian ginseng, is a root vegetable that is native to the high Andes of Peru. The Lesser Celandine is a small, low-growing plant that is native to Europe and Asia. It has dark green, heart-shaped leaves and small, yellow flowers that bloom in the spring. The plant is often found in damp, shady areas and is considered an invasive species in some parts of the world.
Leucine is an essential amino acid that is necessary for protein synthesis.
Leukemia is a cancer of the blood cells. It starts in the bone marrow, the soft tissue inside most bones.

Leukopenia is a condition in which there is a decrease in the number of white blood cells in the blood. White blood cells are responsible for fighting infection, so a decrease in their number can make a person more susceptible to infection.

Levetiracetam-induced side effects are a group of symptoms that may occur in people taking the medication levetiracetam. These side effects can include dizziness, headache, nausea, and fatigue. While these side effects are typically mild, they can be bothersome for some people.
