Lichen planus is a chronic inflammatory skin condition that results in the development of small, itchy bumps on the skin. The bumps are typically purple in color and may be accompanied by thin, white lines. The condition can also affect the nails, scalp, and mucous membranes.

Lichen sclerosus is a chronic, inflammatory skin condition that most often affects the vulva in women. It can also affect the penis and scrotum in men, and the skin around the anus. In rare cases, it can affect other parts of the body, such as the upper thighs, breasts, or upper arms. The cause of lichen sclerosus is unknown, but it is thought to be an autoimmune disorder. The condition causes the skin to thin and develop white patches. It can also cause the formation of small, painful blisters. Lichen sclerosus can be treated with topical corticosteroids, but the condition can recur.
The definition of licorice is a plant that is native to southern Europe and Asia and that is used to flavor food and candy.
Ligandrol is a selective androgen receptor modulator (SARM) that is popular among bodybuilders and athletes for its ability to promote muscle growth and increase strength.
Ligilactobacillus salivarius is a species of Gram-positive, lactic acid-producing bacterium in the genus Ligilactobacillus. It is a commensal of the human oral cavity and gastrointestinal tract.

Lily-of-the-valley is a low-growing, spreading plant that produces small, white, bell-shaped flowers. The flowers are borne on slender stems that arise from a cluster of basal leaves. Lime is a calcium-containing inorganic material in which carbonates, oxides, and hydroxides predominate. In the strict sense of the term, lime is calcium oxide or calcium hydroxide. Lion's Mane Mushroom is an edible mushroom that has a long, shaggy white cap and a thick stem. It is native to North America and Europe, and its scientific name is Hericium erinaceus.

Lobelia is a genus of flowering plants that includes more than 400 species. The vast majority of these are herbaceous annuals or perennials, but a few are woody shrubs. Logwood is a tropical hardwood tree native to Central America. The tree produces a dark red heartwood that is used in a variety of applications, including as a dye, wood stain, and natural insecticide.

Lometrexol Toxicity is a condition where a person has a high level of lometrexol in their body. This can be caused by taking too much of the drug, or by taking it for a long period of time. Lysine is an essential amino acid that is necessary for the growth and development of many tissues in the body. It is also important for the production of enzymes and hormones.

Lysinuric protein intolerance (LPI) is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the way the body processes certain amino acids. Amino acids are the building blocks of proteins. Adiantum capillus-veneris is a species of fern known by the common names southern maidenhair fern, black maidenhair fern, and Venus hair fern. Maitake mushrooms are a type of edible fungi that have a long history of use in traditional Chinese and Japanese cuisine. These mushrooms are prized for their unique flavor and purported health benefits, which include boosting immunity, reducing inflammation, and aiding in weight loss.

Malabar Nut is a large, evergreen tree that can grow up to 30 m tall. The leaves are dark green and glossy, and the flowers are white or pale pink. Male infertility is a condition in which a man is unable to father a child. It may be due to a problem with the man's sperm.
Male sexual dysfunction is a health condition that can affect a man's ability to have or maintain an erection. It can also affect his ability to ejaculate.
Malic acid is a dicarboxylic acid that is found in many fruits and vegetables. It is used as a food additive and has a sour taste.

Malignant pleural effusions are a buildup of fluid in the space between the lungs and the chest wall. This can happen when cancer cells grow in the pleura, the thin layer of tissue that covers the lungs. The cancer cells can block the drainage of fluid from the pleura, causing the fluid to build up.

The Mallow plant is a small, herbaceous plant that is native to Europe, Asia, and Africa. It is a member of the Malvaceae family and its scientific name is Malva sylvestris. The Mallow plant has a taproot system and its leaves are alternate, simple, and lobed. The flowers are small and white, and they bloom in the summer. The Mallow plant is used for its medicinal properties and is also grown as an ornamental plant.
Malnourishment-related diarrhea is a health condition characterized by chronic diarrhea that is caused by a lack of nutrients in the diet. This can lead to severe dehydration and weight loss.

This Malva sylvestris plant is a herbaceous perennial that is native to Europe, Asia, and Africa. It has a spreading habit and can grow to a height of 2-3 feet. The leaves are ovate to lanceolate in shape and are green to dark green in color. The flowers are pink to purple in color and are borne in clusters. The fruit is a schizocarp that is brown to black in color.
Mammalian proteins are a class of proteins that are found in mammals. These proteins are involved in a variety of functions, including cell signaling, cell adhesion, and cell cycle control.
This plant is a small shrub that typically grows to around 2-3 feet tall. It has small, dark green leaves and white flowers that bloom in the summer. The flowers are followed by small, dark berries.

This Manchurian Thorn plant is a deciduous shrub that can grow up to 6 feet tall. It has dark green leaves that are 3-5 inches long and 2-3 inches wide. The leaves are serrated and have a leathery texture. The flowers are white and grow in clusters. The fruit is a blackberry-like drupe that is 1-2 cm in diameter.
Mantra meditation is a type of meditation that involves the repetition of a mantra, or a word or phrase, to focus the mind and achieve a state of relaxation.

There is no formal definition of the Maple Syrup Diet, but it generally refers to a diet plan that involves consuming maple syrup as a main source of calories and nutrients. Some versions of the diet also require participants to consume large amounts of water and lemon juice, and to avoid solid foods altogether.

Maple syrup urine disease is a rare inherited disorder in which the body is unable to process certain proteins. This results in the accumulation of abnormal amounts of certain amino acids in the blood and urine, which gives the urine a characteristic "maple syrup" odor.
The maqui plant is a small shrub that is native to Chile and Argentina. It has small, dark green leaves and produces small, black berries. The berries are often used to make jams and jellies.

Maral root is a perennial herb that grows in the mountains of Central Asia. The root is large and fleshy, and can grow up to two feet long. It is typically harvested in the fall, and is used fresh or dried. Maral root has a sweet, earthy flavor, and is often used in traditional medicine. It is said to have many health benefits, including the ability to improve circulation, boost immunity, and relieve stress. Maral root is also sometimes used as an aphrodisiac.
Marijuana withdrawal is a set of symptoms that can occur when a person stops using marijuana. These symptoms can include irritability, anxiety, and difficulty sleeping.

Marjoram is a perennial herb that is native to the Mediterranean region. It is a member of the mint family and has a strong, sweet, and slightly minty flavor. Marjoram is often used in Mediterranean and French cuisine. It is also used in herbal medicine.

(Liatris spicata)  This Marsh Blazing Star plant is a perennial herb that grows up to 3 feet tall. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are pink or purple. The plant blooms in late summer to early fall.

(Rhododendron tomentosum)  The Marsh Labrador Tea plant is a small shrub that typically grows to between 2 and 4 feet in height. It has dark green, leathery leaves that are covered in a dense layer of white fuzz. The plant produces small, white flowers in the springtime. The Marsh Labrador Tea is native to North America and can be found growing in wetland areas in the northern United States and Canada.
The Marsh Marigold is a plant that is found in marshes and other wet areas. It has yellow flowers that bloom in the spring. The plant is also known as the Caltha palustris.

The Marshmallow plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to 2 meters tall. The leaves are ovate-shaped and the flowers are white. The plant is native to Europe, but can now be found in North America and Asia. The Marshmallow plant is used to make marshmallows, as well as a variety of other sweets and desserts.

Achillea millefolium, commonly known as yarrow or common yarrow, is a flowering plant in the family Asteraceae. It is native to temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere in Asia, Europe, and North America.

The Mastic plant is a small, evergreen shrub that is native to the Mediterranean region. It has small, dark green leaves and produces small, white flowers. The plant is used to produce a resin called mastic, which is used in a variety of products, including chewing gum, cosmetics, and food.

Mastitis is a condition that results when the milk ducts in the breast become blocked and inflamed. This can happen when a woman is breastfeeding, but it can also occur in women who are not breastfeeding. Mastitis can cause a woman's breast to feel hot, swollen, and painful. It can also cause fever, chills, and body aches.

Mastocytosis is a rare disorder that occurs when there is an abnormal buildup of mast cells in the body. Mast cells are a type of white blood cell that is involved in allergic reactions and plays a role in the immune system. Mastocytosis can cause a variety of symptoms, including skin rashes, abdominal pain, diarrhea, and fatigue. In some cases, mastocytosis can be life-threatening. There is no cure for mastocytosis, but treatment can help to manage the symptoms.

column1: Maternally Inherited Diabetes Mellitus And Deafness (MIDD)
column2: Maternally Inherited Diabetes Mellitus And Deafness (MIDD) is a condition that is passed down from mother to child. It is characterized by diabetes mellitus (high blood sugar) and deafness.

Mcardle disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the muscles. People with this condition have problems breaking down a substance called glycogen, which is stored in the muscles. This can lead to muscle weakness and cramping.
Meats are the edible flesh of animals.
Medications taken by mouth are drugs that are swallowed and absorbed into the bloodstream through the lining of the gastrointestinal tract.
There are many different types of medications used for lowering cholesterol. Some of the most common include statins, bile acid sequestrants, and niacin.

The Mediterranean diet is a diet inspired by the eating habits of Greece, Southern Italy, and Spain. The diet emphasizes fresh, whole foods such as fruits, vegetables, whole grains, legumes, and olive oil.
Meitnerium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Mt and atomic number 109. It is an extremely radioactive metal that has only been produced in minuscule quantities.

Melanoma is a type of skin cancer that begins in melanocytes, the skin cells that produce pigment. Melanoma can occur on any skin surface, but it is most likely to develop on the face, neck, or legs. Melanoma is the most serious type of skin cancer and can be fatal if it is not detected early and treated.

Melasma is a common skin condition that causes brown or gray patches on the face. Most people get it on their cheeks, nose, forehead, or chin. It's more common in women than men, and it often happens to people with darker skin. Melasma is not harmful, but it can be hard to get rid of.

Membranous nephropathy is a kidney disease that occurs when the thin layer of tissue that separates the blood from the urine in the kidney (the renal membrane) becomes thick and inflamed. This can lead to kidney damage and, in some cases, kidney failure.

Mendelevium is a synthetic element with the symbol Md (formerly Mv) and atomic number 101. It is the first element of the transuranium series and was synthesized by bombarding einsteinium with alpha particles.
Meniere disease is a disorder of the inner ear that can cause vertigo, tinnitus, hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or pressure in the ear.

Meningitis is a serious infection of the meninges, the thin lining that surrounds the brain and spinal cord. It can be caused by bacteria, viruses, or other organisms. Meningitis can lead to brain damage, hearing loss, or death.

Menorrhagia is a health condition characterized by heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding. Bleeding may last for more than 7 days and be so heavy that you have to change your pad or tampon every 2 hours or less. Menorrhagia can also cause anemia (low iron levels in the blood).

Mentabolan is a naturally occurring steroid hormone that is produced in the body. It is responsible for the development and maintenance of male sexual characteristics. It also plays a role in the production of red blood cells and the regulation of metabolism.

Mercury is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are white or pink. The plant is native to Europe and Asia and has been introduced to North America. Mercury is sometimes used as an herbal remedy for skin conditions and as a diuretic.

Mercury is a heavy metal that is found in the environment. It can be released into the air, water, and soil. It can also be found in some products, such as certain types of light bulbs, thermometers, and dental fillings. Mercury can be harmful to your health if you are exposed to it.

Mesoglycan is a complex molecule composed of a protein core with attached chains of alternating sugars. It is found in the connective tissues of animals and is thought to play a role in the organization of these tissues.

Metabolic-Associated Fatty Liver Disease (MAFLD) is a health condition associated with the accumulation of fat in the liver. This accumulation of fat can lead to liver damage and eventually liver failure. MAFLD is often seen in people who are obese or have diabetes.
This health condition is characterized by a pattern of methamphetamine use that leads to significant impairment or distress.

Methicillin-Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus (MRSA) is a type of bacteria that is resistant to antibiotics. MRSA can cause infections in the skin, lungs, and blood. MRSA is often spread through contact with contaminated surfaces or through contact with an infected person.

Methotrexate Toxicity is a condition caused by the overuse of the drug methotrexate. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal pain. If left untreated, methotrexate toxicity can lead to liver damage and death.

Methoxydienone is a synthetic anabolic-androgenic steroid (AAS) and a derivative of dihydrotestosterone (DHT). It was first described in the 1960s and was used for medical purposes until the 1980s. Methoxydienone is no longer used medically, but it is still used by bodybuilders and athletes for its anabolic effects.

Methoxylated flavones are a class of flavonoids that have a methoxy group attached to the 2-position of the flavone backbone. These compounds are found in a variety of plants, and have been shown to have a variety of biological activities, including antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anticancer activity.
Methyldiazinol is a synthetic organic compound with the chemical formula C4H6N2. It is a white solid that is used as a reagent in organic synthesis.

Methylliberine is a chemical compound that is structurally similar to the neurotransmitter dopamine. It is found in a variety of plants, including the coffee plant. Methylliberine has been shown to increase levels of dopamine in the brain, and it is thought to have similar effects on the body as caffeine.

Methylsulfonylmethane (MSM) is a naturally occurring sulfur compound found in plants, animals, and humans. It is often used as a dietary supplement for its purported health benefits, which include relief from joint pain and inflammation.
Methylsynephrine is a stimulant drug of the phenethylamine and amphetamine chemical classes. It is a positional isomer of synephrine, and occurs naturally in some citrus fruits.

The Mezereon plant is a small, deciduous shrub that is native to Europe and Asia. It typically grows to a height of 2-3 feet and has small, greenish-yellow flowers that bloom in the spring. The Mezereon plant is poisonous and can cause skin irritation if handled.
Microangiopathy is a condition where the small blood vessels in the body become damaged. This can lead to a variety of problems, including organ damage, stroke, and heart attack.

Microscopic colitis is a condition that causes inflammation in the colon. The inflammation is seen when the colon is looked at under a microscope. There are two types of microscopic colitis: lymphocytic colitis and collagenous colitis.
Migraine headaches are a type of headache that can cause severe pain, nausea, and vomiting. They are often accompanied by auras, which are visual or sensory disturbances.

Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) is a health condition in which a person has problems with memory, language, or thinking. MCI is not a disease, but it may be a sign of a future dementia, such as Alzheimer's disease.
This is a health condition characterized by bleeding that is not heavy or continuous.
A miracle fruit is a fruit that has the ability to change the way that other foods taste. For example, a sour food may taste sweet after eating a miracle fruit.
A miscarriage is the loss of a pregnancy before the 20th week.
A mitochondrial cytopathy is a type of disease that affects the mitochondria, which are the parts of cells that convert energy from food into a form that cells can use.

Mitochondrial myopathies are a group of muscle disorders caused by dysfunctional mitochondria. The mitochondria are responsible for generating energy in cells, and when they are not functioning properly, the cells cannot produce enough energy, leading to muscle weakness and other problems. There are many different types of mitochondrial myopathies, and symptoms can vary from person to person. Some people may only experience mild muscle weakness, while others may have more severe symptoms such as heart or respiratory problems. There is no cure for mitochondrial myopathies, but treatments are available to help manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

This Mitragyna Speciosa plant is a tropical evergreen tree in the coffee family (Rubiaceae) native to Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, and Papua New Guinea, where it has been used in traditional medicine since at least the 19th century. M. speciosa is a large tree that can grow up to 30 m (98 ft) tall with a trunk up to 2 m (6.6 ft) diameter. The leaves are dark green and glossy, with a shape that resembles a fan.
Mitral valve prolapse is a condition in which the valve between the left atrium and left ventricle of the heart doesn't close properly.

Molybdenum is a chemical element with the symbol Mo and atomic number 42. It is a silvery-white metal with a grayish tint, has the sixth-highest melting point of any element, and can withstand high temperatures.

Molybdenum is a mineral that is found in food. It is needed for the body to make enzymes that are important in many chemical processes in the body. A molybdenum deficiency can cause problems with these enzymes and lead to health problems.
(Bacopa monnieri)  Bacopa monnieri is a small, creeping herb that is native to India. It has small, white flowers and is often used in Ayurvedic medicine.
Monolaurin is a compound derived from lauric acid, which is found in coconut oil. It is used as an antimicrobial agent.
A type of fat found in foods such as nuts and olive oil that is considered to be healthier than other types of fat.
The Monterey pine is a species of pine that is native to the central coast of California.

This Moringa plant is a small, evergreen tree that grows to a height of about 10 meters. It has a slender trunk with a smooth, gray bark. The leaves are simple and ovate, and the flowers are white and fragrant. The fruit is a small, brown capsule that contains a single seed.

(Ephedra viridis)  The Mormon Tea plant is a small, shrubby plant that grows to about 2 feet tall. It has small, greenish-yellow flowers and produces small, greenish-brown fruits. The leaves are small and scale-like, and the stems are green and slightly woody. Mormon Tea is native to the southwestern United States and northern Mexico, and is often found in dry, open areas.
Moscovium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Mc and atomic number 115.
A mosquito repellent is a substance that is applied to the skin, clothing, or other surfaces to keep mosquitoes from landing or climbing onto that surface.

Motherwort is a perennial herb that grows up to 3 feet tall. The leaves are opposite, oblong to lanceolate, and have toothed margins. The flowers are small, pink to purple, and borne in dense, terminal spikes. The fruit is a small, dry capsule.
A mountain ash is a tall tree with dark green leaves and red berries.
Mountain flax is a perennial herb in the family Linaceae. It is native to the mountains of Europe, Asia, and North America. The plant has blue or purple flowers and is used in herbal medicine.

The Mountain Laurel is a shrub that is native to the eastern United States. It is a member of the heath family and can grow to be 10 feet tall. The leaves are evergreen and have a leathery texture. The flowers are white and have a bell-shaped appearance. The fruit is a dark blue berry.

This Mouse-Ear Hawkweed is a perennial herb that grows to about 30 cm (12 in) tall. The leaves are oblong to lanceolate, and the flowers are yellow, borne in corymbs.  The Mouse-Ear Hawkweed is native to Europe, and has been introduced to North America.
Mouth cancer is a type of cancer that forms in the tissues of the mouth. It can occur on the tongue, gums, roof of the mouth, or inside the cheeks. Mouth cancer is also called oral cancer.

Mucositis is a condition that results in the inflammation and ulceration of the mucous membranes lining the digestive tract. The most common symptoms of mucositis include pain, diarrhea, and bleeding from the affected area. In severe cases, mucositis can lead to malnutrition and dehydration.

The Muira Puama plant is a small shrub that is native to the Amazon rainforest. It has long, thin leaves that are green in color. The flowers of this plant are white and have a strong, sweet fragrance. The fruit of the Muira Puama plant is a small, red berry.

This is a common mullein plant (Verbascum thapsus). It is a tall, erect plant with a woolly stem and leaves. The leaves are large and hairy, and the flowers are yellow and borne in a dense spike. Mullein is native to Europe and Asia, but has been introduced to North America. It is a common weed in fields and roadsides.
Multiple myeloma is a cancer of the plasma cells. Plasma cells are a type of white blood cell that is found in the bone marrow. Multiple myeloma is a cancer that starts in the plasma cells.

Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic, often disabling disease that attacks the central nervous system (CNS). The CNS consists of the brain, spinal cord, and optic nerves. Symptoms may be mild, such as numbness in the limbs, or severe, such as paralysis or loss of vision. The course of the disease is unpredictable, and its effects vary from person to person.

Multiple sclerosis-related fatigue is a type of fatigue that is experienced by people who have multiple sclerosis. This type of fatigue is different from other types of fatigue because it is often more severe and can last for a longer period of time. Additionally, people who experience multiple sclerosis-related fatigue often find it difficult to do everyday activities such as walking, dressing, and bathing.

Multisystem organ failure is a health condition in which multiple organs in the body fail to function properly. This can be caused by a variety of factors, including infection, trauma, and chronic illness. Treatment typically involves supporting the failing organs with life-sustaining measures until they can recover.

Muscle breakdown is a health condition where the muscles in the body break down and are unable to function properly. This can be caused by a variety of factors, including injury, disease, or medications.
Muscle fatigue is a condition in which muscles feel tired and unable to work properly. It can be caused by overuse, lack of sleep, or other factors.

Muscle soreness is a common condition that can be caused by a variety of factors, including exercise, overuse, and injury. It is characterized by pain and stiffness in the muscles and can range from mild to severe. Treatment typically involves rest, ice, and over-the-counter pain medications.
Muscular dystrophy is a group of muscle diseases that cause progressive weakness and loss of muscle mass.
Myalgia is a general term for muscle pain. It can be caused by many things, including overuse, injury, or infection.

Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (Chronic Fatigue Syndrome) is a condition characterized by extreme fatigue that does not improve with rest. People with this condition may also experience other symptoms, such as muscle pain, joint pain, headaches, and difficulty concentrating. The cause of Myalgic Encephalomyelitis is unknown, but it is thought to be a combination of genetic and environmental factors. There is no cure for Myalgic Encephalomyelitis, but treatments are available to help manage symptoms.

Myasthenia gravis is a chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease that causes muscle weakness and fatigue. The main symptom of myasthenia gravis is muscle weakness that gets worse with activity and improves with rest.
Mycosis Fungoides is a type of cancer that starts in the skin. It is the most common type of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma.
MDS is a cancer of the blood and bone marrow. It is a type of leukemia.

Myeloid malignancies are a type of cancer that starts in the bone marrow. The bone marrow is the soft tissue inside the bones where blood cells are made. Myeloid malignancies can affect the production of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.

MAD is a health condition characterized by a deficiency of the enzyme myoadenylate deaminase. This enzyme is important for the breakdown of ATP, the energy molecule in the body. People with MAD often experience muscle weakness and fatigue.

A myocardial infarction (MI) is a heart attack that occurs when the blood supply to the heart muscle is blocked. This can happen if the arteries that supply the heart with blood become blocked by a build-up of plaque.

Myofascial pain syndrome is a condition that causes pain in the muscles and fascia. The fascia is the connective tissue that surrounds the muscles. The syndrome is caused by trigger points, which are knots of muscle that form when the muscle is overworked or injured. The trigger points can cause pain in the muscle and the surrounding area. The syndrome is often treated with massage, stretching, and ice.
Myofascial Release is a type of bodywork that focuses on releasing myofascial (muscle and connective tissue) restrictions in order to alleviate pain and restore range of motion.
Myopia is a health condition that causes distant objects to appear blurry. It occurs when the eyeball is too long or when the cornea, the clear front surface of the eye, has too much curvature.

Myositis is a rare condition that causes inflammation of the muscles. It can be caused by autoimmune diseases, infections, or other conditions. Symptoms include muscle weakness, pain, and fatigue. Treatment depends on the underlying cause.

Myotonic dystrophy type 1 is a rare, inherited disorder that causes muscle weakness and wasting. It is the most common form of muscular dystrophy in adults. The disorder is caused by a mutation in a gene called DMPK. People with myotonic dystrophy type 1 typically have a slowly progressive form of the disorder. Symptoms may include muscle weakness, wasting, and twitching; difficulties with speaking, swallowing, and breathing; and problems with heart rhythm. There is no cure for myotonic dystrophy type 1, but treatments can help manage symptoms.
This Myrcia plant is a shrub that can grow to be about 6 feet tall. It has dark green leaves and white flowers. The flowers have a strong, sweet fragrance.
Myristic acid is a saturated fatty acid with a 14-carbon chain. It is found in animal and vegetable fats, and is a major component of nutmeg, mace, and palm kernel oil.
Myrrh is a natural gum or resin extracted from a number of small, thorny tree species of the genus Commiphora. Myrrh resin has been used throughout history as a perfume, incense, and medicine.
The plant has small, dark green leaves and small white flowers. It is a low-growing plant that spreads quickly.

N-Acetyl Cysteine (NAC) is a supplement that is used to raise levels of glutathione in the body. Glutathione is a powerful antioxidant that helps to protect cells from damage. NAC is also used to treat a variety of other conditions, including liver disease, bronchitis, and schizophrenia.

N-Methyltyramine is a naturally occurring trace amine and monoamine alkaloid derived from the amino acid tyrosine. It is found in a variety of plants and animals, including humans. N-Methyltyramine is also a metabolite of the neurotransmitter dopamine.
N,N-DMPEA is a synthetic organic compound that is used as a reagent in chemical synthesis. It is a white solid that is insoluble in water.
Nasal irrigation is a practice in which the nose is flushed with a saline solution. The solution helps to thin mucus, remove irritants and allergens, and moisturize the nasal passages.
Nasopharyngeal cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the nasopharynx, which is the upper part of the pharynx (throat) behind the nose.

This Nasturtium plant is a beautiful, flowering plant that is native to South America. It has large, showy flowers that come in a variety of colors including yellow, orange, red, and pink. The leaves are dark green and have a slightly peppery flavor. Nasturtiums are easy to grow and make a great addition to any garden.

Necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC) is a serious illness that can occur in newborn babies. It is a rare but life-threatening condition that affects the intestines. NEC occurs when the intestines become inflamed and start to die. This can lead to a hole in the intestines, infection, and sepsis (a potentially life-threatening condition caused by infection). NEC is a medical emergency and requires immediate treatment.
Necrotizing fasciitis is a rare but serious bacterial infection that spreads quickly through the body's soft tissue. The infection can cause the tissue to die, and it can be life-threatening.

The neem tree is a fast-growing, evergreen tree that can grow up to 20–30 metres (66–98 ft) tall, with a trunk diameter of up to 1 metre (3 ft). The leaves are arranged in opposite pairs, each leaf being 20–40 centimetres (8–16 in) long and 15–18 centimetres (5.9–7.1 in) broad. The flowers are small and white, with four petals. The fruit is a drupe, containing a single seed.

A negative ion generator is a device that emits negative ions into the air. Negative ions are particles that have been charged with electricity. They are found in nature, and they can also be created by man-made devices. Negative ions have been shown to have a variety of health benefits, including reducing stress, improving mood, and increasing energy levels.
A neodymium magnet is a type of rare-earth magnet made from an alloy of neodymium, iron, and boron.

Neon is a colorless, odorless, inert monatomic gas under standard conditions, with about two-thirds the density of air. It was discovered in 1898 by the British chemist Sir William Ramsay and the Scottish chemist Morris W. Travers.
This is a health condition where a newborn baby's breathing is irregular or stops for short periods of time.

This is a health condition where there is damage to the brain of a newborn baby. This can be caused by many things, including infection, lack of oxygen, or problems with the placenta or umbilical cord. Symptoms can include seizures, feeding problems, irritability, and problems with movement.

Neonatal jaundice is a yellowing of the skin and eyes in newborn babies. It is caused by an excess of bilirubin, a yellow pigment that is produced when red blood cells break down. Neonatal jaundice is usually harmless and resolves on its own within a few weeks.

The Neonatal Resuscitation health condition is a medical emergency that requires immediate medical attention. It is a life-threatening condition that can occur when a baby is born not breathing or not breathing properly.
Neptunium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Np and atomic number 93.
Neural tube birth defects are birth defects of the brain and spinal cord. They occur when the neural tube does not close properly during development.

Neuroblastoma is a cancer that develops from immature nerve cells found in several areas of the body. Neuroblastoma most commonly arises in and around the adrenal glands, but can also occur in the neck, chest, or spinal cord. The cause of neuroblastoma is unknown.

Neurodermatitis is a condition where the skin becomes inflamed and irritated in response to stress or other psychological factors. It is also known as lichen simplex chronicus or chronic idiopathic urticaria. The exact cause is unknown, but it is thought to be related to an overactive immune system. Treatment typically involves avoiding triggers, managing stress, and using topical corticosteroids or antihistamines.

The neurogenic bladder is a health condition where the bladder is unable to store or empty urine properly due to a problem with the nervous system. This can lead to urinary incontinence, urinary retention, and an increased risk for urinary tract infections.

The description of this Neurological Trauma health condition is that it is a type of brain injury that can occur when the head is suddenly and violently jarred or shaken. This can cause the brain to bounce around or twist inside the skull, which can damage the brain cells and lead to a wide range of problems.

Neuropathic pain is a type of pain that is caused by damage to the nervous system. It can be caused by diseases such as diabetes, cancer, and multiple sclerosis. It can also be caused by injuries to the nervous system, such as a spinal cord injury. Neuropathic pain can be very severe and can make it difficult for people to function.

Neutropenic fever is a condition that can occur when the body doesn't have enough neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. This can make it hard for the body to fight off infection. Neutropenic fever can be serious, and it may require hospitalization.

This New Jersey Tea plant is a deciduous shrub that grows to about 3 feet tall. It has small, white flowers that bloom in the summer and dark green leaves. This plant is native to the eastern United States and is often used as an ornamental plant.

The New Zealand Green-Lipped Mussel is a species of bivalve mollusc in the family Mytilidae. It is endemic to New Zealand, where it is found in the intertidal and subtidal zones of the North and South Islands. The shell of the New Zealand Green-Lipped Mussel is green, brown or black, and can reach a length of up to 10 cm. The mussel is an important food source for a variety of animals, including humans.
Niacin-induced flushing is a condition in which the skin becomes red and warm due to the increased blood flow. It is a side effect of taking niacin supplements.

Niauli oil is an essential oil that is extracted from the leaves of the niauli tree. This tree is native to Australia and New Zealand. The oil has a strong, sweet, and floral aroma. It is used in aromatherapy and is believed to have a number of benefits, including reducing stress and anxiety, boosting energy levels, and improving circulation.
A nickel is a coin worth five cents.
Nickel Deficiency is a health condition where the body does not have enough of the mineral nickel. This can lead to problems with the bones, skin, and blood.

Nigella sativa is an annual flowering plant in the family Ranunculaceae, native to south and southwest Asia. The plant grows to 20–30 cm (8–12 in) tall, with finely divided, linear (but not thread-like) leaves. The flowers are delicate, and usually coloured pale blue and white, with five to ten petals. The fruit is a large and inflated capsule composed of three to seven united follicles, each containing numerous seeds.

Nihonium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Nh and atomic number 113. It is extremely radioactive; its most stable known isotope, nihonium-286, has a half-life of 20 seconds. In the periodic table, nihonium is a d-block transactinide element. It is a member of period 7 and group 13, like its lighter homologues boron, aluminium, gallium, indium, and thallium.

The Nikko Maple is a deciduous tree that is native to Japan. It is a small to medium-sized tree that typically grows to 15-20 feet tall. The leaves are ovate-shaped and have a toothed margin. The leaves are green in the summer and turn yellow, orange, or red in the fall. The flowers are small and white and appear in the spring. The fruit is a small, winged seed that is dispersed by the wind.

Niobium is a chemical element with the symbol Nb and atomic number 41. It is a soft, grey, ductile transition metal, which is often found in the pyrochlore mineral, the main commercial source for niobium, and columbite.
Nipple fissures are cracks in the skin of the nipple. They can be painful and may bleed.
Nitrogen is a colorless, odorless, tasteless gas that makes up about 78% of the Earth's atmosphere.

Nobelium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol No and atomic number 102. It is named in honor of Alfred Nobel, the inventor of dynamite and benefactor of science. A radioactive metal of the actinide series, nobelsium is the tenth transuranic element and is the penultimate member of the 7th period of the periodic table. Nocturia is a condition in which a person wakes up during the night to urinate. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including drinking too much fluid before bed, an overactive bladder, or a urinary tract infection.

Phytosteroids are a type of steroid found in plants. They have a variety of functions, including regulating the growth and development of plants, and protecting them from stress.

Phytosterols are plant-derived compounds that are structurally similar to cholesterol. They are found in small amounts in many plant-based foods, such as fruits, vegetables, nuts, and seeds. Phytosterols have been shown to lower cholesterol levels and may also have other health benefits.
Picamilon is a nootropic drug that is created by combining niacin and gamma-aminobutyric acid. It is used to improve blood flow and increase cognitive function.

This Picrorhiza plant is a small, herbaceous perennial that is native to the Himalayan region. It has dark green leaves and small, blue flowers. The roots of the plant are used in traditional medicine to treat a variety of ailments.

Pimpinella is a genus of flowering plants in the family Apiaceae. The genus includes about 30 species of annual and perennial herbs, which are found in temperate and subtropical regions of the world. The leaves of Pimpinella species are usually pinnate, with leaflets arranged in pairs along the leaf rachis. The flowers are small and white, and are borne in umbels. The fruit is a dry, one-seeded schizocarp.  Pimpinella species are used as food plants by the larvae of some Lepidoptera species, including the setaceous Hebrew character.

Pinellia ternata is a perennial herbaceous plant that is native to China. It grows to a height of 30–60 cm (12–24 in). The leaves are ovate to lanceolate, and measure 10–20 cm (4–8 in) long and 5–10 cm (2–4 in) wide. They are arranged in a rosette at the base of the plant. The flowers are white or greenish-white, and borne in an umbel. The fruit is a globose berry, which turns black when ripe.
This plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lanceolate and the flowers are pink. The plant blooms in the summer and fall.

This Piper cubeba plant is a tropical evergreen vine that is native to Indonesia. It has long, heart-shaped leaves and produces small, white flowers. The plant is used to make the spice known as cubeb pepper.

Pipsissewa is a small, evergreen plant that typically grows to only about 6 inches (15 cm) tall. The leaves are opposite, oblong-lanceolate, and have a toothed margin. The small, white flowers are borne in clusters at the leaf axils. The fruit is a small, black drupe.
Piracetam is a nootropic drug that has been shown to improve memory and cognitive function. It is thought to work by increasing levels of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.

The Pitcher Plant is a carnivorous plant that gets its nutrients from the insects it catches. The plant has a pitcher-shaped trap that is filled with a sweet-smelling liquid. The insect is attracted to the liquid and falls into the trap. The plant then digests the insect.

Pituitary resistance to thyroid hormone (PRTH) is a condition in which the pituitary gland does not respond properly to thyroid hormone. This can lead to problems with growth, metabolism, and other functions controlled by the pituitary gland.

Pityriasis Lichenoides Chronica (PLC) is a rare, chronic skin disorder that is characterized by small, red-brown bumps on the skin. The bumps may be scaly or crusted, and they often form in clusters. PLC typically affects the trunk and upper extremities, but it can also occur on the face, scalp, and nails. The exact cause of PLC is unknown, but it is thought to be a type of autoimmune disorder. There is no cure for PLC, but treatment can help to control the symptoms.
Plant sterols are a type of phytochemical found in plants. They have a variety of functions, including acting as antioxidants and helping to regulate cholesterol levels.

Plantain is a herbaceous perennial plant in the genus Plantago. It is native to Europe and Asia and is also found in North America, Africa, and Australia. The plantain has a rosette of leaves and a long, slender stalk that bears a small, brownish-black fruit. The plantain is a member of the plant family Plantaginaceae.

Plantar heel pain is a condition that causes pain in the heel of the foot. The pain is often worse when you first get up in the morning or after you have been sitting or standing for a long period of time.
Plastic surgery is a medical specialty that deals with the correction or restoration of form and function.

Platinum is a chemical element with the symbol Pt and atomic number 78. It is a dense, malleable, ductile, highly unreactive, precious, silverish-white transition metal. Its name is derived from the Spanish term platina, meaning "little silver".

Pleurisy root is a perennial herb that grows up to 1.5 m tall. The leaves are lanceolate to ovate, and the flowers are white or pale blue. The fruit is a capsule.  Pleurisy root is native to North America and Europe. It is found in woods, meadows, and damp areas.  Pleurisy root is used as a herbal remedy for pleurisy, bronchitis, and other respiratory disorders. It is also used as a diuretic and expectorant.
A plum is a fruit that is typically red, purple, or blue.

Plutonium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Pu and atomic number 94. It is an actinide metal of silvery-gray appearance that tarnishes when exposed to air, and forms a dull coating when oxidized. The element normally exhibits six allotropes and four oxidation states.

Podophyllum is a genus of herbaceous perennials in the family Berberidaceae, comprising around 23 species. The plants are native to temperate and subtropical regions of Asia, North America and South America. The species vary in size from 30 cm to 1.5 m tall. The leaves are variable in shape, but are generally large and palm-like, with five to seven lobes. The flowers are borne in clusters of two to five, and are white or pink with six petals. The fruit is a fleshy berry.  Podophyllum plants are grown for their ornamental value. They are typically used as groundcover or in shady borders. Some species are also grown as houseplants.

This poinsettia plant has large, deep green leaves and bright red flowers. The flowers are borne in clusters and have a yellow center. The plant grows to a height of 3-4 feet and has a spread of 2-3 feet.

This Poison Ivy plant has glossy, dark green leaves that are arranged in a cluster of three. The leaves are each about 3-6 inches long and have a pointed tip. The edges of the leaves are serrated, and the surface of the leaves is smooth. The leaves are attached to the stem by a short petiole. This plant produces small, greenish-white flowers that grow in clusters. The flowers are followed by small, white berries.

column1: Poison Oak And Poison Ivy Dermatitis
column2: Poison oak and poison ivy dermatitis is a condition caused by contact with the plants poison ivy, poison oak, or poison sumac. Symptoms include red, itchy, and blistering skin.
The person has a headache, feels dizzy and has a fast heart rate.

Pokeweed is a perennial herb that can grow up to 10 feet tall. The stem is green and smooth with purple spots. The leaves are large, oval-shaped, and have a toothed margin. The flowers are small, white, and grow in clusters. The fruit is a dark purple berry that is poisonous to humans.

Polarity Therapy is a system of natural healing that uses the body's energy fields to promote balance and well-being. It is based on the belief that the body is composed of five elements - earth, water, fire, air, and ether - which are in constant interaction with each other. Polarity Therapy practitioners use a variety of techniques, including massage, acupressure, and energy work, to restore balance and harmony within the body.
Policosanol is a natural substance found in sugar cane and beeswax. It is used as a supplement to lower cholesterol and improve heart health.
Polonium is a radioactive element that occurs naturally in the environment. It has no known uses.

Polymorphous light eruption (PMLE) is a skin condition that is characterized by an itchy or burning rash that appears after exposure to sunlight. The rash typically consists of small, red bumps or blisters. PMLE is thought to be caused by an abnormal reaction of the immune system to ultraviolet (UV) light.

Polymyalgia rheumatica is a disorder of the muscles and joints that causes pain and stiffness in the arms, legs, and neck. The cause is unknown, but it is thought to be related to an autoimmune disorder. Treatment typically involves the use of corticosteroids and other anti-inflammatory medications.

Polyphenols are a type of phytochemical that are found in plant-based foods. They are known for their antioxidant properties and have been linked to health benefits like reduced inflammation, improved heart health, and better blood sugar control.

Polypodium leucotomos is a tropical fern native to Central and South America. The plant has large, leathery leaves that are green on top and brown on the bottom. The leaves are arranged in a spiral pattern on the stem. The plant produces small, greenish-white flowers that grow in clusters. The flowers are followed by small, black fruits.
Polysaccharides are long chains of saccharide molecules.
A polyunsaturated fat is a type of fat molecule that has more than one double bond in its structure. This makes them more unstable than saturated fats, which have no double bonds.
Poppy seeds are small, dry seeds from the poppy plant.

Poria mushroom is a type of fungi that is commonly used in traditional Chinese medicine. It is believed to have a variety of health benefits, including aiding in digestion, reducing inflammation, and boosting the immune system.

Porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT) is a type of porphyria, a group of disorders that result from problems with the production of heme, a substance in red blood cells that carries oxygen. PCT is the most common type of porphyria. People with PCT have a deficiency of the enzyme uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (UROD). This enzyme is needed to make heme. Without enough UROD, the body can't make heme, and heme builds up in the body.

Portal hypertension is a condition in which the blood pressure in the portal vein (the vein that carries blood from the intestines and other organs to the liver) is higher than normal. This can cause the veins in the esophagus and stomach to swell and can lead to bleeding.
Post-polio syndrome (PPS) is a condition that affects some people who have had polio. PPS can cause new weakness, pain, and fatigue.

Post-stroke fatigue is a common and debilitating symptom that can occur after a person has had a stroke. It is characterized by an overwhelming sense of tiredness and exhaustion that can last for weeks, months, or even years. Although post-stroke fatigue can be difficult to manage, there are treatments and strategies that can help.

Postbiotics are the beneficial compounds that are produced by probiotics during their fermentation process in the gut. These compounds include short-chain fatty acids, vitamins, minerals, and other antioxidants that can help to improve gut health.
Postmenopausal conditions are health conditions that can occur after a woman has gone through menopause. These conditions can include hot flashes, night sweats, vaginal dryness, and mood swings.

A postoperative fistula is an abnormal connection between two organs or vessels that results from surgery. Fistulas can occur between the intestines and the skin, the bladder and the skin, or two blood vessels.
A postoperative headache is a headache that occurs after surgery. It can be a dull ache or a throbbing pain, and it may be accompanied by nausea, vomiting, or dizziness.
Postoperative ileus is a condition that can occur after surgery in which the intestines do not work properly. This can lead to cramping, bloating, and nausea.
A postoperative infection is an infection that occurs after surgery.

Postoperative muscle loss is a condition that can occur after surgery. It is characterized by a loss of muscle mass and a decrease in muscle strength. This can lead to a decrease in mobility and an increased risk of falls and fractures.

PONV is a condition that can occur after surgery. It is characterized by nausea and vomiting. PONV can be a side effect of anesthesia or pain medication. It can also be caused by a reaction to the surgical procedure itself. PONV is a common condition, and it can be very unpleasant.

Postoperative pain is a type of pain that occurs after surgery. It can be mild or severe, and it can last for a short time or a long time. Postoperative pain is a normal part of the healing process, and it is important for the body to heal properly.

Postoperative pulmonary hypertension is a condition in which the blood pressure in the lungs is abnormally high. This can occur after surgery, and can be a serious complication. Symptoms may include shortness of breath, chest pain, and dizziness. Treatment typically involves medications to lower the blood pressure in the lungs.
The person has undergone surgery and is in the process of recovering. This may include staying in the hospital, going home with instructions, and/or returning for follow-up visits.
Postoperative sleep disturbance is a condition where a person has difficulty sleeping after surgery. This can be due to pain, anxiety, or other factors.
A sore throat is a common condition that can be caused by a number of things, including viral infections, bacterial infections, and irritants.

Postoperative swelling is a medical condition where the body experiences an abnormal accumulation of fluid in the tissues. This can happen after any type of surgery, but is most common after orthopedic procedures. Swelling can cause pain, stiffness, and decreased range of motion. It can also lead to serious complications if not treated properly.
Postpartum complications are health conditions that can occur after a woman gives birth. They can include infections, bleeding, and blood clots.

Postpartum depression is a mental health condition that can occur in the weeks and months after giving birth. It's marked by feelings of sadness, anxiety, and exhaustion that make it hard to care for yourself and your baby.
Postprandial hypotension is a condition in which blood pressure falls after a meal. This can cause lightheadedness, dizziness, and fainting.

Postural syncope is a condition in which a person experiences a sudden drop in blood pressure, leading to lightheadedness, dizziness, or fainting. It is often caused by standing up too quickly, and can be treated by lying down or sitting down.

Postural Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS) is a condition in which a person experiences a sudden and dramatic increase in heart rate when moving from a lying down to a standing position. The condition is often accompanied by lightheadedness, dizziness, and fainting.
Potatoes are a type of starchy vegetable that are often eaten as a side dish. They are a good source of vitamins and minerals, and can be cooked in many different ways.

This Potentilla plant is a deciduous shrub that typically grows to 3-6’ tall and to 6-9’ wide. It is native to woodlands, forest edges, and open areas in Europe, Asia, and North America. The leaves are palmately compound with 5-7 leaflets. The leaflets are ovate to oblong-ovate, serrate, and have a crenate margin. The flowers are yellow, have 5 petals, and bloom in clusters from late spring to early summer. The fruit is a dry achene. This plant prefers full sun to part shade and moist, well-drained soils. It is tolerant of a wide range of soils, including clay.
Pouchitis is a condition in which the pouch that is created during surgery to treat ulcerative colitis becomes inflamed.
Poultry is a category of domesticated birds kept by humans for their eggs, meat or feathers.

Prader-Willi syndrome (PWS) is a rare, complex genetic disorder that affects many parts of the body. The most well-known features of PWS include low muscle tone, short stature, incomplete sexual development, and a constant feeling of hunger that can lead to excessive eating and life-threatening obesity. PWS is caused by a missing or defective gene on chromosome 15, and it occurs in both males and females. There is no cure for PWS, but treatments can help manage the symptoms.
Praseodymium is a soft, silvery, malleable, and ductile metal in the lanthanide group. It is the third member of the series, and is traditionally considered to be one of the rare-earth metals.

Pre-Procedural Anxiety is a condition characterized by anxiety and fear prior to a medical procedure. This may be due to a previous bad experience, fear of the unknown, or anxiety about the potential pain or discomfort associated with the procedure. Symptoms may include heart palpitations, shortness of breath, sweating, and dizziness.
Prediabetes is a health condition in which a person's blood sugar levels are higher than normal, but not high enough yet to be diagnosed with diabetes.
Pregnancy-induced hypertension (PIH) is a condition that can occur during pregnancy in which the blood pressure becomes too high.

Pregnancy-induced nausea and vomiting (NVP) is a condition that pregnant women may experience during pregnancy. NVP can cause nausea, vomiting, and sometimes both. NVP is also sometimes called “morning sickness.”

Pregnancy-related edema is a condition characterized by swelling in the hands, feet, and ankles. It is most common in the third trimester of pregnancy, and can be caused by the increased blood volume and pressure on the veins.
Pregnancy-related gingivitis is a condition that can occur during pregnancy and is characterized by inflammation of the gums.

This Pregnancy-Related Iron Deficiency health condition is characterized by a lack of iron in the body. This can lead to anemia, which is a condition in which the blood is unable to carry enough oxygen to the body's tissues.

Pregnancy-related leg cramps are a common complaint during pregnancy, especially in the third trimester. They are often described as a sharp, shooting pain in the calf or foot that can be quite debilitating. While the exact cause of pregnancy-related leg cramps is unknown, they are thought to be related to the increased weight and pressure on the legs and feet during pregnancy. Treatment for pregnancy-related leg cramps typically includes stretching and massaging the affected muscles, as well as taking over-the-counter pain relievers.
Pregnancy-related pain is a condition that is characterized by pain that is associated with pregnancy. This pain can occur in the abdomen, back, pelvis, and legs. It can be mild to severe in nature.
Pregnenolone is a hormone that is produced in the body from cholesterol. It is a precursor to other hormones, including testosterone, estrogen, and progesterone.
A premature birth is a birth that takes place more than three weeks before the baby's due date. In the United States, about 12% of babies are born premature.
Premature ejaculation is a sexual disorder in which a man ejaculates sooner during sexual intercourse than he or his partner would like.
PROM is a condition in which the membranes that surround and protect the baby rupture before labor begins.
The definition of prematurity is when a baby is born before 37 weeks of gestation.

Premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD) is a severe, sometimes disabling extension of premenstrual syndrome (PMS). While PMS affects many women, PMDD is much less common. It is estimated that 3–8% of women of childbearing age suffer from PMDD. PMDD symptoms include depressed mood, anxiety, irritability, anger, and decreased interest in usual activities. These symptoms are severe enough to interfere with work, school, social activities, and relationships with others. PMDD symptoms typically occur during the last week of the luteal phase and improve within a few days after the onset of menses.
PMS is a health condition that can cause a woman to experience a range of symptoms in the days or weeks before her period. These symptoms can include mood swings, irritability, bloating, and fatigue.
Preterm labor is a condition in which a pregnant woman begins to have contractions before her 37th week of pregnancy. These contractions may lead to premature birth.

Prickly heat is a skin condition that is characterized by small, raised bumps that are often itchy. The bumps are caused by sweat glands that become blocked and inflamed. Prickly heat often occurs in hot, humid weather and is more common in people who sweat excessively.

The prickly pear fruit is a type of cactus fruit that is native to Mexico and other parts of Central and South America. The fruit is oval or spherical in shape and has a thick, fleshy exterior with small, sharp spines. The interior of the fruit is filled with a sweet, juicy pulp that is often used in jams, jellies, and other desserts.
Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC) is a chronic liver disease in which the bile ducts are slowly destroyed. This can lead to scarring of the liver (cirrhosis) and eventual liver failure.

Primary dysmenorrhea is defined as menstrual cramps in the absence of other pelvic disorders. The pain is usually felt in the lower abdomen and can radiate to the lower back and thighs. The pain is usually cyclical, starting one to two days before menses and lasting for the first one to two days of menses.

Primary intestinal lymphangiectasia is a condition in which the lymphatic vessels in the intestine are abnormally dilated. This can lead to a build-up of lymph fluid in the intestine, which can cause abdominal pain, bloating, and diarrhea.

Primary ovarian insufficiency (POI) is a health condition in which a woman's ovaries stop working normally before she is 40 years old. POI is also known as premature ovarian failure (POF) or primary ovarian failure (POF).

A PNET is a rare, fast-growing cancer that forms in the cells of the nervous system. It most often starts in the brain or spinal cord, but can also occur in the nerves outside of the brain and spinal cord. PNETs are most common in children and young adults.
The definition of primordial is something that is present or existing from the beginning.
Probiotics are live microorganisms that are intended to have health benefits.
Procaine is a local anesthetic drug of the amino ester group. It is used primarily to reduce the pain of intramuscular injection of penicillin, and it is also used in dentistry.
Prohormones are substances that are precursors to hormones and are usually converted into active hormones by the body.

Proline is an amino acid that is essential for the structure and function of proteins. Proline is unique among amino acids because it contains a cyclic ring structure. This structure gives proline the ability to form stable bonds with other proteins, which is essential for the function of many proteins.

Prolonged grief disorder (PGD) is a condition where a person experiences intense grief for an extended period of time. This can be due to the death of a loved one, or any other type of loss. Symptoms may include feeling isolated, feeling numb, feeling angry, and having difficulty moving on.
Promethium is a radioactive metal that is used in some types of batteries.
Propionyl-L-carnitine is a naturally occurring amino acid that is involved in energy metabolism. It is also a potent antioxidant and has been shown to improve blood flow and reduce inflammation.

Prostatitis is a health condition that affects the prostate gland. The prostate is a small, walnut-sized gland that is located in front of the rectum and below the bladder. The prostate gland produces a fluid that helps to nourish and protect sperm. Prostatitis is a condition that can cause pain, urinary problems, and sexual problems.

Protactinium is a chemical element with the symbol Pa and atomic number 91. It is a dense, silvery-gray metal which readily reacts with oxygen, water vapor, and inorganic acids. It forms a series of radioactive decay products through alpha decay. The first element of the actinide series, protactinium is the heaviest element that can be formed by beta decay of lighter elements.
Protease enzymes are enzymes that break down proteins into smaller peptides.

Proximal myotonic myopathy (PROMM) is a rare genetic disorder that is characterized by muscle weakness and stiffness. The disorder is caused by a mutation in the myotonic dystrophy protein kinase gene. PROMM is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.
A prudent diet is one that is moderate in all nutrients and low in fat, saturated fat, and cholesterol.
A prune is a dried plum.

Prurigo Nodularis is a chronic skin condition characterized by intensely itchy bumps that can appear anywhere on the body. The bumps are usually red and may be filled with pus. They can range in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters. Prurigo Nodularis is a relatively rare condition, and its exact cause is unknown. Treatment typically involves a combination of topical and oral medications.
Pruritus is a medical term for the sensation of itchiness. It can be caused by a number of things, including allergies, insect bites, and dry skin.
This is a condition where the skin is damaged from exposure to Psoralen-Uva (PUVA) light therapy. The skin may become red, dry, and cracked. There may also be blistering and peeling.
Psoriatic arthritis is a form of arthritis that affects people who have psoriasis. It causes inflammation, pain, and stiffness in the joints, and can also cause changes in the nails and skin.
Pu-erh tea is a type of Chinese black tea that has been fermented.

Pulsatilla vulgaris, known as the pasque flower, is a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family Ranunculaceae, native to Europe. It is a herbaceous perennial growing to 20–30 cm tall, with deeply divided blue-green leaves and violet-blue flowers in early spring. The flowers are hermaphrodite and are pollinated by bees. The plant is self-fertile.  This Pulsatilla plant is a herbaceous perennial that grows to 20-30 cm tall. It has deeply divided blue-green leaves and violet-blue flowers in early spring. The flowers are hermaphrodite and are pollinated by bees. The plant is self-fertile.

Pulse diagnosis is a traditional Chinese medicine technique that is used to assess the health of a patient. The practitioner will feel the pulse on the wrist of the patient and use this information to make a diagnosis.

Pulsed electromagnetic field therapy is a type of therapy that uses magnetic fields to stimulate healing. The therapy is based on the principle that magnetic fields can help to reduce inflammation and promote cell repair.

The Purple Hyacinth Bean is a beautiful, fast-growing vine that produces stunning purple flowers and dark purple beans. The beans are edible and can be used in a variety of dishes. The vine is also a great source of nectar for bees and other pollinators.

(Lythrum salicaria)  This Purple Loosestrife plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to 2m tall. The leaves are lanceolate to oblong-lanceolate in shape and are arranged in opposite pairs along the stem. The flowers are borne in dense, cylindrical spikes and are pink to purple in colour. The fruit is a small, dry capsule.

(Cyperus rotundus)  This Purple Nut Sedge is a perennial plant that grows in clumps. The leaves are long and narrow with a purple tinge. The flowers are small and green, and they grow in clusters. The plant produces small, brown, nut-like seeds.

This is a Pygeum plant. It is an evergreen tree that can grow up to 30 feet tall. The leaves are oblong and have a glossy surface. The flowers are white and grow in clusters. The fruit is a drupe that is red when ripe.

This plant is a member of the Asteraceae family and is native to Europe, Asia, and Africa. It grows to a height of 2-3 feet and has daisy-like flowers that are white or pale pink in color. The flowers have a strong, sweet fragrance and are used in a variety of cosmetics and perfumes.
Pyruvate is a three-carbon compound that is a key intermediate in the metabolism of glucose.
Qi Gong can be defined as a form of traditional Chinese exercise that is said to promote health and well-being. This exercise is often characterized by slow, deliberate movements and deep breathing.
This Quassia plant is a shrub that can grow up to 6 feet tall. It has dark green leaves and white flowers. The fruit of this plant is a small, dark red berry.

The Quebracho Blanco is a large tree that can grow up to 30 meters tall. It has a straight trunk with a diameter of up to 1.5 meters. The bark is thick and dark brown in color. The leaves are large, leathery, and dark green in color. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a large, woody capsule that contains several seeds.

Queen's Delight (Stillingia sylvatica) is an herbaceous perennial native to the southeastern United States. It has a low-growing, upright habit and can reach heights of 1-3 feet. The bright green leaves are oblong and up to 4 inches long. The plant produces yellow, daisy-like flowers from May to August, which are followed by three-lobed, green fruits. Queen's Delight prefers moist, well-drained soils in partial shade and does best in USDA zones 6-9. It is drought tolerant and can tolerate a variety of soil types, making it a great choice for gardens. Queen's Delight is a great choice for attracting butterflies and other pollinators to the garden.
This Quillaia plant is a shrub that can grow up to 6 feet tall. It has small, green leaves and white flowers. The fruit of this plant is a small, red berry.
A quince is a fruit that is similar in appearance to a pear, but is much harder and has a sour taste.
Rabdosia Rubescens is a perennial herb that grows up to 1 meter tall. The leaves are ovate to lanceolate, and the flowers are white or pink. The fruit is a black berry.
Radiation dermatitis is a skin condition that develops when the skin is exposed to radiation therapy. The skin may become red, dry, and irritated. The condition can also lead to skin infections.

Radiation exposure is a health condition that can occur when a person is exposed to high levels of ionizing radiation. This type of radiation can damage the cells in the body and cause a range of health problems, including cancer.

Radiation fibrosis is a condition that results when tissue is damaged by radiation therapy. Radiation fibrosis can lead to the formation of scar tissue, which can cause the affected area to become stiff and difficult to move. Radiation fibrosis can also cause the formation of blood clots, which can lead to serious health complications.

Radiation proctopathy is a condition that can occur after radiation therapy to the pelvis. It is marked by changes in the rectum and anus, including inflammation, bleeding, and scarring. In severe cases, it can lead to a narrowing of the rectum (stricture) or blockage of the anal opening (fistula).

Radiation-induced cystitis is a condition that can occur after a person has been treated with radiation therapy for cancer. The condition is caused by the radiation damaging the lining of the bladder, which can lead to inflammation and the formation of cysts. Symptoms of radiation-induced cystitis can include urinary frequency, urgency, and pain. Treatment for the condition may include medications, surgery, or both.

Radiation-induced diarrhea is a condition that can occur after a person has been exposed to radiation therapy. The symptoms of this condition include abdominal pain, cramping, and diarrhea. In some cases, the diarrhea may be bloody.

Radiation-induced esophagitis is a condition that can occur when the esophagus is exposed to radiation therapy. Symptoms may include pain, difficulty swallowing, and bleeding. Treatment typically involves medications to help relieve symptoms and prevent complications.

Radiation-induced fatigue is a common side effect of radiation therapy. It is often described as a feeling of extreme tiredness that is not relieved by rest. Fatigue can range from mild to severe, and may last for weeks or months after treatment.
Radiation-induced nausea and vomiting (RINV) is a condition that can occur after a person has been exposed to radiation therapy. RINV can cause a person to feel nauseated and vomit.

Radiation-induced pneumonitis is a condition in which the lungs are inflamed due to exposure to radiation. Symptoms include shortness of breath, coughing, and chest pain. Treatment typically involves steroids and other medications to reduce inflammation.

Radiation-induced sialadenitis is a condition that results from exposure to radiation. The condition is characterized by inflammation of the salivary glands. Symptoms of the condition include pain, swelling, and redness in the affected area. Treatment of the condition typically involves the use of anti-inflammatory medications.

A radish is a root vegetable that is typically red, white, or purple in color. Radishes can vary in size, but they are typically small and round. Radishes are often eaten raw, as they have a crisp texture and a slightly spicy flavor.
Radium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Ra and atomic number 88. It was discovered in 1898 by French chemist Pierre Curie and his wife, Marie Curie.

Radon is a radioactive gas that is formed from the decay of uranium in the ground. It can enter homes through cracks in the foundation and can build up to high levels. Radon is the leading cause of lung cancer in non-smokers.
Ramadan fasting is the practice of abstaining from food and drink, including water, from dawn to dusk during the Islamic month of Ramadan.
Rapeseed oil is a type of vegetable oil that is extracted from the seeds of the rapeseed plant.

column1: Rapid Eye Movement Sleep Behavior Disorder (RBD)
column2: A sleep disorder that is characterized by acting out vivid dreams during REM sleep.

This Rauvolfia Vomitoria plant is a shrub that can grow to be about 6 feet tall. It has dark green leaves that are about 3 inches long and 2 inches wide. The flowers are white and they grow in clusters. The fruit is a black berry that is about 1/2 inch in diameter.

Rauwolscine is an alkaloid that is found in a variety of plants. It has a variety of effects on the body, including stimulating the central nervous system, increasing blood pressure, and decreasing appetite.
A raw food diet is a diet that consists of foods that are either uncooked or only lightly cooked.

Raynaud syndrome is a condition in which the blood vessels in the fingers and toes spasm in response to cold or emotional stress. This can cause the fingers and toes to feel numb and cold. In severe cases, the skin may ulcerate.

Recurrent Respiratory Papillomatosis (RRP) is a rare, chronic viral infection of the upper respiratory tract. It is caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV), which is the same virus that causes genital warts. RRP is characterized by the growth of warts (papillomas) in the airway, which can cause difficulty breathing, wheezing, and coughing. In severe cases, RRP can lead to obstruction of the airway and even death. There is no cure for RRP, but it can be managed with medical and surgical treatments.

Some people might say that sound healing is the use of sound to promote physical and emotional wellbeing, while others might say that it is the use of sound to create a state of deep relaxation and promote healing.

Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA) is a rare, progressive neuromuscular disorder characterized by muscle weakness and atrophy. Spinocerebellar ataxia (SCA) is a rare neurological disorder that affects the cerebellum, the part of the brain that controls movement. SCA can cause problems with balance, coordination, and speech. It can also cause problems with thinking and memory. SCA is a progressive disorder, which means it gets worse over time. There is no cure for SCA, but there are treatments that can help improve symptoms.

The Spiny Restharrow is a small, spiny, perennial herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the pea family and has small, white flowers that bloom in the summer. It is often found growing in fields, on roadsides, and in other disturbed areas.

Geranium maculatum, commonly called wild geranium, spotted geranium, wood geranium, cranesbill, or alumroot, is a Missouri native wildflower that typically occurs in dry woods, glades or rocky open areas. A stabbing headache is a type of headache that is characterized by a sharp, piercing, or jabbing pain in the head. The pain may be localized to one area or may be felt all over the head. It is often accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound.

Stable angina is a type of chest pain that occurs when the heart muscle is not getting enough oxygen. The pain is usually felt in the chest, but it may also be felt in the shoulders, arms, neck, jaw, or back. The pain may come and go, or it may be constant.

Star anise is an evergreen tree that grows to about 20 feet tall. The leaves are oblong and the flowers are white with purple streaks. The fruit is a star-shaped, brownish-black drupe that contains a single seed. Star anise is native to China and Vietnam.

Star Of Bethlehem is a small, perennial plant with white star-shaped flowers that bloom in the summer months. It grows to a height of about 12 inches and has long, thin and slightly curved leaves. The flower has six petals, each with a yellow centre. The plant is native to Europe, North Africa and Western Asia, but is now naturalized in many parts of the world. It is a weed of pastures, roadsides, waste areas, and is also commonly grown in gardens. It is a poisonous plant and should be handled with care.
Starch is a type of carbohydrate that is found in many plants. It is made up of long chains of glucose molecules and is used by plants as a storage form of energy.
A starch and sucrose restricted diet is a diet that limits the amount of starch and sucrose that you eat.

Statin-induced myalgia is a condition characterized by muscle pain and weakness. It is thought to be caused by the use of statin medications, which are used to lower cholesterol levels. Symptoms may include muscle aches, pain, and weakness. The condition may resolve on its own or with treatment.

Subfertility is a health condition where a person has difficulty conceiving or carrying a pregnancy to term. Suicidal ideation is defined as thinking about, considering, or planning suicide. This can range from very vague and fleeting thoughts to detailed plans and preparations.

(Peganum harmala)  The Syrian Rue plant is a small, woody shrub that grows to a height of about 2-3 feet. It has small, dark green leaves and white or pale pink flowers. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body. In SLE, the body’s immune system attacks healthy tissue and organs. Tardive dyskinesia is a condition that causes involuntary, repetitive movements of the face and body. The movements are often jerky and can be difficult to control. Tay-Sachs disease is a rare, fatal disorder that primarily affects infants and young children. The disease is caused by a mutation in a gene called HEXA, which is responsible for producing an enzyme called hexosaminidase A. Teas are a type of dried plant that is used to make a beverage.

This Teazle plant is a small, spiny herbaceous plant in the daisy family. It is native to Europe, Asia, and Africa, and has been introduced to North America and Australia. Technetium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Tc and atomic number 43. It is the lowest atomic number element without any stable isotopes; every form of it is radioactive. Nearly all technetium is produced synthetically, and only minute amounts occur in nature.

Telangiectasias are small, dilated blood vessels near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes, measuring between 0.5 and 1 millimeter in diameter. They can occur anywhere on the body but are most commonly seen on the face, chest, and legs.
Tellurium is a chemical element with the symbol Te and atomic number 52. It is a brittle, mildly toxic, rare, silver-white metalloid. Tellurium is chemically related to selenium and sulfur.

The Temporomandibular Disorder (TMD) is a health condition that affects the jaw and the muscles that control it. The disorder can cause pain in the jaw, face, neck, and head. It can also cause clicking or popping sounds when the jaw is moved.

Tendinopathy is a condition that results from the overuse or injury of tendons, the tissues that connect muscles to bones.
