Tennessine is a superheavy artificial chemical element with an atomic number of 117 and a symbol of Ts. It is an extremely radioactive element that has only been created in laboratories and has not been found in nature.

Tension headaches are the most common type of headache. The pain is usually mild to moderate, and feels like a tight band around your head. You may also have a dull, aching feeling in your neck and shoulders.
Teratozoospermia is a condition in which there is an abnormal number of sperm with abnormal morphology.

Terbium is a chemical element with the symbol Tb and atomic number 65. It is a silvery-white, rare earth metal that is malleable, ductile, and soft enough to be cut with a knife. Terbium is a lanthanide, a rare earth element that is found in the minerals euxenite, gadolinite, and monazite.

The Terminalia is a large genus of flowering plants in the family Combretaceae, native to tropical regions of the world. The genus is characterized by its terminal inflorescences, which are often showy and brightly colored.

Testicular cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the testicles, which are the male reproductive glands. The testicles produce sperm and testosterone, and are located in the scrotum, which is the sac of skin that hangs below the penis. Testicular cancer is relatively rare, accounting for about 1% of all cancers in men. However, it is the most common cancer in men between the ages of 15 and 44. There are two main types of testicular cancer: seminoma and non-seminoma. Seminoma is the most common type, accounting for about 50% of all cases. Non-seminoma is more aggressive and accounts for the other 50% of cases.

Testolone is a synthetic anabolic-androgenic steroid (AAS) and a derivative of dihydrotestosterone (DHT). Tetanus is a serious bacterial infection that can cause muscle spasms, seizures, and death. It is often called "lockjaw" because one of the most common symptoms is a tightening of the jaw muscles. Tetanus occurs when the bacterium Clostridium tetani enters the body through a cut or wound. The bacteria produce a toxin that affects the nervous system, causing muscle spasms. Tetanus is most common in developing countries, where immunization rates are low.

Thallium is a chemical element with the symbol Tl and atomic number 81. It is a gray post-transition metal that is not found free in nature. When isolated, thallium resembles tin, but discolors when exposed to air. Theacrine is a purine alkaloid that is structurally similar to caffeine. It is found in various plants, including Camellia sinensis (tea), and is known for its stimulant effects.

Theophylline-induced cardiotoxicity is a condition in which theophylline, a medication used to treat asthma and other respiratory conditions, causes heart problems. Symptoms may include irregular heartbeat, chest pain, and shortness of breath. The condition can be fatal if not treated.

Therapeutic Touch is a type of energy therapy that uses gentle touch to help promote healing. The therapist will use their hands to lightly touch or hold the person's body in order to help balance their energy field.

A thiamine deficiency is a health condition that occurs when there is not enough thiamine in the body. Thiamine is an essential nutrient that is found in many foods, including meat, poultry, fish, nuts, and seeds. It is also found in some fortified foods, such as breakfast cereals and energy bars. Thiamine is important for the body to make energy, and it is also involved in the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats. A thiamine deficiency can cause fatigue, muscle weakness, and difficulty walking. It can also lead to problems with the nervous system, such as numbness and tingling in the hands and feet. A thiamine deficiency can be caused by a diet that does not include enough thiamine-rich foods, or by a condition that interferes with the body's ability to absorb thiamine.

Thorium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Th and atomic number 90. Thorium is silvery and tarnishes black when it is exposed to air, forming thorium dioxide; it is moderately hard, malleable, and has a high melting point.
Threonine is an amino acid that is essential for the growth and repair of tissues in the body. It is also necessary for the production of enzymes and hormones.
Thrombocytopenia is a condition in which there are not enough platelets in the blood. Platelets are blood cells that help the blood to clot.
This Thrush health condition is characterized by a white, creamy discharge from the vagina that has a yeasty smell. It is caused by an overgrowth of the Candida albicans fungus.

Thuja is a genus of evergreen coniferous trees in the Cupressaceae family. The genus includes five species, two of which are widely known in cultivation: Thuja occidentalis (northern white cedar or eastern arborvitae) and Thuja plicata (western red cedar).
Thulium is a chemical element with the symbol Tm and atomic number 69. It is the thirteenth and third-last element in the lanthanide series.

Thyme is a small, woody, perennial herb with tiny, fragrant leaves and pink or white flowers. It is native to the Mediterranean region and is widely cultivated as a culinary herb. Thyme is also used as a medicinal herb and is thought to have a number of health benefits.

The thyroid is a butterfly-shaped gland that sits in the front of the neck. It makes hormones that help the body work properly. Cancer starts when cells in the body begin to grow out of control. Thyroid cancer happens when cells in the thyroid gland start to grow uncontrollably.
Thyroid hormones are hormones produced by the thyroid gland. They are essential for many body functions, including growth and development, metabolism, and heart rate.

A thyroid storm is a rare but life-threatening condition that occurs when the body produces too much thyroid hormone. Symptoms include high fever, rapid heart rate, and agitation. Treatment typically involves taking medication to reduce the production of thyroid hormone and providing supportive care.

Tianeptine is a drug used for the treatment of depression and anxiety. It is a tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) and is structurally similar to amitriptyline. Tianeptine is thought to work by increasing the levels of serotonin and norepinephrine in the brain.
A tick repellent is a substance that is applied to the skin or clothing that repels ticks.

This Timothy grass plant is a perennial grass that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a common forage grass in many parts of the world and is also used as a turfgrass. The leaves of this grass are long and narrow, and the plant produces small, brown seeds.

Tinea capitis is a fungal infection of the scalp that can cause hair loss. It is most common in children, but can occur in adults. Symptoms include scaly patches on the scalp, itching, and hair loss. Treatment involves antifungal medications.

Tinea corporis is a fungal infection of the skin that typically appears as a red, scaly rash on the body. The rash is often itchy and may be accompanied by flaking, peeling, or cracking of the skin. Tinea corporis is most commonly caused by the fungus Trichophyton rubrum, although other fungi, such as Microsporum gypseum, can also cause the condition. Treatment of tinea corporis typically involves the use of antifungal medications, such as clotrimazole or miconazole.

Tinea cruris is a fungal infection of the groin and inner thighs. It is also known as jock itch. The fungus that causes tinea cruris is the same one that causes athlete's foot. Tinea cruris is more common in men than in women. The symptoms of tinea cruris include itching, burning, and redness in the groin and inner thighs. The rash may also have a scaly or flaky appearance. Tinea cruris is usually treated with antifungal creams or powders.

Tinea pedis is a fungal infection of the feet that can cause the skin on the feet to become red, itchy, and cracked. The fungus that causes tinea pedis thrives in warm, moist environments, and can be spread through direct contact with an infected person or through contact with contaminated surfaces, such as towels or floors.

Tinea versicolor is a common fungal infection of the skin. The fungus that causes tinea versicolor is a type of yeast that naturally lives on the skin. When the fungus overgrows, it can cause a rash. Tinea versicolor is not contagious.

(Lycopodium clavatum)  The Toothed Clubmoss is a small, evergreen plant that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the Lycopodium genus and the Lycopodiaceae family. The plant grows to be about 10-15 cm (4-6 in) tall and has a creeping, spreading habit. The leaves are simple, oblong-lanceolate in shape, and have serrated margins. The leaves are arranged in whorls of 3-6. The plant is dioecious, meaning that there are male and female plants. The male plants produce cones that are about 2 cm (0.8 in) long, while the female plants produce cones that are about 1 cm (0.4 in) long. The cones contain the plant's spores. The plant reproduces via spores.

Tormentil is a small, herbaceous perennial plant that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the rose family (Rosaceae) and is closely related to other members of the genus Potentilla, such as cinquefoil and silverweed. The plant typically grows to 10-30 cm (4-12 in) in height and has a basal rosette of deeply-divided, dark green leaves. Small, yellow flowers bloom in summer and are followed by dark red fruits.  Tormentil is commonly found in damp, grassy habitats such as meadows, pastures, and roadside ditches. It is a hardy plant that can tolerate poor soil and drought conditions. The roots of tormentil are used medicinally for a variety of purposes, including the treatment of diarrhea, stomach upset, and wounds.

Torsades de pointes is a type of ventricular tachycardia that is characterized by a rapid heart rate and a wide QRS complex on an electrocardiogram. The QRS complex is the portion of the electrocardiogram that represents the ventricular depolarization. Torsades de pointes can be a life-threatening condition if it is not treated promptly.

Toxin-induced liver damage is a condition that can occur when the liver is exposed to certain toxins. These toxins can come from the environment, certain medications, or even some foods. The liver is responsible for filtering these toxins out of the body, but if it is overloaded, the toxins can build up and cause damage. Symptoms of toxin-induced liver damage can include fatigue, nausea, vomiting, and jaundice. If the damage is severe, it can lead to liver failure.

Tpn-Associated Hepatic Steatosis is a condition where there is an accumulation of fat in the liver. This can be caused by a number of factors, including certain medications, obesity, and alcohol abuse. Symptoms of this condition can include fatigue, weight loss, and abdominal pain. In severe cases, it can lead to liver failure.

Tracheostomy care is the process of caring for a person with a tracheostomy, which is a surgical opening in the neck that leads to the trachea (windpipe). This opening allows a person to breathe without the use of their nose or mouth.

Trachoma is a chronic infectious disease of the eye that can lead to blindness. It is caused by the bacterium Chlamydia trachomatis and is spread through contact with infected eye secretions or flies. The disease is most common in areas with poor sanitation and lack of clean water.

Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) is a system of medicine that has been used for over 2,000 years in China. It is based on the belief that the human body is a system of energy channels and that illness is caused by imbalances in these channels. TCM practitioners use a variety of techniques to restore balance, including acupuncture, herbal medicine, and massage.

Tragacanth is a plant that is native to the Mediterranean region. It is a member of the legume family and its scientific name is Astragalus gummifer. The plant is a shrub that can grow to be about four feet tall. The leaves of the plant are green and the flowers are white. The plant produces a gum that is used in a variety of products.

Trager Therapy is a type of bodywork that uses gentle, rhythmic movements and deep, relaxing stretches to release tension and improve flexibility. The therapist may also use light touch and massage to help the client relax.

The Trailing Arbutus plant is a small, evergreen shrub that is native to North America. It has small, white flowers that bloom in the spring and summer. The leaves are dark green and glossy. The plant grows to be about 2 feet tall and 3 feet wide.

Trans fat is a type of unsaturated fat that occurs when liquid fat is made into a solid fat, such as margarine or shortening. Trans fat is created during the process of hydrogenation, which adds hydrogen atoms to the fat molecules. This makes the fat more solid and less likely to spoil. Trans fat is found in many processed foods, such as crackers, cookies, and fried foods.

Transcutaneous electrical acustimulation (TEA) is a form of electrical stimulation that is applied to the skin. The electrical stimulation is thought to stimulate the nervous system and produce a variety of therapeutic effects.

A Transjugular Intrahepatic Portosystemic Shunt (TIPSS) is a procedure to place a shunt (tube) between the hepatic vein and the portal vein. This is done to relieve portal hypertension (high blood pressure in the portal vein).

A transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP) is a surgical procedure to remove parts of the prostate gland. The prostate is a small, walnut-shaped gland that is part of the male reproductive system. It is located just below the bladder and in front of the rectum. The prostate gland produces a fluid that is a part of semen.  The most common reason for a TURP is an enlarged prostate gland. This condition is also called benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH). An enlarged prostate gland can cause urinary problems, such as a weak stream, hesitancy, dribbling, and urgency. A TURP can relieve these urinary problems.
A TBI is a type of brain injury that occurs when an external force causes damage to the brain. TBI can result in a wide range of cognitive, physical, and emotional symptoms.

Traumatic oral ulcers are open sores that can occur in the mouth as a result of trauma, such as from biting the inside of the cheek or lip. These ulcers can be painful and may make it difficult to eat or drink.

This plant is a member of the clematis family and is native to Europe. It is a climbing vine that can grow up to 30 feet in length. The leaves are large and have a toothed margin. The flowers are small and white, and they bloom in the summer.
This is a condition where a person experiences loose, watery stools and abdominal cramps. It is often caused by consuming contaminated food or water.

A tree of heaven is a fast-growing tree that can reach up to 30 meters in height. It has dark green, pinnate leaves and small, greenish-white flowers. The tree is native to China and was introduced to North America in the 18th century.

Tree tobacco is a plant in the nightshade family that is native to South America. It can grow to be over 10 feet tall and has large, oval-shaped leaves. The flowers are white or pale pink and the fruit is a small, greenish-yellow berry.
Tree turmeric is a plant in the ginger family that is native to India. The plant has yellow flowers and a rhizome that is used as a spice.
Trendione is a synthetic anabolic steroid that is similar to testosterone. It is used to promote muscle growth and to increase strength and endurance.

Tribulus terrestris is a flowering plant in the family Zygophyllaceae, native to warm temperate and tropical regions of the Old World in southern Europe, southern Asia, throughout Africa, and in northern Australia. It can grow up to 0.5 m in height, with deeply lobed leaves and yellow flowers. The fruit is a small, hard, spiny capsule containing two seeds.  This plant has many traditional uses, including as a diuretic, tonic, and aphrodisiac. It is also used in traditional Chinese medicine.

Trichomoniasis is a sexually transmitted infection that is caused by a parasite. The parasite is called Trichomonas vaginalis and it infects the vagina, urethra, and bladder. Symptoms of trichomoniasis include itching, burning, and pain in the genitals. The infection can also cause pain during urination and sex. Trichomoniasis is treated with antibiotics.

Trichopus zeylanicus is a small, herbaceous plant that is native to Sri Lanka. It grows to a height of 30 cm and has oblong, toothed leaves. The flowers are white or pale pink and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, fleshy berry.
Trichotillomania is a mental health condition that causes people to pull out their hair.
Trichotillomania (Hair Pulling) is a condition where a person has an irresistible urge to pull out their hair, resulting in baldness.

Trigger point therapy is a type of massage that focuses on specific areas of the body that are known to cause pain. These areas are called trigger points, and they can be found in the muscles, tendons, and ligaments. Trigger point therapy is designed to relieve the pain that is associated with these trigger points.
Trismus is a condition where the muscles in the jaw area are tight and stiff, making it difficult to open the mouth.

Tronadora is a plant that is native to the tropical regions of South America. It is a member of the Solanaceae family, which includes other plants such as tomatoes, potatoes, and peppers. The plant is also known by its scientific name, Solanum tronadora.  Tronadora is a perennial plant that can grow to be about 6 feet tall. It has large, dark green leaves that are arranged in a spiral pattern on the stem. The leaves are covered in small, sharp spines. The plant produces small, white flowers that bloom in the summer. The flowers are followed by small, green fruits that turn red when they mature.  Tronadora is typically grown in home gardens and is used as a culinary herb. The leaves and fruits of the plant are used in a variety of dishes, including soups, stews, and sauces. Tronadora can also be used to make a tea.
Trypsin is a proteolytic enzyme that is produced in the pancreas and is responsible for the breakdown of proteins in the digestive system.

Tuberculosis (TB) is a disease caused by bacteria that most often affect the lungs. It can also affect other parts of the body, such as the brain, kidneys, and spine. TB is spread through the air from person to person. Most people who get TB don’t have any symptoms and can’t spread the disease. But some people with TB infection become sick with TB disease.

Tuberous sclerosis complex (TSC) is a rare, multi-system genetic disease that causes non-malignant tumors to grow in the brain and on other vital organs such as the kidneys, heart, lungs, and skin. The tumors are typically benign, but can become malignant. TSC can also cause developmental delays, intellectual disability, and epilepsy. There is no cure for TSC, but treatments are available to help manage the symptoms.
Tung oil is a drying oil derived from the seeds of the tung tree. It is used as a finish for wood and stone and as a lubricant and waterproofing agent.

Tungiasis is a parasitic skin disease caused by the penetration of the female sand flea (Tunga penetrans) into the skin. The sand flea burrows into the skin, causing intense itching and irritation. In severe cases, the sand flea can cause secondary bacterial infections, which can lead to serious health complications.

Tungsten is a chemical element with the symbol W and atomic number 74. The name tungsten comes from the former Swedish name for the tungstate mineral scheelite, tungsten meaning "heavy stone". Tungsten is a rare metal found naturally on Earth almost exclusively in chemical compounds. It was identified as a new element in 1781 and first isolated as a metal in 1783. Its important ores include wolframite and scheelite. The free element is remarkable for its robustness, especially the fact that it has the highest melting point of all the elements.
Turkey corn is a type of corn that is typically used for decoration or as feed for animals.

Turkey tail mushrooms are a type of medicinal mushroom that has been used for centuries in traditional Chinese medicine. Turkey tail mushrooms are rich in polysaccharides and other compounds that have been shown to have immune-boosting, anti-inflammatory, and anti-cancer properties.
Turner Syndrome is a health condition that affects females. It is caused by a missing or incomplete X chromosome. Symptoms may include short stature, webbed neck, low hairline, and low-set ears.
Turpentine oil is a volatile oil that is distilled from the resin of certain pine trees. It is used as a solvent and as a source of materials for the production of other chemicals.

This Turtlehead plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are white or pink, borne in clusters at the ends of the stems. The plant blooms from mid-summer to early fall.

Tylophora is a genus of flowering plants in the family Apocynaceae. The genus is native to tropical and subtropical regions of Asia, Africa, and Australia. Plants in the genus Tylophora are herbs, shrubs, or climbers. They have opposite or whorled leaves and produce small, white or green flowers. The fruit is a follicle or a drupe.  Tylophora plants are used in traditional medicine for the treatment of various ailments, including asthma, bronchitis, and diarrhea. The plants contain various alkaloids, including tylophorine, which is thought to be responsible for the medicinal properties.
Type 1 diabetes is a chronic health condition in which the body is unable to produce insulin, a hormone that is necessary for the body to process sugar.

Type 2 diabetes is a chronic condition that affects the way your body metabolizes sugar. It is characterized by high levels of sugar in the blood. Type 2 diabetes can be caused by a number of factors, including genetics, lifestyle, and weight. The condition can be controlled with medication, diet, and exercise.
Tyrosinemia is a rare, inherited disorder that prevents the body from breaking down the amino acid tyrosine. Tyrosinemia can lead to liver and kidney damage, and can be fatal if left untreated.
Ultraprocessed food is defined as any food that has been processed beyond its natural state, including adding preservatives, artificial flavors, and colors.

extract  This is an extract of the plant Umckaloabo, which is native to South Africa. It is a perennial herb that grows to a height of 1-2 m. The leaves are opposite, oblong-lanceolate, and have a toothed margin. The flowers are white or pale pink, and borne in clusters. The fruit is a capsule, containing small, black seeds.

Unani medicine is a form of traditional medicine that is practiced in India and other parts of South Asia. It is based on the belief that the human body is made up of four elements: air, water, fire, and earth.
Unsaturated fat is a type of fat that contains one or more double bonds in its hydrocarbon chain. This makes the fat molecules less stable and more prone to oxidation.

Unstable angina is a type of chest pain that occurs when the blood supply to the heart muscle is reduced. The pain is usually severe and may be accompanied by shortness of breath, sweating, and nausea.

The common cold is a viral infection of your upper respiratory tract, which includes your nose, throat, sinuses, and eustachian tubes. A cold is usually caused by one of several viruses, with rhinoviruses being the most common.

Uranium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol U and atomic number 92. It is a silvery-grey metal in the actinide series of the periodic table. A uranium atom has 92 protons and 92 electrons, of which 6 are valence electrons.

Uremic pruritus is a condition characterized by itching of the skin. It is a symptom of kidney failure and can be very severe. Treatment typically involves managing the underlying kidney failure and using medications to relieve the itching.

Urethral syndrome is a condition that can cause pain in the urethra, the tube that carries urine from the bladder out of the body. The pain may be worse when urinating or during sexual activity. There may also be a burning sensation or a feeling of needing to urinate more often.

Urinary incontinence is a health condition in which a person experiences involuntary leakage of urine. This can happen when the person coughs, laughs, or sneezes. It can also happen when the person is exerting themselves physically.

Urinary retention is a condition in which a person is unable to empty their bladder. This can be a temporary or chronic condition. Symptoms may include an inability to urinate, pain in the abdomen or pelvis, and an inability to empty the bladder completely.

A urinary tract infection (UTI) is an infection that affects any part of the urinary tract. The urinary tract includes the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra. A UTI can occur in both men and women.
A urinary tract infection (UTI) is an infection that affects any part of the urinary tract, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, or urethra.
A urine drug test is a test that measures the levels of certain drugs in a person's urine.
Urine therapy is the use of urine for medicinal purposes. It may be taken internally or applied externally.
Urticaria is a condition that causes the skin to break out in hives and can be accompanied by itching, swelling, and redness.
Usnea is a type of lichen that grows on trees. It is long and stringy, and often has a greenish-gray color.

Uterine fibroids are non-cancerous growths of the uterus that often occur during a woman's childbearing years. Symptoms can include heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding, pelvic pain or pressure, and difficulty urinating. While most fibroids are small and cause no problems, some can grow to be very large and cause severe symptoms. Treatment options include medication, surgery, and, in some cases, no treatment at all.

Uva Ursi is a small, evergreen shrub that grows in the mountainous regions of Europe, Asia, and North America. The leaves of the plant are used to make medicine.  Uva Ursi is used for urinary tract infections (UTIs), including cystitis, urethritis, and nephritis. It is also used for kidney stones and other kidney disorders. Some people use it as a diuretic to increase urine flow and as an astringent to reduce inflammation.  Uva Ursi is sometimes applied directly to the skin for skin conditions such as eczema and psoriasis.

Uveitis is a condition that results in inflammation of the uvea, which is the middle layer of the eye. The uvea consists of the iris, ciliary body, and choroid. Uveitis can cause pain, redness, and blurred vision.
The Uzara plant is a small, herbaceous plant that is native to Africa. It has small, white flowers and is used in traditional medicine for a variety of purposes.

Vaginal candidiasis is a health condition that results when there is an overgrowth of the Candida albicans fungus in the vagina. This overgrowth can cause symptoms such as itching, burning, and discharge. Candidiasis is usually treated with antifungal medications.

Vaginitis is an inflammation of the vagina that can be caused by several different things, including infections, allergies, and irritants. The most common symptom of vaginitis is itching, but other symptoms may include burning, redness, and discharge.

Valproic acid-induced toxicities are a group of conditions that can occur when someone takes too much of the medication valproic acid. These toxicities can range from mild to life-threatening, and can include problems such as liver damage, pancreatitis, and bleeding.

Vanadium is a chemical element with the symbol V and atomic number 23. It is a hard, silvery-grey, ductile, and malleable transition metal. The elemental metal is rarely found in nature, but once isolated artificially, the formation of an oxide layer (passivation) stabilizes the free metal somewhat against further oxidation.

Vanadium is a mineral that is found in many foods. It is also available as a dietary supplement. Vanadium is needed for the proper growth and development of bones, teeth, and muscles. It also helps the body to use carbohydrates and fats. Vanadium deficiency is rare.
Varicose veins are enlarged, twisted veins that are often found on the legs. They can cause pain, swelling, and cramping.
Vascular dementia is a type of dementia that occurs when there is damage to the brain's blood vessels. This can lead to problems with thinking, memory, and movement.
Vasospastic angina is a type of angina (chest pain) that occurs when the arteries that supply blood to the heart muscle spasm. This can reduce or block the flow of blood to the heart muscle.
A vegan diet is a type of vegetarian diet that excludes all animal products, including eggs, dairy, and honey.
Vegetable oils are oils that are extracted from plants.
A vegetable is a plant or part of a plant that is eaten as food.
A vegetarian diet is a diet that does not include meat, poultry, or fish.

Venous insufficiency is a condition in which the veins have difficulty returning blood from the legs to the heart. This can cause the legs to feel tired, achy, and heavy. It can also lead to more serious problems such as ulcers.
A venous leg ulcer is a sore on the leg that does not heal within two weeks, and is usually caused by poor circulation.

A blood clot that forms in a vein is called a venous thromboembolism (VTE). A VTE can be dangerous because it can break off and travel to your lungs, blocking blood flow (pulmonary embolism). A VTE can also cause long-term damage to your veins.

A venous thromboembolism (VTE) is a blood clot that forms in a vein, usually in the leg. It can cause pain, swelling, and redness. If the clot breaks loose, it can travel to the lungs and block blood flow. This can cause chest pain, shortness of breath, and even death.

Ventilator-Associated Pneumonia (VAP) is a type of pneumonia that occurs in people who are on mechanical ventilation. VAP is a serious complication that can occur in people who are on mechanical ventilation, and can lead to death.
Ventilator-Associated Pneumonia (VAP) is a serious lung infection that can occur in people who are on mechanical ventilation (breathing machine). VAP is a leading cause of death in hospitals.

Ventricular arrhythmias are a type of heart rhythm disorder that affects the lower chambers of the heart (the ventricles). The ventricles are the heart's pumping chambers, and they work with the atria (the heart's upper chambers) to pump blood through the heart and out to the rest of the body. In people with ventricular arrhythmias, the ventricles beat too fast, too slow, or irregularly. This can cause the heart to pump less effectively, and it can lead to symptoms like chest pain, shortness of breath, and dizziness. Ventricular arrhythmias can be serious, and they can sometimes lead to sudden cardiac death.

This Verbena plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to 2 feet tall. The leaves are opposite, oblong, and have toothed margins. The flowers are small, white, and borne in clusters. The plant blooms from June to September.
This Veronica plant has small, blue flowers and glossy green leaves. It is a low-growing plant that spreads quickly, making it ideal for groundcover.
Vesicoureteral reflux (VUR) is a condition in which urine flows backward from the bladder into the ureters. The ureters are the tubes that carry urine from the kidneys to the bladder.

Vestibulopathy is a disorder of the vestibular system, which is responsible for balance and eye movement. Symptoms include dizziness, vertigo, and problems with balance. Treatment depends on the underlying cause and may involve vestibular rehabilitation, medications, or surgery.

Vetiver is a perennial grass that is native to India. It is a hardy plant that can grow up to 10 feet tall. The leaves are long and narrow, and the flowers are small and white. The roots of the plant are very strong and can grow up to 6 feet long. Vetiver is often used in Ayurvedic medicine, and it is also used to make perfumes and incense.

This plant is a member of the mint family and is native to Vietnam. It has a strong, pungent flavor and is often used in Vietnamese cuisine. The leaves are used fresh or dried, and the plant can also be used to make a tea.
Vincristine-Induced Neuropathy is a condition caused by the chemotherapy drug vincristine. This drug can damage the nerves, causing pain, numbness, tingling, and weakness.
Vinegar is a sour liquid that is made by fermenting alcohol.
Vinpocetine is a synthetic compound derived from the alkaloid vincamine. It is used as a drug in the treatment of Alzheimer's disease and other cognitive disorders.
Vitamin B12 deficiency is a condition in which there is a lack of vitamin B12 in the body. This can lead to a number of problems including anemia, fatigue, and neurological problems.

Vitamin B6 is a water-soluble vitamin that is part of the vitamin B complex. It is involved in many biochemical reactions in the body and is essential for good health. A vitamin B6 deficiency can cause a wide range of health problems.

Vitamin K-Dependent Clotting Factors Deficiency (VKCFD) is a rare bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors. People with VKCFD may bleed excessively from minor cuts or bruises, and may have prolonged bleeding after surgery or dental procedures. VKCFD is usually diagnosed in infancy or early childhood.

Vitiligo is a health condition in which the skin loses its pigment. The affected areas of skin can be any color, but they are usually white. Vitiligo usually starts as small patches of white skin. The patches can spread and get larger. They can also join together and cover large areas of the body.

Vocal cord dysfunction (VCD) is a condition that causes your vocal cords to close when you breathe in. This can make it hard to breathe and can also cause you to make a high-pitched sound when you breathe out.
Volatile oils are oils that evaporate easily at room temperature.
The Volumetrics Diet is a weight-loss plan that emphasizes eating more foods that are low in energy density and high in water and fiber content.

Vulvar pain is a condition in which a woman experiences pain in her vulva, the external female genital area. The pain may be constant or intermittent, and can vary in intensity. It may be felt as burning, stinging, itching, or throbbing. Vulvar pain may be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, skin disorders, and nerve disorders. Treatment for vulvar pain often includes a combination of medical and self-care measures.

Vulvovaginal candidiasis (VVC) is a type of yeast infection that affects the vagina and vulva. The most common symptom of VVC is itching, which may be severe. Other symptoms include burning, redness, and swelling of the vulva; burning, redness, and irritation of the vagina; and a thick, white, cottage cheese-like discharge.
The definition of wahoo is "an exclamation of triumph, joy, or excitement."
This Wallflower plant is a beautiful, fragrant, and easy to grow flower. It blooms in the spring and summer, and is a great addition to any garden.

Warfarin-induced hair loss is a condition in which hair loss occurs as a side effect of taking the medication warfarin. Warfarin is a blood thinner that is used to treat conditions such as heart disease and stroke. While warfarin is effective at treating these conditions, it can also cause a number of side effects, including hair loss. In most cases, warfarin-induced hair loss is temporary and will resolve once the medication is stopped. However, in some cases, the hair loss may be permanent.

The water avens is a perennial herb that grows in damp areas. The plant has a reddish-brown stem and leaves that are deeply lobed and toothed. The flowers are small and white, and they grow in clusters. The water avens is native to Europe and Asia, but it can also be found in North America.

The Water Dock plant is a perennial herb that grows in wet areas. The plant has large, dark green leaves and produces small, white flowers. The plant is native to Europe and Asia and is often used as an ornamental plant in gardens.
Water Germander is a perennial herb that grows in wet areas. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are small and white.

Water hemlock is a perennial herb that grows in wet areas. The plant has a large, white taproot and large, compound leaves. The flowers are small, white, and borne in umbrella-like clusters. The fruit is a small, black, spherical drupe.

Water warts are small, flesh-colored growths that commonly appear on the hands and feet. They are caused by a virus and are contagious. Water warts are not cancerous and do not cause any health problems.
Watercress is a leafy, green plant that grows in water. It has a peppery flavor and is often used in salads or as a garnish.
Watermelon juice is a type of juice made from watermelons.

The Weight Watchers Diet is a diet plan that emphasizes eating healthy foods and exercising regularly. The diet plan is based on a points system, which assigns points to different foods based on their calorie content, fat content, and fiber content.
WKS is a condition that affects the nervous system and can cause problems with muscle coordination, vision, and memory. It is caused by a deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B1).
The Western diet is a diet that is typically high in red and processed meats, refined grains, added sugars, and unhealthy fats.
Western herbal medicine is a system of medicine that uses plants and plant extracts to treat a wide variety of conditions.
The definition of wheatgrass is a grass that is used as a cereal grain, as a forage crop, or as a soil-building cover crop.

Lamium album, commonly known as white dead-nettle, is a herbaceous flowering plant in the family Lamiaceae. It is native to Europe and Asia, but has also been introduced to North America. It is a perennial plant that typically grows to 10–50 cm (4–20 in) tall. The leaves are opposite, ovate to lanceolate, 2–8 cm (0.8–3.1 in) long and 1–3 cm (0.4–1.2 in) broad, with a toothed margin. The flowers are produced in whorls of three to five in the leaf axils, each flower 2–3 cm (0.8–1.2 in) long, with a tubular white corolla with a yellow or purple throat.

This white hellebore plant is a perennial herb that blooms in the spring. The flowers are white and have a bell-shaped structure. The plant is native to Europe and Asia and has been introduced to North America.

White horehound is a perennial herb that is native to Europe and Asia. It has been introduced to North America, where it is now found in the eastern and central United States. The plant grows to a height of 30 cm (12 in). The leaves are opposite, ovate to lanceolate in shape, and have toothed margins. The flowers are white and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, black, four-lobed capsule.  White horehound has a long history of use in herbal medicine. It was used to treat a variety of ailments, including colds, coughs, and digestive problems. The plant is still used today in cough syrups and lozenges.

The White Lily is a beautiful plant that is native to North America. It has large, white flowers that bloom in the summer and early fall. The plant grows to be about 3 feet tall and has dark green leaves.

The White Mulberry is a deciduous tree that can grow up to 50 feet tall. The leaves are alternate, simple, and oblong with serrated margins. The flowers are small, greenish-white, and borne in clusters. The fruit is a small, blackberry-like drupe.

White Oak is a type of oak tree that has white bark and leaves.

This White Pepper plant is a perennial vine that produces small, white berries. The berries are dried and used as a spice. White pepper is used to add flavor to food, and it is also used as a medicinal herb.
The definition of White Sandalwood is a type of wood that is often used in making furniture. It is a hardwood that is very strong and durable.
This plant is a member of the carrot family and has a white, five-petaled flower. The stem is hairy and the leaves are deeply lobed. The plant can grow to be about two feet tall.

The Wild Cherry tree is a deciduous tree that can grow up to 50 feet tall. The tree has a smooth, gray bark and its leaves are dark green and glossy. The wild daisy is a perennial plant that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are lance-shaped and the flowers are white with yellow centers. The plant blooms in the spring and summer.

Baptisia australis, commonly known as blue wild indigo, is a herbaceous perennial plant in the legume family, Fabaceae. It is native to the eastern United States and Canada. The plant grows up to 1.5 m tall, with trifoliate leaves and blue-violet flowers. The flowers are pollinated by bees, and the seeds are dispersed by ants.

(Lactuca virosa)  The Wild Lettuce plant is a member of the Asteraceae family and is native to Europe, North Africa, and Asia. It is a biennial herb that grows to a height of 2-3 feet and has a rosette of large, lobed leaves. The plant produces small, yellow flowers that bloom in the summer. The leaves of the Wild Lettuce plant are used to make a tea that has sedative and analgesic properties.

This Wild Mint plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2-3 feet tall. The leaves are opposite, ovate to lanceolate in shape, and have a toothed margin. The flowers are white and borne in terminal spikes. The plant blooms from June to August.
This plant is a member of the mint family and has a strong, thyme-like flavor. The leaves are used fresh or dried in a variety of dishes.
Willard water is a type of water that has been treated with a special process that makes it more alkaline.
Wilson Disease is a rare inherited disorder that prevents the body from getting rid of extra copper. The build-up of copper damages the liver, brain, and other organs.
Wine is an alcoholic beverage made from fermented grapes.

Winter cherry is a small, woody shrub that produces small, white flowers in the spring. The flowers are followed by small, red berries in the fall. The berries are edible and have a sweet, tart flavor. Winter cherry is native to Europe and Asia and has been introduced to North America.

Winter savory is a perennial herb that is native to the Mediterranean region. It has a strong, pungent flavor that is similar to thyme. Winter savory is often used to flavor meats, soups, and stews. It is also used as a garnish or to make a savory tea.

Wintergreen is a small, evergreen shrub that typically grows to only 6-12 inches (15-30 cm) tall. The leaves are dark green and glossy, with a white underside. The flowers are small and white, blooming in late spring or early summer. The fruit is a small, black berry. Wintergreen is native to North America, where it is found in woods and forests.

Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the immune system and causes problems with bleeding. The disorder is caused by a mutation in the WAS gene. People with Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome are more likely to develop infections, easy bruising, and bleeding.

The Witch Hazel plant is a shrub that can grow to be about 15 feet tall. It has oval-shaped leaves that are about 3-5 inches long and 2-3 inches wide. The leaves are green in the summer and turn yellow, orange, or red in the fall. The plant has small, yellow flowers that bloom in the fall. The Witch Hazel plant is native to North America and can be found in woods and forests.

The wood anemone is a small, delicate flower that blooms in early spring. It has white petals and a yellow center, and its leaves are deeply lobed and have a toothed margin. The wood anemone is found in woods and shady areas, and it prefers moist, well-drained soil.

Wood Sage is a perennial herb that grows to about 2 feet tall. The leaves are opposite, ovate to lanceolate, and have toothed margins. The flowers are small, white, and borne in terminal clusters. The fruit is a small, black drupe. Wood Sage is native to Europe and Asia, but has been introduced to North America.

The wood sorrel plant is a small, herbaceous plant that is native to Europe and Asia. It is a member of the buckwheat family and has small, heart-shaped leaves. The plant produces small, white flowers that have five petals. The flowers are borne in clusters and bloom from May to July. The wood sorrel plant is a low-growing plant and typically reaches a height of 10-15 cm (4-6 in).

This Wormwood plant is a perennial herb that can grow up to four feet tall. The leaves are dark green and lance-shaped with serrated edges. The plant produces small, yellow flowers in summer. Wormwood is native to Europe and Asia and has been introduced to North America. The plant is considered an invasive species in some areas.

This Xanthoparmelia plant is a yellow-green alga that grows on rocks in the intertidal zone. It has a holdfast that anchors it to the substrate, and a thallus that is flat and strap-like. The thallus is covered in small, rounded, yellow-green cells. The plant reproduces by releasing spores into the water.
Xenon is a chemical element with the symbol Xe and atomic number 54. It is a colorless, odorless, tasteless noble gas found in the Earth's atmosphere in trace amounts.
Xerosis is a dry skin condition that can be caused by a number of factors, including weather, dehydration, and certain skin disorders. Symptoms of xerosis include itching, redness, and flaking.
Xylitol is a sugar alcohol that is used as a sweetener. It is found in a variety of plants, including birch trees.
This yarrow plant has fine, feathery leaves and small white flowers. It is a member of the Asteraceae family and is native to Europe and Asia.

Yellow dock is a perennial herb in the buckwheat family. The plant is native to Europe and Asia, and has been introduced to North America. It grows up to 1.5 m (5 ft) tall, with a rosette of leaves at the base and alternate leaves on the stem. The leaves are oblong to lanceolate, 10–30 cm (4–12 in) long and 2–8 cm (1–3 in) wide, with toothed margins. The flowers are small, greenish-yellow, and borne in clusters. The fruit is a brown achene.  Yellow dock is often found in disturbed habitats, such as roadsides and fields. It is considered a weed in many parts of the world. The plant is used as a food and herbal medicine. The roots and leaves are used to make a tea that is taken internally for a variety of conditions, including constipation, diarrhea, and liver problems. The tea can also be applied externally for skin conditions such as eczema and psoriasis.

(Lysimachia punctata)  This plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 2-3 feet tall. The leaves are lanceolate to ovate in shape and are arranged in opposite pairs along the stem. The flowers are yellow and borne in clusters at the ends of the stems. The fruit is a small capsule.

(Linaria vulgaris)  This plant is a herbaceous perennial that is native to Europe and Asia. It has been introduced to North America, where it is now considered an invasive species. The plant grows to a height of 30-100 cm (12-40 in). The leaves are lanceolate to oblong-lanceolate in shape and are 5-15 cm (2-6 in) long. The flowers are yellow, 2-3 cm (0.8-1.2 in) long, and are borne in racemes. The fruit is a capsule that contains numerous small seeds.

The Yerba Mansa plant is a perennial herb that is native to North America. It is a member of the mint family and has a strong minty smell. The leaves are green and have a serrated edge. The flowers are white and have a yellow center. The plant blooms in the summer.

(Eriodictyon californicum)  The Yerba Santa plant is a perennial shrub that is native to California. It grows to a height of 3-6 feet and has dark green leaves that are 3-5 inches long and 2-3 inches wide. The flowers are white or pale pink and bloom in the spring. The fruit is a small, dark blue berry that ripens in the summer.
A yew is a type of evergreen tree that is native to Europe, Asia, and North America.

This Yin Chen plant is a perennial herb that grows to about 1 meter in height. It has dark green, lance-shaped leaves and small white flowers. The plant is native to China and is used in traditional Chinese medicine.
Ylang ylang oil is an essential oil derived from the flowers of the ylang ylang tree. It has a sweet, floral scent and is used in perfumes, cosmetics, and soaps.
Yogurts are a type of fermented milk product that is made by adding bacteria to milk. The bacteria culture the milk and turn it into yogurt.

Ytterbium is a chemical element with the symbol Yb and atomic number 70. It is the second-most abundant element in the lanthanide series, after lanthanum. Ytterbium is a soft, silvery-white metal in the lanthanide series of the periodic table.

Yttrium is a chemical element with the symbol Y and atomic number 39. It is a silvery-metallic transition metal chemically similar to the lanthanides and has often been classified as a "rare-earth element". Yttrium is almost always found in combination with lanthanide elements in rare-earth minerals, and is never found in nature as a free element.

The Yucca plant is a perennial shrub that can grow up to 15 feet tall. It has long, stiff leaves that are green or blue-green in color. The flowers are white or cream-colored and grow in clusters at the top of the plant. Yucca plants are native to the southwestern United States and Mexico.

Zero Balancing is a hands-on bodywork therapy that uses the fulcrums created by bones to help release tension deep in the body. It is based on the idea that the body is a self-regulating system and that when the bones are in alignment, the body can heal itself.

Zirconium is a chemical element with the symbol Zr and atomic number 40. It is a lustrous, gray-white, strong transition metal that resembles hafnium and, to a lesser extent, titanium. Zirconium is mainly used as a refractory and opacifier, although small amounts are used as an alloying agent for its strong resistance to corrosion.

This Zizyphus plant is a small, deciduous shrub that typically grows to 6-9 feet tall and wide. It has dark green, glossy leaves and small, white flowers that bloom in the summer. The fruit is a small, red berry that ripens in the fall.

Adenoside is a nucleoside that is composed of adenine and ribose.

An allergy is a hypersensitivity reaction by the immune system to a foreign substance, such as pollen, that does not ordinarily cause a reaction in most people.

There is no one definition of alternative medicine, as it is a broad category that includes a range of practices. Atherosclerosis is a health condition that is characterized by the buildup of plaque in the arteries. This plaque can narrow the arteries and make it difficult for blood to flow through them. Atherosclerosis can lead to heart disease, stroke, and other serious health problems.

Boredom is a feeling of apathy or dissatisfaction that comes from having nothing to do.

Central Asia is a region located in the northern and eastern hemispheres. It is bordered by Russia to the north, China to the east, Afghanistan to the south, and Iran and Turkey to the west. The Caspian Sea lies to the southwest.
The central nervous system is the control center for the body. It consists of the brain and the spinal cord.
The cerebral cortex is the outer layer of the brain that is responsible for higher brain functions such as thought, memory, and language.
A chemical compound is a substance formed when two or more chemical elements are combined in fixed proportions.

The development of inflammation is the body's response to injury or irritation. The inflammatory response is a complex process that involves the release of various chemicals and other substances that help to protect the body from further damage.
A dietary pattern is a combination of foods that are eaten together regularly.

Dietary reference values (DRVs) are a set of guidelines for the general public that are used to promote healthy eating habits. The DRVs are based on the latest scientific evidence and provide recommendations for energy, macronutrients (fat, protein, and carbohydrates), and micronutrients (vitamins and minerals).

Dystonia is a neurological movement disorder that is characterized by involuntary muscle contractions and abnormal postures. The disorder can be caused by genetic factors, brain injury, or certain medications. Symptoms of dystonia can vary from mild to severe, and may include muscle spasms, cramping, and tremors. There is no cure for dystonia, but treatments are available to help manage the symptoms.
The electrical system of the heart is the system that controls the heart's electrical impulses. This system includes the heart's pacemaker, the sinoatrial node, and the atrioventricular node.

Endocrine glands are glands that secrete hormones into the bloodstream.
The endometrium is the innermost layer of the uterus. It is a thin layer of tissue that is shed during menstruation.
An enzyme is a protein that catalyzes a chemical reaction.

Essential tremor is a neurological condition that causes a person's hands, head, trunk, voice, or legs to shake uncontrollably. The tremor is often worse when the person is under stress or when they are trying to do something with their hands. Europa is one of the Galilean moons of Jupiter, and is the sixth-closest moon to the planet. Its diameter is 3,122 km, making it the fourth-largest moon of Jupiter.

The definition of Fear of gaining weight is the anxiety that one will gain weight. This can be a result of a number of factors, including a fear of becoming overweight or obese, a fear of losing control, or a fear of not being able to stop eating.

Fluid retention is the accumulation of fluid in the body. This can happen in the tissues, in the blood vessels, or in body cavities.

Hydroxycitric acid is a compound found in the fruit of the Garcinia cambogia plant. HCA has been shown to boost weight loss and decrease body fat.

headaches can be caused by a variety of factors. However, generally speaking, a headache is a pain or discomfort that is felt in the head, neck, or face. Headaches can be caused by a number of things, including stress, tension, allergies, eyestrain, sinus infections, and migraines.
The definition of heart health is the state of being free from cardiovascular disease.

Heat stroke is a condition caused by your body overheating, usually as a result of prolonged exposure to or physical exertion in high temperatures. This most serious form of heat injury, heat stroke can occur if your body temperature rises to 104°F (40°C) or higher.
A herb is a plant that is used for its flavor, scent, or medicinal properties.
Histamine is a molecule that is released by immune cells during an allergic reaction. It is also a neurotransmitter, and it plays a role in the inflammatory response.

A human being is a member of the species Homo sapiens, which means "wise man" in Latin. The term "human" is also used to refer to all members of the human family, which includes Homo sapiens, Neanderthals, and other extinct species of hominids.

The human body is the entire structure of a human being. It is composed of many different types of cells that together create tissues and subsequently organ systems. They ensure homeostasis and the viability of the human body.
Hypnotic drugs are drugs that are used to induce sleep or a state of sleep-like trance.

The immune response is the body's reaction to a foreign substance, such as a virus, bacteria, or toxin. The immune response can be divided into two types: the innate immune response, which is the body's first line of defense against foreign invaders, and the adaptive immune response, which is a more specific and targeted response that is triggered by the body's exposure to a foreign invader.

Some people might say that improved digestion is when the digestive process is more efficient, and food is broken down and absorbed more effectively. Others might say that improved digestion is when there are fewer digestive issues, such as bloating, gas, or constipation.

Kerala is a state located in the southernmost part of India. It is bordered by the states of Karnataka to the north and Tamil Nadu to the east and south, and the Lakshadweep Sea to the west.
Ketalar is a brand name for the drug ketamine. It is a dissociative anesthetic that is used in human and veterinary medicine.

A physiological reaction is a response of the body to a stimulus.

Plant-based food is food that is made from plants and does not contain any animal products.
